<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alexander Attacks Violent Videos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Teacher pension funds should pull their  
investments from companies that make ultra-violent video games to 
erode a ``culture of violence'' that contributed to the Colorado 
school shootings, Republican presidential hopeful Lamar Alexander 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Teachers in this country should be outraged to learn that  
their pension funds are major investors in many of the companies 
that make these ultra-violent video games,'' Alexander, who is a 
former education secretary, said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander argued that the violent games contributed materially  
to the Littleton, Colo., high school shootings, which left 15 dead. 
</P>
<P>
	``Following the Littleton killings, it's been reported that  
hundreds of hours playing these games helped make the teenage 
killers such deadly marksmen,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander purchases airtime on Iowa radio stations each Sunday  
for a weekly broadcast. A script for this week's broadcast, on the 
video game connection, was provided to The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Teacher pension funds in California, Texas, Ohio and Kentucky,  
as well as the College Retirement Equity Fund -- a fund for college 
teachers -- are ``major investors'' in companies that make the 
violent games, Alexander said. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, all five are investors in Cendant Corp., creators  
of ``Phantasmagoria,'' a game that includes a brutal rape scene, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the California and college retirement funds own  
shares in a company called GT Interactive Software, which produces 
``Duke Nukem,'' another violent game, Alexander said. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Goldman of the Texas teacher pension fund said he didn't  
have any comment on Alexander's remarks. ``We'd have to look 
specifically at what he's saying,'' Goldman said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kentucky, the issue was raised by local politicians a few  
months ago, according to Pat Miller of that state's teacher pension 
fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Individual shares of Cendant were sold, although a mutual fund  
in which the Kentucky fund invests holds shares in the company. 
Miller said the sale decision came because the price fell. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd have to sell every media stock we ever thought about'' if  
investors worried about products, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Herb Byer of the Ohio fund said he would have no comment until  
he heard from Alexander personally. There was no immediate response 
to a request for comment from the California fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander said the pension funds aren't small players but own  
millions of shares in the companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It helps create the culture of violence that teachers have to  
deal with every day,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	While dealing an economic blow to violent games won't solve  
school problems, it's a step in the right direction, he argued. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every day as we search for answers one would be to tell the  
makers of these ultra-violent video games to take the violence out 
of the videos or we'll take the investment out of your company,'' 
Alexander argued. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander was education secretary under President Bush is a  
former president of the University of Tennessee. He is seeking to 
improve on his showing in the 1996 race for the Republican 
presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	He is only the latest contender to seek to use the Colorado  
school shootings as a platform to argue for changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no easy way to stop the culture of violence, but as a  
first step we should hit the producers of these violent images in 
the pocketbook,'' Alexander says in his radio spot. ``We can all 
join to make violence unprofitable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While television programming and violence in music and in movies  
have received heavy attention, Alexander said video games are by 
far the worst offenders. He said children spend hours playing games 
that features dismemberments and sexual assaults. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most parent would be shocked to see the games,'' he said.  
``It's 10 times worse than anything on television and the movies. 
They literally reward children playing the games for blowing the 
arms off of policemen. The more gruesome the better.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
