<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Senate OKs Gun Show Limits  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reversing their position on the issue,  
Republicans today pushed through a Senate bill they claimed would 
establish a system of background checks for all buyers of firearms 
at gun shows. Even in advance of the 48-47 vote, President Clinton 
and Senate Democrats cited numerous loopholes, and Republicans 
agreed to consider further changes. But the Senate voted 50-43 to 
kill an amendment by Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., to require Web sites 
selling guns to be federally licensed. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Plunge; Dow Off 225.66  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks plunged today after the government's  
report of a steep rise in consumer prices set off renewed worries 
about inflation and sent bond prices sharply lower. Just before the 
close, the Dow Jones industrial average was at 10,881.53, down 
225.66 -- wiping out a 106.82-point gain yesterday that gave the Dow 
a new closing high of 11,107.19. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 
2,395-696. Broader stock indicators were lower as well. The Nasdaq 
composite index was at 2,519.53, down 62.47. Consumer prices jumped 
in April by an unexpectedly sharp 0.7 percent, the largest monthly 
gain in nearly nine years. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia Claims NATO Hit Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO warplanes bombed a convoy of  
ethnic Albanian refugees, killing 50-100 civilians early today, 
Yugoslav authorities claimed. Reporters were shown a devastated 
scene of charred bodies, wrecked tractors and terrified survivors. 
NATO said it was investigating the claim, while the State 
Department urged skepticism on Serb reports that blamed the allies 
for the attack on the Kosovo village of Korisa until the facts are 
known. Officials at NATO headquarters, speaking on condition of 
anonymity, said there was no immediate indication that allied 
aircraft were involved. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Expresses Regret to Jiang  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, whose calls to Chinese  
President Jiang Zemin had been refused since the U.S. bombing of 
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade last week, got through to the 
Chinese leader today and expressed hope that the two countries 
could repair the damage to their relations. On the 52nd day of 
NATO's air campaign, Defense Secretary William Cohen said U.S. 
troop morale remains high. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Voids EPA Air-Pollution Rules  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal appeals court today set aside new  
air quality standards issued by the Environmental Protection Agency 
in 1997, handing the Clinton administration a major environmental 
defeat. The three-judge panel, acting on a lawsuit by a number of 
industry groups, said the section of the 1990 Clean Air Act on 
which the EPA relied in issuing the air pollution rules amounted to 
``an unconstitutional delegation of legislative power.'' The EPA is 
almost certain to appeal the case, although the agency had no 
immediate comment. 

</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart Rejects Morning-After Pill  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Wal-Mart, the nation's largest  
retailer, said today its pharmacies will not sell an emergency 
``morning-after'' anti-pregnancy pill that can be used up to 72 
hours after unprotected sexual intercourse. Wal-Mart did not say 
why it would not sell the drug at its 2,428 pharmacies, calling the 
ban a ``business decision.'' Family planning advocates criticized 
the move, saying that some women, particularly those in small 
towns, will have greater difficulty finding the drug, Preven. 

</P>
<P>
	Rescued Toddler Home From Hospital  
</P>
<P>
	MULVANE, Kan. (AP) -- A toddler rescued from a well after a  
five-hour ordeal gave his mother ``a smile I won't ever forget'' in 
the emergency room, she said today after she brought her son home. 
Seventeen-month-old Jessy Kraus was released from HCA Wesley 
Medical Center in Wichita hours after his nationally televised 
rescue from the well in his back yard. 

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Prices Jump in April  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer prices jumped in April by an  
unexpectedly sharp 0.7 percent, the largest monthly gain in nearly 
nine years, the Labor Department said today. The news drove down 
stock and bond prices. A record 6.1 percent spike in energy prices, 
including a 15 percent leap in the price of gasoline, led the 
upward swing. However, prices for many other products and services, 
from food and clothing to housing and medical care, also rose. 

</P>
<P>
	Graf, Serena Exit German Open  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- The German Open lost two of its most prominent  
players today -- a hobbling Steffi Graf lost in three sets and 
Serena Williams pulled out because of an arm injury. Top-seeded 
Martina Hingis advanced to the semifinals by defeating Barbara 
Schett 7-5, 7-5. Graf lost to Julie Halard-Decugis of France 5-7, 
6-4, 6-4. Graf developed back pain and needed medical treatment 
during changeovers. Williams quit during her quarterfinal against 
Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
