<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Faking Reporter Denies Having AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OWENSBORO, Ky. (AP) -- First, newspaper reporter Kim Stacy told  
her editors she'd fabricated five columns about her life-and-death 
struggle with cancer to hide the fact she really has AIDS. 
</P>
<P>
	Now she says she has never been diagnosed with AIDS, either.  
</P>
<P>
	In an interview published Friday in the Owensboro  
Messenger-Inquirer, Ms. Stacy, 33, said she began making up stories 
about her health several years ago so she could make friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Stacy was fired on Monday after admitting the first lie,  
about having cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Then on Thursday, Ms. Stacy told the newspaper that to the best  
of her knowledge, she has never had any symptoms of AIDS-related 
illnesses. She said she has never tested positive for AIDS or been 
treated for the disease. 
</P>
<P>
	She agreed to have two reporters accompany her to take an AIDS  
test. The results were not immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past few weeks, Ms. Stacy wrote movingly about how she  
had brain cancer, had only a few months to live and was undergoing 
chemotherapy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I refuse to believe I'm going to die,'' she wrote. ``My life  
may be over in six months, but I'm not going out of this world 
without a fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This week, she met with an editor at a newspaper where she used  
to work, and she admitted that she didn't have cancer. The meeting 
came after suspicions were raised by former co-workers of Ms. 
Stacy's. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Stacy said the deceit began in late 1995 when she told  
co-workers at the Appalachian News-Express in Pikeville that she 
had cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know where the idea came from,'' she told the  
Messenger-Inquirer. ``At the time I was having trouble with my 
blood sugar and going to the doctor a lot, and everybody was real 
nice to me, real concerned. It seemed like to me they really made 
an effort to be friends with me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Stacy joined the Messenger-Inquirer in 1998.  
</P>
<P>
	This week, Ms. Stacy was asked in an interview with The  
Associated Press how readers would know that she was telling the 
truth about having AIDS. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have an answer for you all,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Stacy said she has had stomach problems but attributes them  
to stress. ``Sometimes I have night-sweats, and occasionally I have 
a rash around my neck and on my chest,'' she told the Owensboro 
newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Ms. Stacy's father, Monroe Stacy, told the  
Messenger-Inquirer that she is diabetic. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Stacy was a reporter for the newspaper and her only columns  
were about her illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Ashley, editor of the Messenger-Inquirer, said there have  
not been any questions raised about her news stories. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hear nothing but praise for from the folks she covered in  
Ohio and Hancock Counties,'' Ashley said. ``Some have even sought 
to reassure us that Kim's reporting was accurate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If anybody raises any questions we'll certainly investigate  
it,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
