<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Keegan Named England's Soccer Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Kevin Keegan was hired Friday as England's  
national soccer coach -- one of the most high-profile jobs in the 
sport. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's my job not to get beheaded,'' the former English star  
said. ``I don't want a knighthood but I want to keep my head on my 
shoulders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He agreed to a three-year contract in a widely expected move.  
England's Football Association said he will work through the 2002 
World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see Kevin as England's manager for the millennium and far  
beyond that,'' F.A. interim executive director David Davies said. 
</P>
<P>
	Keegan had taken over as coach in February from the fired Glenn  
Hoddle and said he would coach only four games so he could stay 
with his English club. 
</P>
<P>
	But two weeks ago he said he would take the job full time and  
leave Fulham as soon as a deal could be struck. 
</P>
<P>
	In two games, Keegan led England to a 3-1 win over Poland in a  
qualifier for the 2000 European Championship and a 1-1 tie in an 
exhibition with Hungary. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know what comes with the job,'' Keegan said. ``I know the  
upside and downside. In this country people get very emotional 
about football and that's what I like about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said his goal is to win the World Cup, which England did in  
1966. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to try and match what the '66 team did,'' he said.  
``They had a bit of luck and we will need that, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not as cavalier as people make out, but I do like winning  
and I do know what it takes to win,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Keegan was one of soccer's biggest names in the 1970s. He helped  
Liverpool win three league championships and was twice voted 
European Player of the Year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
