<DOCNO> APW19990514.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 16:35:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Israel Election Remains Uncertain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and  
opposition leader Ehud Barak were left in suspense Friday as two 
minor contenders dropped hints but did not make a firm pledge to 
pull out before Monday's election. 
</P>
<P>
	New polls indicate that Barak has widened his lead over  
Netanyahu, but unless minor candidates withdraw the Labor leader 
might not get the 50 percent plus one vote he needs to clinch a 
first-round victory. 
</P>
<P>
	All eyes were on Yitzhak Mordechai, the center party candidate  
who was fired by Netanyahu as defense minister and who has vowed to 
stay on despite sinking in the polls. 
</P>
<P>
	The other contenders -- Azmi Bishara, the first-ever Arab  
candidate, and Benny Begin, the hawkish son of the late Prime 
Minister Menachem Begin -- were expected to withdraw. 
</P>
<P>
	Polls published Friday showed Barak widening his lead by about  
four percentage points since last week. 
</P>
<P>
	A Gallup poll in the Maariv daily gave Barak 48.5 percent and  
Netanyahu 35.5 percent in a five-way race. Mordechai won 4.6 
percent, Bishara received 2.5 percent and Begin got 2.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In a head-to-head contest, the poll gave Barak 54.2 percent and  
Netanyahu 37.4 percent. The poll questioned 1,100 Israeli adults 
and had a margin of error of four percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	A Dahaf poll in another newspaper, Yediot Ahronot, also put  
Barak ahead, but by a smaller margin: 44 percent to Netanyahu's 38 
percent in the first round, and 51 percent to Netanyahu's 41 
percent in a second. For this poll, 1,100 Israeli adults were 
questioned. It gave a margin of error of three percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Mordechai was not expected to make any move about staying in the  
race until Saturday night. If he dropped out, he would raise hopes 
for Barak to win a first-round victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheered by hundreds of supporters at a campaign rally, Mordechai  
pledged Thursday to stay in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not deterred by the results of this or that poll,''  
Mordechai said. ``The election is the real poll.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But pressure for Mordechai to withdraw has grown this week, with  
members of his own party asking him to pull out. 
</P>
<P>
	Bishara was widely expected to withdraw over the weekend. He has  
said from the beginning that his main reason for running was to 
galvanize the 500,000 Israeli Arab voters -- about 11 percent of the 
electorate of 4.3 million -- and to press for Arab rights. 
</P>
<P>
	His withdrawal would be a coup for Barak, whose Labor party is  
traditionally supported by Israeli Arabs. 
</P>
<P>
	Begin, who opposes territorial compromise with the Palestinians,  
is expected to decide Sunday whether he will stay in the race. 
Begin is said to have been driven into the race by a personal 
grudge against Netanyahu. 
</P>
<P>
	The candidates and parties will make their last pitches to the  
public Saturday night, when the final election ads are broadcast on 
television. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
