<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Motorcycle Champ Recovering Nicely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) -- Five-time world motorcycle champion  
Mick Doohan was recovering Friday after surgery to repair several 
broken bones suffering in a qualifying accident, and his doctor 
said prospects for his return to racing were excellent. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Arthur Ting, along with trauma experts Dr. Kevin Louie and  
Dr. Trig G. McClellan, needed 3 1/2 hours to repair a collarbone, left 
forearm and right leg broken May 7 during qualifying for last 
Sunday's Spanish Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	Doohan, 33, has six screws and a metal plate in his forearm and  
12 screws, two plates and a bone graft repairing his right tibia, 
Ting said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very, very pleased with how things went,'' he said.  
``His prospects for racing again are excellent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ting said getting the Australian racer back on a bike in three  
months was optimistic. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to depend on the way things heal,'' he said. ``We  
want to be optimistic and the way things turned out, we are 
optimistic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doohan, who has won the last five championships in the premier  
500cc class, was at The Recovery Inn, 25 miles south of San 
Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's extremely tough,'' Ting said. ``He needed very little  
pain medication for an extremely painful injury. He's lucky to be 
alive.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
