<DOCNO> APW19990514.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 14:33:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympics Announce New Sponsor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The 2002 Winter Games, struggling to  
rebound from scandal, got their first new corporate sponsor in 
nearly a year today. 
</P>
<P>
	Marker Ltd. of Salt Lake agreed to provide uniforms to games  
workers in a sponsorship worth at least $20 million, including 
cash, for OPUS, the company jointly marketing the games for the 
Salt Lake Organizing Committee and the U.S. Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other Utah companies have agreed to donate the medals and  
natural gas for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	``This gives us a real shot in the arm,'' said Salt Lake  
committee president Mitt Romney. ``It's a real boost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O.C. Tanner, a jewelry maker, will provide 1,500 gold, silver  
and bronze medals as well as 50,000 commemorative medals for 
athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	Questar Corp., Utah's biggest natural gas supplier, will provide  
the gas, including fuel for the Olympic cauldron flame. 
</P>
<P>
	The value of those deals is between $5 million and $10 million  
each. 
</P>
<P>
	The Olympic committees do not disclose the precise value of  
sponsor and supplier contracts in order to preserve negotiating 
room with other companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC has been saying it needs $300 million more from  
corporations to meet its $1.45 billion budget, and Romney declined 
Friday to say how much the three new contracts will knock off that 
figure. The SLOC generally gets 70 percent of sponsor fees. 
</P>
<P>
	The three companies signed letters of intent, with contracts to  
follow. 
</P>
<P>
	Corporations have been wary about the marketing value of the  
rings since revelations this winter that executives pushing Salt 
Lake's bid gave more than $1 million in gifts and services to 
International Olympic Committee members. The IOC voted in 1995 to 
give Salt Lake the games. 
</P>
<P>
	But the scandal was far from Romney's mind Friday as he joked  
about hitting up 18 IOC members for donations when they come next 
week to review Salt Lake's games preparations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told them to bring $10,000 each. That's the legal maximum  
for bringing into the country,'' Romney said, catching himself only 
after his staff burst into embarrassed laughter. ``I didn't think 
of the double entendre,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday night, Salt Lake officials will launch the games'  
mascot. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 13:42:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Maple Leafs' Domi Steps Lightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Tie Domi is a disappointed hockey player, but not  
one to cause dissension in the Toronto Maple Leafs' dressing room 
in the midst of the Stanley Cup playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Domi, upset about taking the pre-game skate then being deleted  
from the lineup before a 3-2 overtime victory Thursday night in 
Pittsburgh, skated with the scrubs Friday. The regulars had the day 
off, resting up for Saturday night, when they try to take a 3-2 
lead in the best-of-7 Eastern Conference semifinal series. 
</P>
<P>
	But he held his ego in check.  
</P>
<P>
	``We won, and that's all that matters,'' he said,  
</P>
<P>
	Coach Pat Quinn said he scratched Domi because the fourth-line  
forward is injured. During the first-round elimination of the 
Philadelphia Flyers, Domi was said to have a slight groin pull. But 
he hadn't missed any games and fully expected to skate in Game 4 
against the Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not 100 percent,'' Domi said, adding he's unsure if he'll  
be in the lineup for Game 5. ``I feel better. We'll see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Domi sat in the dressing room watching Game 4 on TV, fiddling  
with a crossword puzzle. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was tough not to be part of it,'' he said. ``After all  
these years not being in the playoffs and being in the playoffs 
now, not being part of a big game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a touchy subject to Quinn, who had a one-word retort when  
asked if he was worried that Domi's obvious disappointment would 
create dissension. 
</P>
<P>
	``No,'' he icily replied.  
</P>
<P>
	Egos must be put aside in favor of team goals, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're here to do one thing and that's to win this series,''  
Quinn said. ``It's my job to make the decisions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Domi has been largely ineffective in the playoffs. A racism  
charge by Philadelphia's Sandy McCarthy, which Domi denied, drained 
him emotionally. Quinn has warned Domi to stay out of the 
post-season penalty box, and used him for only about six minutes a 
game against the Penguins before yanking him Thursday in favor of 
first-line castoff Freddie Modin. 
</P>
<P>
	If Domi isn't going to fight, his usefulness -- healthy or not --  
comes into question when more skilled players are available to the 
coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Quinn does not perceive the Pittsburgh series to be one  
requiring a lot of muscle. That's why he's not using 6-foot-7 
defenseman Chris McAllister, who was impressive in the elimination 
of the Flyers. The more docile but speedier Tomas Kaberle took 
McAllister's place against the Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	McAllister has been told not to expect to get to defend against  
Pittsburgh's sensational Jaromir Jagr. 
</P>
<P>
	``This series is a little bit different from the Philadelphia  
series,'' McAllister said. ``They don't really have a physical 
presence on their team. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not a big, physical team. I just have to rest for this  
series, and once we get past this one I'll play against either 
Buffalo or Boston, I'm hoping.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, center Steve Sullivan continues to receive treatment  
for back spasms. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm getting better every day,'' Sullivan said. ``But I don't  
know how long it's going to take to be in game shape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also is uncertain if he'll play in Game 5.  
</P>
<P>
	``That I don't know,'' he said. ``We'll see how I feel and how  
the coaches feel about putting me in the lineup. It'll be a coach's 
and trainer's decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quinn says Sullivan will play if he's ready.  
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins, who won Game 1 on the road, are not concerned  
about the return to Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	``It takes the pressure off us playing up there,'' said forward  
Matthew Barnaby. 
</P>
<P>
	The status of injured Penguins Alexei Kovalev and German Titov  
remains uncertain. Without them, coach Kevin Constantine has relied 
heavily on Jagr, Martin Straka and Kevin Hatcher. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins looked worn down by the time the overtime period  
began Thursday night, but Barnaby didn't agree. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't speak for our whole team, but I don't think we were  
tired,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
