<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 21:11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress May Double Presidents Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House subcommittee approved legislation  
Friday that would provide for an increase in the president's salary 
-- effective the day President Clinton leaves office. 
</P>
<P>
	The adjustment would take effect at noon on Jan. 20, 2001 and  
would mark the first raise in the president's salary since Lyndon 
Johnson retired 30 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would double the chief executive's salary to  
$400,000 annually, according to Saturday's editions of The 
Washington Post. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation passed the House Appropriations Committee's  
Treasury-Postal Service Subcommittee as part of a huge spending 
bill. The House Government Reform Committee's panel on management, 
information and technology is scheduled to review the issue May 24. 
</P>
<P>
	The last pay increase for a president was in January, 1969, when  
the salary was doubled from $100,000 to $200,000 upon Richard Nixon 
assuming office. A $50,000 annual expense account established by 
Congress for the president also became effective then. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Constitution, pay raises can only be enacted at the  
change of administrations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 08:23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate GOP Retreats on Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With Republicans in full retreat, President  
Clinton today prodded the Senate to approve new restrictions on 
firearm sales at gun shows and to reject a ``phony proposal'' that 
he said was ``riddled with high-caliber loopholes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president turned up the heat after Republicans, stung by  
public criticism, agreed Thursday to reconsider a Senate vote a day 
earlier that had rejected a Democratic-proposed crackdown on 
private sales at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate today was expected to take up a proposal by Sen.  
Larry Craig, R-Idaho, that essentially would undo Wednesday's vote 
on gun-show sales. Still, some Democrats complained that the 
amendment wasn't all that it appeared to be. Clinton endorsed the 
Democrats' view. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new Senate Republican bill is still riddled with  
high-caliber loopholes,'' the president said at the White House. 
``It won't stop criminals from buying guns at gun shows. At the 
same time, it will open up a new pawnshop loophole that lets 
convicted felons get guns at a local pawnshop. That's actually 
worse than current law. I simply can't believe the Senate will make 
the same mistake twice. 
</P>
<P>
	``So, once again, I ask them to reject this phony proposal and  
to pass real legislation that requires the background checks 
necessary to prevent criminals from buy guns at gun shows which 
they cannot buy at gun stores,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republicans' abrupt U-turn underscored the shift in the gun-  
control debate following last month's shooting spree in Littleton, 
Colo., that left 14 high school students and a teacher dead. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the Senate agreed to prohibit the import of  
high-capacity ammunition clips not included in a 1994 assault 
weapons ban. An effort to kill the measure was rejected, 59-39, 
with almost all votes in opposition cast by Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats called it a victory over the National Rifle  
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NRA said no and it passed anyway,'' Sen. Dianne Feinstein,  
D-Calif., said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate also agreed to a proposal by Sen. John Ashcroft,  
R-Mo., to ban juvenile possession of semiautomatic weapons and 
high-capacity ammunition clips. That vote was 96-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite this week's action, a big backlog of amendments  
threatened to derail Sen. Orrin Hatch's underlying bill, which 
would stiffen prosecution standards for juvenile offenders. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in such a doggone log jam here that we might have to  
pull this bill down,'' Hatch, R-Utah, sputtered from the floor late 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate on Wednesday approved an amendment by Craig to make  
instant background checks of private sales at gun shows voluntary. 
But a half-dozen Republicans later complained to Craig, a member of 
the NRA's board of directors, that his amendment should go further 
to ensure that background checks are performed even in private 
sales at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a 2000 presidential  
contender, told Craig the amendment needed to be fixed. Sen. Gordon 
Smith, R-Ore., threatened to change his vote on Craig's amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	Several GOP sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said  
private polling in recent weeks has shown very strong support for 
gun control, even among potential voters in Republican presidential 
primaries. That is a marked shift from the past, in which base GOP 
voters were less supportive of gun control than the nation as a 
whole. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration also pounced on Wednesday's vote.  
Clinton, joined by Attorney General Janet Reno in some of the 
harshest terms she's used on congressional action, accused the 
Senate of ignoring the threat highlighted less than a month earlier 
by the shootings at Columbine High School. 
</P>
<P>
	By midafternoon Thursday, Craig announced that he would propose  
an amendment that would require background checks for all transfers 
of firearms at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats at first rejoiced. But later, they accused Craig of  
not strengthening gun laws. Democrats said Craig's new proposal 
still would leave a group of people who would not be required to do 
background checks of purchasers. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig disagreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Every gun transfer at gun shows would have a background check  
performed,'' Craig told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics also said that under Craig's new proposal, a sale would  
be approved automatically if the background check was not completed 
within 24 hours, rather than the three days in current law. They 
also said the proposal would continue to allow an individual to 
pawn a gun and reclaim it without undergoing a background check. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
