<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin Pushes Strong Decision-Making </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Outgoing Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin had at  
least one common bond with the New York University graduates he 
addressed today. 
</P>
<P>
	They're all in the job market.  
</P>
<P>
	A day after officially announcing he will step down from his  
Cabinet post, Rubin used folksy anecdotes and tales from his days 
in the Treasury to tell about 5,000 graduates that strong, reasoned 
decision-making is a key to success in life. 
</P>
<P>
	``The circumstances for decision-making may never be ideal. But  
you must decide nonetheless,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin's speech drew no parallels to his own long-anticipated  
decision to leave the Treasury. But in a brief conversation with 
reporters before he took the podium in Manhattan's Washington 
Square Park, he said he knew his job wasn't completely finished, as 
several world economies still struggle under the weight of last 
year's economic crises. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet he said he would not have resigned if he had been less  
confident in his successor, former deputy secretary Lawrence 
Summers. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, a former co-chairman at investment bank Goldman Sachs &AMP;  
Co., would not say whether he plans to return to a post in the 
private sector. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't know what I'm going to do,'' he said. ``But I  
will re-engage in some fashion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As an architect of U.S. economic policy, Rubin has been known as  
a cautious, disciplined thinker and speaker. But he encouraged the 
NYU graduates to embrace uncertainty. 
</P>
<P>
	``A healthy respect for uncertainty and focus on probability  
drives you never to be satisfied with your conclusions,'' he said. 
As an investment banker and as a Cabinet official, Rubin said, he 
was forced to make choices that might compromise profits or 
political relationships, often with little time to weigh every 
choice. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the end, all decisions are based on imperfect or incomplete  
information,'' he said. ``But decisions must be made -- and on a 
timely basis -- whether in school, on the trading floor, or in the 
White House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, draped in NYU's traditional purple robe, received an  
honorary doctor of laws degree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
