<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justice: Courts Must Build Trust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal and state courts should not sacrifice  
their independence while trying to bolster public confidence in the 
nation's system of justice, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``The search for greater public trust and confidence in the  
judiciary must be pursued consistently with the idea of judicial 
independence,'' Rehnquist told a national conference studying 
public perceptions of courts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is possible, in the name of building public trust and  
confidence in the judicial system, to say that judges who have 
rendered an unpopular decision should reconsider it if a majority 
of the public does not agree with it,'' said Rehnquist, the 
top-ranking federal judge. 
</P>
<P>
	``But whatever such a practice might do to increase public trust  
and confidence in the system -- and I think it might be quite 
counterproductive -- it would be quite contrary to the idea of an 
independent judiciary,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Recall of judicial decisions by some sort of a popular mandate  
... is too high a price to pay for public approval,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the justice system is an adversarial one, Rehnquist  
said, the typical case features one side that will win and one that 
will lose. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of the losers will understandably be disappointed, and  
some may feel they got a raw deal from the courts,'' he said. 
``There is little that the judicial system can do to change this 
perception if it is based solely on the fact that the litigant 
lost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unsuccessful litigants are not the only court critics. Those  
ranks also include lawyers, law professors, editorial commentators 
and writers in legal journals. Rehnquist said he hoped such 
criticism ``would be informed and rational,'' but he invoked a 
quote from 19th century Supreme Court Justice David Brewer: ``True, 
many criticisms may be, like their authors, devoid of good taste, 
but better all sorts of criticism than no criticism at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such criticism, if widespread and persistent, eventually proves  
effective, Rehnquist said. ``As judges of appellate courts resign, 
retire or die, public opinion through the appointing process by 
which the political branches choose their successors may change the 
judicial philosophy of a court. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a slow process,'' he said, ``but it is the only one  
consistent with the idea of an independent judiciary.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
