<HEADLINE> 2000 Presidential Race Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich, whose bid for the Republican  
presidential nomination has been met with a lukewarm response 
within his party, picked up a key endorsement Friday in crucial New 
Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	State Senator Carl Johnson, the highest ranking Republican  
legislator in the state, said his pick was based on Kasich's 
leadership in Congress, particularly his fight to balance the 
federal budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``John Kasich is a leader, plain and simple,'' Johnson said in  
statement. ``Under his leadership, Congress passed the first 
balanced budget since man walked on the moon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican leader of the state senate also praised Kasich's  
frequent visits to New Hampshire since becoming a contender for the 
Republican ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one is coming here more often,'' Johnson said. ``And no one  
is meeting more people than John Kasich.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush had vied for Johnson's support.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, the Republican front-runner, picked up the endorsements of  
another batch of state legislators on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan Gov. John Engler, and leaders from the Michigan House  
and Senate led a delegation of 20 Republican lawmakers to Austin, 
Texas, to deliver their endorsement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gov. Bush stands ready to lead our nation into the next  
millennium,'' said Charles Perricone, speaker of the Michigan 
House. ``He is a true leader who has the integrity and fortitude to 
serve as our nation's next president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 60 Michigan lawmakers endorsed Bush. Engler is a  
member of Bush's presidential exploratory committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also named Gerald W. Parsky, a University of California  
regent and a former assistant U.S. Treasury secretary, to head his 
California campaign. On Thursday, he mailed out fund-raising 
letters to 28,000 Californians, promising, ``Anyone contributing 
now will be included in events when I am able to come to your state 
later this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Gore announced Monday that he has named a top  
member of his finance team to anchor his presidential nomination 
team in New Hampshire, home of the nation's first presidential 
primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Nick Baldick, currently national deputy finance director for the  
Gore campaign, will take over the reins in the Granite State in the 
first week in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Baldick worked for the Clinton-Gore campaign in New Hampshire  
during the 1996 primaries, and he directed Democratic efforts in 
Florida in the 1996 general election. He also has worked as a 
political aide for the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 

</P>
<P>
	Hillary Rodham Clinton plans to use a Florida vacation with her  
husband late this month to decide whether to continue pursuing a 
possible run for retiring Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan's New 
York seat in the U.S. Senate, New York Democrats said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democrats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Mrs.  
Clinton's advisers have begun telling top party members in the 
state that she will make an announcement sometime in June. 
</P>
<P>
	``She will either announce she is not running or possibly  
announce formation of an exploratory committee,'' one Democrat with 
knowledge of the situation said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
