<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- A slain Argentine newspaper  
editor was buried here Friday, as his colleagues demanded he not 
join the list of journalists whose killers go unpunished. 
</P>
<P>
	Ricardo Gangeme, 56, editor of El Informador Chubutense and  
former editor of the Buenos Aires daily Cronica, was shot once in 
the head early Thursday in the southern Argentine city of Trelew. 
Colleagues reported that Gangeme, a crusading crime-fighting 
journalist, recently had received threats. 
</P>
<P>
	Jorge E. Fascetto, president of the Inter American Press  
Association, told a local radio station that hundreds of 
journalists have been killed worldwide over the years, with few 
cases getting solved. 
</P>
<P>
	But Fascetto, a board member at the El Dia daily newspaper in La  
Plata, said he hoped Gangeme's killers would be found. ``It is a 
terrible thing for democracy when someone kills the messenger so 
that the message isn't received,'' said Fascetto, who was in Taiwan 
for an international press gathering. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- A plasma production center in  
northeastern Brazil thought to have used blood contaminated with 
hepatitis and the AIDS virus has been shut down, the Health 
Ministry said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry said at least eight people may have been  
contaminated with either one of the viruses in the states of 
Pernambuco, Bahia, Rio de Janeiro, Alagoas and Santa Catarina. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 2,000 bags could be contaminated with the HIV virus and  
another 5,000 with the hepatitis virus, said the ministry. 
</P>
<P>
	Health Minister Jose Serra said authorities would try to locate  
where the bags, made from blood collected in 1997 and 1998, were 
sent and determine whether or not they have been used. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- Authorities temporarily closed the  
airport Friday in Tegucigalpa, the nation's capital, after smoke 
from an estimated 1,000 forest and grass fires mixed with fog to 
create a dense haze. 
</P>
<P>
	The terminal was closed to flights for about 11 hours before  
re-opening Friday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	But the problem was nothing compared to last year, when an  
estimated 5,000 such fires -- generally caused by farmers burning 
vegetation in preparation for spring planting -- caused the nation's 
four major airports to shut down for a total of 28 days in May, 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's shutdown forced controllers to reroute flights to the  
La Mesa international airport in the northern city of San Pedro 
Sula, 125 miles north of Tegucigalpa. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoke from this year's forest fires have caused a 30-percent  
increase in reported cases of respiratory illnesses, said Tito 
Alvarado, director of Tegucigalpa's Mario Rivas public hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	ACAPULCO, Mexico (AP) -- Guerrero state officials say they have  
arrested an eighth suspect in the Feb. 17 kidnapping of soccer star 
Jorge Campos' father. 
</P>
<P>
	State judicial police said Thursday that they arrested Obdulio  
Moreno Radilla in the town of Papanoa in the hills northwest of 
Acapulco. 
</P>
<P>
	Alvaro Campos, 66, was released on Feb. 23, reportedly after his  
family paid the equivalent of dlrs 63,000 in ransom. 
</P>
<P>
	Jorge Campos has played in U.S. Major League Soccer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
