<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets ended the week mixed  
Friday, with prices falling in Tokyo and Hong Kong but surging in 
Kuala Lumpur and Taipei. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at  
16,810.39 points, down 40.86 points, or 0.24 percent from Thursday. 
On Thursday, the index lost 96.11 points, or 0.57 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices initially rose in reaction to record gains on Wall  
Street, where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 106.82 points 
to close at 11,107.19, breezing past the previous closing record of 
11,031.59, posted May 7. 
</P>
<P>
	But players grew cautious about pushing prices higher before a  
series of closely watched earnings reports for the last fiscal 
year, ending in March, which are expected in coming weeks, traders 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Institutional investors start selling each time the Nikkei  
average nears 17,000,'' said Kazunori Jinnai, deputy general 
manager of the equity department at Daiwa Securities SB Capital 
Markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 122.18 yen late Friday,  
up 0.60 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New 
York level of 121.85 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Hong Kong slumped Friday after two straight  
sessions of advances. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, fell 198.15 points, or 1.5 percent, closing at 
12,855.52. On Thursday, the index had gained 40.7 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said share prices fell as investors took profits  
following recent sharp gains. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the index rose to 13,000 points, the atmosphere has turned  
cautious,'' said James So, head of sales at Asia Financial 
(Securities) Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysian share prices soared on hopes that Malaysia will be  
reinstated into the closely-watched Morgan Stanley Capital 
International Indexes, or MSCI, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange's Composite Index, which tracks  
100 key stocks, rose 4.5 percent, or 33.29 points, to close at 
766.82. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan Stanley is expected to announce changes Monday to the  
components of its index, which is widely watched by fund managers 
in Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Malaysia is in the index, we can expect money from the U.S.  
to enter the local bourse,'' said an institutional dealer. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Taiwan also closed sharply higher, fueled by  
gains in U.S. stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taipei market's key Weighted Stock Price Index rose 176.33  
points, or 2.37 percent, to 7,592.53. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Share prices closed sharply higher as the Indonesia  
government signed a new letter of intent with the International 
Monetary Fund, paving the way for the release of around U.S. dlr 1 
billion in loans from the IMF's bailout package. The Composite 
Index rose 15.130 points, or 2.6 percent, to 591.634. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed sharply higher,  
spurred on by broad demand for local blue-chip stocks, brokers 
said. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 32.17 points or 1.5 
percent, to 2,251.32. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed lower on fears of a possible  
rise in key U.S. interest rates next week, traders said. The 
30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index fell 19.26 points, or 
0.8 percent, to 2,502.75. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed generally higher, after  
the country's major banks and other blue-chip industrial stocks 
helped to boost the market indicator. The All Ordinaries Index rose 
25.4 points, or 0.8 percent, to 3,055.0. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed lower on concerns about rising  
interest rates. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell 4.54 
points, or 0.6 percent, to 737.83. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed higher, with the benchmark index  
gaining on the back of selective buying of index linked stocks. The 
Straits Times Index rose 14.45 points, or 0.8 percent, to 1,883.28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
