<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rudd Hopes Crew Chief Brings Luck </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Virginia native Ricky Rudd is hoping crew  
chief Michael McSwain will help get his Ford team moving in the 
right direction. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chesapeake native arrived at Richmond International Raceway  
37th in the driver standings and hasn't finished better than 19th 
this season, which he entered having won a race in a modern-record 
16 consecutive seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've watched him and he's a real good people person,'' Rudd  
said of McSwain, who resigned as crew chief for Rick Mast last 
week. ``He knows how to take the people around him and get them to 
rally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McSwain was with his new team for testing at Lowe's Motor  
Speedway in Charlotte last week, and is hoping to get comfortable 
in a hurry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Like any new deal, it will take Ricky and me some time to  
learn how to work with each other,'' he said. ``I need some time to 
learn what he likes in a race car and I think we made some progress 
at Charlotte.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *RUSTY'S RACEWAY:* Rusty Wallace declared Bristol his favorite  
track last month, then proceeded to win the pole, lead 425 of 500 
laps and post his seventh career victory on the high-banked 
.533-mile oval. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace's career numbers at Richmond are even better since the  
track was rebuilt into a three-quarter-mile layout. 
</P>
<P>
	Since finishing 35th in the first race on the new track in the  
fall of 1988, Wallace has six victories, 19 top-10 finishes and 15 
top-fives at Richmond. He's run all but four of the 8,000 laps in 
those 20 races. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace almost got win No. 7 in this race a year ago, but wound  
up third after bumping Jeff Gordon off the lead -- and into the wall 
-- with 28 laps to go. Terry Labonte nudged Dale Jarrett aside with 
two laps left to win. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a wild one, that's for sure,'' Wallace said. ``And we  
were in the middle of it. It'll probably be another wild one again 
this Saturday.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MORE CREWS NEWS:* Pat Tryson has joined Johnny Benson's Winston  
Cup team as crew chief after a year as the car chief for Chad 
Little. 
</P>
<P>
	For Tryson, the move is like going home, at least when it comes  
to the car number. Benson drives the No. 26 Ford for Roush Racing, 
the same car number Tryson worked with as crew chief for NHRA star 
Kenny Bernstein. 
</P>
<P>
	Benson, 28th in the driver standings, was surprised by the  
switch, which put Bobby Leslie in apparent limbo within Jack 
Roush's racing stable. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a shock, but by the same token we need to have better  
results than what we've been having,'' Benson said. His best finish 
is 11th. 
</P>
<P>
	Other drivers working with new crew chiefs this weekend include  
Steve Park, now with Steve Hmiel in charge; Rick Mast, who hired 
Jerry Pitts after Pitts quit Bill Elliott's team; and Elliott, who 
promoted Wayne Orme, the chief for the now defunct No. 13 team at 
Daytona to start the season. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LOCAL OWNER GETS SPONSOR:* Struggling Winston Cup owner Junie  
Donlavey, based in Richmond, announced a sponsorship deal with Hill 
Brothers Coffee for the Pontiac 400 at RIR on Saturday night. 
Donlavey, in his 50th season as a Winston Cup owner, will put Hut 
Stricklin in his Ford for the race. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STAT OF THE DAY:* Jeff Gordon had 17 consecutive top-five  
finishes after getting bumped by Rusty Wallace after taking the 
lead with 28 laps to go in the spring race last year. Gordon 
finished that race a season-worst 37th. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
