<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Candidates Running on Spite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Two Virginia primary races are marked by  
the thinking: Don't get mad, get even. 
</P>
<P>
	State legislator Anne G. ``Panny'' Rhodes angered Gov. Jim  
Gilmore, a fellow Republican, by opposing some of his initiatives. 
So Gilmore has taken the extraordinary step of endorsing her 
opponent in the June 8 primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Another House of Delegates member, William P. Robinson Jr., had  
a falling-out with friend Luther C. Edmonds. Now Edmonds is running 
against Robinson in a Democratic primary while awaiting retrial on 
charges he pistol-whipped Robinson. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Rhodes is among a small band of moderate Republicans who  
have bucked Gilmore and his predecessor, George Allen, both 
conservatives, on tax cuts and major social issues such as abortion 
and welfare. 
</P>
<P>
	In announcing his backing for Ms. Rhodes' challenger, Ruble  
Hord, Gilmore said Ms. Rhodes had effectively switched parties. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not just about Panny Rhodes,'' said University of  
Virginia political analyst Larry Sabato. ``It's about a handful of 
other moderates who go their own way. It's a warning with a capital 
`W' -- toe the line, or this could happen to you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it is rare for governors to meddle in primaries.  
</P>
<P>
	``They learn to avoid fights that aren't absolutely necessary  
because every fight reduces the political capital you have in the 
bank,'' Sabato said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilmore can afford the risk more than most governors because  
Virginia is the only state that does not allow its chief executive 
to seek re-election. 
</P>
<P>
	Edmonds is charged with malicious wounding, use of a firearm in  
a felony and the unlawful wearing of a mask in a 1997 attack on 
Robinson. A mistrial was declared Thursday after the jury 
deadlocked. Prosecutors said they will retry the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The two men parted ways when Robinson publicly disputed the  
reason Edmonds gave for resigning from the bench during a 
misconduct inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	Edmonds said his personal feelings have nothing to do with his  
second attempt to unseat Robinson (the first came just weeks before 
the attack). ``I feel I'm a better candidate for the position,'' 
Edmonds said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson told The Virginian-Pilot: ``I don't think there is any  
question about the real motivation of his candidacy -- spite.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
