<DOCNO> APW19990514.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 16:41:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Home Ice No Blessing in Playoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- In a series in which home ice is no advantage, the  
edge, surprisingly, goes to the reeling Detroit Red Wings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings' pursuit of a third straight Stanley Cup  
championship appeared shaky after being pummeled twice in a row at 
home, 5-3 and 6-2, by the Colorado Avalanche. The two victories 
squared the playoff series at 2-2 and gave the momentum to 
Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	But wait. Two of the remaining three games -- if the series goes  
the limit -- are scheduled for Colorado, which looks like a 
disadvantage for the Avalanche since the home team hasn't won a 
game yet in this Western Conference semifinal. 
</P>
<P>
	In an unusual twist, the team that manages to steal a win at  
home might be the series winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado, 1-4 at home in the postseason this year, went to 5-0  
on the road with its 6-2 romp over Detroit on Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're playing very well on the road, and we're due to win a  
game at home,'' said Avalanche goalie Patrick Roy, who had 31 saves 
in notching his 105th career playoff victory, extending his NHL 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	``We seem to come up with the big effort when we've needed to on  
the road,'' forward Theo Fleury said. ``All year long, ever since 
I've been here, we've been a great road team. That's something we 
should think about when we go to Denver. Let's simplify the games 
now, not get too fancy, do what we've done the last two hockey 
games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That seemed to be the only reasonable explanation for Colorado's  
superior play on the road as opposed to at home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that at home, we put too much pressure on ourselves to  
do too much,'' said Peter Forsberg, who scored his first goal of 
the series Thursday night. ``When we are playing on the road, we 
seem able to relax and play our type of hockey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just four days earlier, the Avs looked primed to be swept.  
Detroit embarrassed the home team with a methodical 4-0 victory 
last Sunday to take a commanding 2-0 lead, with Games 3 and 4 in 
Detroit. One Denver columnist wrote: ``This series is done. We all 
know. It's over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But then came two unexpected victories at Detroit. Roy was  
brilliant, and the Avs finally got scoring from their third and 
fourth lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``We looked passive out there,'' Detroit defenseman Nicklas  
Lidstrom said. ``I thought we let them skate through the neutral 
zone again. We weren't there to clear the rebounds, and they jumped 
on all the loose pucks in our end. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we have to get back to the way we played in Denver --  
play real solid defensively and prevent them from getting the 
rebounds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the second straight game, Detroit goalie Bill Ranford failed  
to make it through the second period, and now the Red Wings face a 
goalie controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	Ranford, starting his fourth straight game in place of injured  
Chris Osgood, who is out with a sprained right knee, let three of 
the first 14 shots he faced get past him. He was replaced by Norm 
Maracle at 14:04 of the second period with Detroit trailing 3-0. 
</P>
<P>
	If Osgood is close to being healthy, do the Wings switch to  
their regular goalie? Or do they stay with Ranford, or go with the 
rookie Maracle? 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit coach Scotty Bowman said his team was flat Thursday  
night and he replaced Ranford because ``I felt we needed some kind 
of boost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman said Osgood ``was close'' to playing Thursday night.  
``He's not 100 percent,'' Bowman said. ``I would hope in the next 
couple of days. It will depend on how he does in the workouts (in 
Denver).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Game 6 is set for next Tuesday in Detroit. A seventh game, if  
necessary, would be played in Denver next Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
