<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hail Delays Discovery Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Discovery is headed  
back to the hangar instead of into orbit next week because of hail 
damage to its giant fuel tank. 
</P>
<P>
	Discovery had been scheduled to blast off May 20 with 1 1/2 tons of  
cargo for the new international space station. NASA is now 
targeting liftoff for no earlier than May 27. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll take the amount of time it takes to go fix the vehicle  
correctly,'' shuttle processing director Dave King said following 
Thursday's decision. ``We think that's a week to 10 days at this 
point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hail gouged about 150 holes into the foam insulation on  
Discovery's 15-story external fuel tank during a severe 
thunderstorm over the weekend. At least 35 of the nicks are in an 
area that cannot be reached from the launch pad. 
</P>
<P>
	The largest visible hole on the tank is 2 inches wide and  
one-third of an inch deep. Most are much smaller. 
</P>
<P>
	Engineers are worried that ice could form in the holes when the  
tank is filled with super-cold fuel in the final hours of the 
countdown. If chunks of ice broke off at liftoff, the shuttle could 
be damaged. The cockpit windows are especially vulnerable. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is we could not rule out the possibility of  
ice in those areas,'' King said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shuttles have been rolled off the pad and back into the Vehicle  
Assembly Building only 12 times before. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Discovery was sent back because of fuel-tank damage  
caused by a pair of woodpeckers that drilled about 200 holes in the 
rust-colored foam insulation, apparently in an attempt to roost and 
build nests. 
</P>
<P>
	The technique that was used to fix the woodpecker damage will  
probably be used again this time, King said. 
</P>
<P>
	Discovery's 10-day ferry mission will be the year's first  
shuttle flight. The last was in December, when Endeavour carried up 
the first U.S.-built section of the space station. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the longest gap in shuttle launches since flights resumed  
in 1988 following the 1986 Challenger disaster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
