<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chase Manhattan Exec Eyed for Fed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House is getting closer to choosing  
a banker active in lending to disadvantaged people and businesses 
as a new governor of the Federal Reserve Board. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration is currently tangling with Senate  
Banking Committee head Phil Gramm, R-Texas, over federal 
requirements for banks to do that kind of lending. Any White House 
nominee for the post would have to be approved by the banking panel 
before being confirmed by the full Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Carol J. Parry, 58, is an executive vice president of Chase  
Manhattan Bank, the nation's third-largest. She is in charge of 
community development lending programs, making her responsible for 
loans for low- and moderate-income housing, commercial 
revitalization projects and businesses owned by women and 
minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks are required to make such loans by the Community  
Reinvestment Act, which Gramm staunchly opposes and the 
administration heartily defends. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House considers Ms. Parry highly qualified for the Fed  
governor post and she is now the ``front-runner,'' an 
administration official said Friday. He spoke on condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Parry, who has more than 30 years of management experience  
in the financial industry and the public sector, was named by 
President Clinton in 1997 to the Fed's Consumer Advisory Council. 
</P>
<P>
	The spot on the powerful, seven-member governors' board of the  
central bank has been vacant since last June, when Republican 
appointee Susan Phillips resigned to head the business school at 
George Washington University. 
</P>
<P>
	The board is the governing body of the Fed, which determines  
interest-rate policy, regulates banks, oversees the nation's 
payments system and is the lender of last resort in financial 
crises. It currently has only one member -- Edward W. Kelley Jr. -- 
who was not named by Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Parry, who previously had been criticized by some community  
groups for not doing enough, now appears to have their support. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things have changed. People have developed more confidence in  
her,'' said John Taylor, president and chief executive officer of 
the National Community Reinvestment Coalition, a liberal group. 
</P>
<P>
	He described Ms. Parry as someone ``with a good heart and good  
experience'' who ``knows what community reinvestment lending is all 
about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If confirmed, she would become the first Fed governor with  
``sustained experience'' with lending under the Community 
Reinvestment Act, Taylor said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1977 law is fiercely opposed by Gramm and other conservative  
Republicans, who maintain it is an unfair government mandate 
telling banks to whom they should lend. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeping legislation to lift the barriers separating banks,  
securities firms and insurance companies, which passed the Senate 
last week, contains provisions drafted by Gramm that the White 
House views as an attack on the lending law. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Clinton administration supports the financial  
services legislation in principle, it has threatened a presidential 
veto of the Senate bill unless the provisions are removed. 
</P>
<P>
	The provisions would exempt small rural banks from the  
community-lending law and make it harder for the government to use 
satisfactory community-lending ratings as a requirement for banks 
being allowed to expand. 
</P>
<P>
	Christi Harlan, a spokeswoman for Gramm, said Friday he had no  
comment on Ms. Parry's possible nomination because it had not yet 
occurred. Edward Yingling, a lobbyist for the American Bankers 
Association, also declined comment. Chase Manhattan spokeswoman 
Charlotte Gilbert-Biro said Ms. Parry would not be available for 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to heading the Community Development Group at New  
York-based Chase Manhattan, Ms. Parry also is a member of the 
bank's Policy Council and is responsible for its corporate 
philanthropy. 
</P>
<P>
	She also has worked as a management consultant, headed her own  
consulting business, and directed child welfare services for New 
York City. She has a bachelor's degree from Tufts University and a 
master's in social work from the University of Connecticut. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
