<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Where Did Yankee Magic Go? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The best team in baseball is just another club  
again. 
</P>
<P>
	In two weeks the New York Yankees have gone from a team that was  
virtually unbeatable last year to one that is downright 
bewildering. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season the Yankees rolled through their championship season  
without a pronounced slump. Now, just halfway through May, they've 
already hit notable lows. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees have been shut out at home one more time than they  
were last season. They've been swept in a three-game series for the 
first time since 1997. They have as many home losses as they had by 
July 19 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of things were almost magical last year,'' Bernie  
Williams said. ``It was almost like a dream season. That happens 
once every hundred years. I think it would be very unfortunate to 
hold us to that standard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It may by unfortunate, but after winning an AL-record 114 games  
and sweeping the San Diego Padres in the World Series expectations 
clearly were heightened. 
</P>
<P>
	They rose even further after the Yankees re-signed all of last  
year's key players and then traded for Roger Clemens, the five-time 
Cy Young Award winner. 
</P>
<P>
	The record-setting season, however, has provided further  
motivation for opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	A small-market team like the Kansas City Royals, trying to keep  
its players and stay near .500, can make its season with a good 
showing against the World Series champions. 
</P>
<P>
	A struggling team like the injury-riddled Anaheim Angels can use  
a sweep in New York to vault back into contention. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no team that ever comes in here that is flat,'' Angels  
manager Terry Collins said after sweeping the Yankees. ``You can't 
do it. They are the best team in the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But they sure haven't played that way, especially during their  
7-9 streak the last two weeks -- a slump they didn't hit until they 
led the AL East by 18 1/2 games last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether coincidental or not, the skid paralleled the mixup in  
Texas when interim manager Don Zimmer announced he was leaving the 
team only to find out Joe Torre wasn't ready to return from 
prostate cancer surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre's absence, which should last about two more weeks, has  
been one of many for New York, which has put Clemens, Andy 
Pettitte, Jeff Nelson, Scott Brosius on the disabled list. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees also have played the entire season without Darryl  
Strawberry, who is on ``administrative leave'' after being arrested 
on charges of cocaine possession and solicitation. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one is going to feel sorry for the Yankees,'' Paul O'Neill  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Neill, New York's most reliable hitter the five seasons, is in  
a 3-for-27 slump. O'Neill is one of many Yankees struggling -- Chuck 
Knoblauch is 1-for-25, Brosius is 2-for-20 and Tino Martinez is 
4-for-20 -- and his distress is evident. 
</P>
<P>
	``We scored a lot of runs in batting practice,'' O'Neill said.  
``The problem is we didn't in the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's frustrating, no doubt. That's the only way to describe  
it. You feel like you are letting a lot of people down when you 
play like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Known for slamming batting helmets and throwing water coolers,  
which he did Tuesday, O'Neill has now drifted into a more 
analytical stage. 
</P>
<P>
	He can be seen shaking his head after grounding into a  
rally-killing double play or taking extra swings in the batting 
cage. Neither has provided the answer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Paul O'Neill is going to hit, and hopefully soon,'' Zimmer  
said. ``Eventually, they are all going to start hitting. I'm not 
worried about this club's hitting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Zimmer was worried enough to call his first team meeting as  
manager Thursday. First he broke up a players-only meeting on 
Wednesday and then he delivered his own message Thursday: Be on 
time, play hard and, most important, have fun. 
</P>
<P>
	``How many ball players on the 29 other teams would like to be  
two games in front in their division,'' Zimmer said. ``If you're 
not having fun playing for this team, there's something wrong. 
Baseball is a kid's game and you have to have fun playing it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish I had the right thing to say, then they could snap out  
of it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
