<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies' Brantley Ready To Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Phillies closer Jeff Brantley might not miss  
the whole season after all. 
</P>
<P>
	After Dr. James Andrews prescribed rehab instead of  
season-ending surgery on his right shoulder, Brantley has felt 
``fabulous'' in bullpen workouts and could be activated from the 
disabled list as early as Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brantley did pregame warmups and throwing Friday and warmed up  
in the bullpen during a 7-3 loss to the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Brantley did very well in his workout,'' Phillies manager  
Terry Francona said. ``He said he felt great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That means Brantley could come off the DL by the end of the  
weekend. If the Phillies believe he needs to throw more on the 
side, he will do so again Sunday and be activated Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brantley, 35, acquired from St. Louis in the offseason, went on  
the disabled list April 29 with a sore right shoulder. He was 
eligible to return Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Two doctors diagnosed a torn labrum and recommended surgery,  
which probably would have ended Brantley's season. As a last 
resort, Brantley went to Birmingham, Ala., to get checked out by 
Andrews, who performed his most recent shoulder surgery in 1997. 
Andrews prescribed a cortisone shot and rest, and Brantley got 
positive results. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could pitch in a game right now,'' Brantley said during the  
Phillies' recent 5-1 road trip. ``But we don't want to push it. I 
don't want to be waffling back and forth between the DL all 
season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither do the Phillies, who traded former closer Ricky  
Bottalico and Garrett Stephenson to the Cardinals for Brantley, Ron 
Gant and right-hander Cliff Politte. The Cardinals are paying $1 
million of Brantley's $2.8 million salary, but Philadelphia doesn't 
have a proven closer if Brantley can't pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	The Phillies tried to bolster the bullpen by trading Paul  
Spoljaric to Toronto for right-hander Robert Person last week. 
</P>
<P>
	When Brantley comes off the disabled list, the Phillies will  
have to decide whether to send Mike Grace or Joel Bennett to the 
minors. Bennett was called up from Triple-A last week and won his 
first major league start in Denver. 
</P>
</TEXT>
