<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Probe Won't Change Reading Scores </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two states that posted large gains on a national  
reading test would have shown only average performance had they not 
excluded more special-education students, an analysis by the 
Education Department reveals. One state with modest gains could 
also have been boosted by the exclusions. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland and Kentucky, which were lauded last month for the 1994  
to 1998 increases in reading scores of fourth-grade students, also 
excluded significant numbers of special education students in that 
time period. Minnesota could have claimed higher average scores 
because it excluded fewer special-ed students. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither scores nor rankings will be affected, but the federal  
study of the 1998 test results could lead test-givers to change 
some policies, Pascal D. Forgione Jr., chief of the Education 
Department's statistical branch, said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been woken up on the issue that we must monitor this  
participation rate,'' he said. ``If it keeps going like it is, the 
increase could be statisically significant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forgione's department released the study results today at a  
meeting of the board that oversees the test. 
</P>
<P>
	Because many states used the gains to tout success of reforms  
back home, the validity and integrity of the national voluntary 
test is under the glare of cricial scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know people care a lot about the confidence of these test  
scores,'' he said. ``We will try to develop set of materials to 
help people understand it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though the research pointed out differences in average scores,  
he said, no rankings will be officially changed because the report 
used a model to compare test scores of included students with the 
estimated performance of the types of students who were excluded. 
</P>
<P>
	The study also found:  
</P>
<P>
	-- 10 of the 36 testing states excluded higher percentages of  
special-needs students. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 5 of the 36 states excluded higher numbers of non-native  
English speaking students. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 1 state that posted a modest gain actually did better under  
the analysis formula. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 reading scores of fourth-grade students -- the only  
grade level available for state-by-state comparison -- increased in 
several states, including those that suffered political fallout 
over previous poor showings. 
</P>
<P>
	The states that showed the largest score gains and largest  
increases all would have had lower average scores had 
special-education students been included. Of those states -- 
Connecticut, Kentucky, Louisiana and South Carolina -- only Kentucky 
remained the same. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they don't change the scores, they have a problem,'' said  
Richard G. Innes, a Kentucky education activist who tracks state 
education trends. He believes that state's average score, based on 
the performance of special-needs children on state tests, should 
drop at least three points. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 18 of the 30-plus participating states left out more  
special education students from the 1998 testing sample than from 
the 1994 group. Of those states, 15 posted gains in the average 
score. Kentucky pulled out 10 percent of students selected for its 
1998 sample, compared with 4 percent in 1994. And Connecticut, the 
nation's highest-scoring state, removed 10 percent of the students 
selected to participate, compared with 6 percent in 1994. Louisiana 
pulled 13 percent in 1998, up from 6 percent in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The nationwide percentage of students excluded did not increase.  
</P>
<P>
	States with more exclusions maintain that they followed the  
rules and that their gains are valid. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know that our regular education students gained 7 points on  
their (average) scores,'' said Catherine Heitman, a spokeswoman for 
the Louisiana education department. ``We do not believe pulling out 
special education students affected that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many special-needs students took the test, until 1998, when  
states had to follow a federal law that required that special-needs 
students get special help on any test comparing their results with 
others. The testing board responded by having states exclude those 
students from the national sample. 
</P>
<P>
	The test, called the National Assessment of Educational  
Progress, and its board was established by Congress. The test is 
given roughly every two years to a nationwide sample of children in 
three grade levels in core subjects like math and reading. The 
voluntary test is generally the only way to compare student 
progress nationwide, because states' tests vary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
