<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UMass Campus Mourns Lacrosse Player </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMHERST, Mass. (AP) -- Family, teammates and friends grieved at a  
memorial service Thursday and laid a wreath at a field in memory of 
a Massachusetts lacrosse player killed by an accident in practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Sopracasa, 21, of Farmingville, N.Y., collapsed when struck  
in the chest by a lacrosse ball May 5 on the Amherst campus. 
</P>
<P>
	A state medical examiner awaited more tests before deciding on a  
cause of death. But other doctors say Sopracasa apparently died of 
a known but rare type of injury. 
</P>
<P>
	They say the lacrosse ball hit his chest at precisely the wrong  
moment in the cycle of his heart beat. Such a blow can confuse the 
heart and disrupt its normal beat. 
</P>
<P>
	About 400 people, including Sopracasa's parents and coaches,  
filled a hall at the Newman Center on campus for the hour-long 
memorial service. Sopracasa was remembered as a spirited player and 
warmhearted person. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eric constantly challenged himself,'' said teammate Jay Negus.  
``Tenacity enabled him to be a giant on the field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sopracasa, a junior, was a clothing marketing major and a  
starting defensive midfielder for the lacrosse team. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Cannella, coach of the lacrosse team, said, ``When you  
recruit young men to become part of your program, they become part 
of you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	University Chancellor David Scott, who read a poem, added, ``The  
death of a young person always is hard to understand. This is a sad 
loss for the entire UMass community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those at the service later marched to the team's home field,  
where they placed the wreath. Sopracasa was injured at a separate 
practice field. 
</P>
<P>
	Campus spokeswoman Kay Scanlan later said administrators are  
reviewing the circumstances of the death ``to see if our procedures 
could be improved.'' But she said the lacrosse program is expected 
to remain on a solid footing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
