<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Plunge / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices plunged today, pushing interest  
rates to the highest level in more than a year, after a report 
revealing the biggest leap in consumer prices in nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 2 1/4 points,  
or $22.50 per $1,000 in face value. 
</P>
<P>
	Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, shot higher  
from late Thursday's 5.75 percent, ending the day at 5.92 percent. 
The yield is used to calculate the interest charged on many loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The selloff in bonds, which accompanied a steep decline in the  
stock market, was sparked by government data showing that consumer 
prices jumped an unexpectedly sharp 0.7 percent in April, led by a 
record spike in energy prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The report played on fears that the Federal Reserve might boost  
interest rates to slow the economy and contain inflationary 
pressures. Rapid inflation and rising interest rates make 
fixed-income investments such as bonds less appealing. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market Friday, prices of short-term Treasury  
securities fell between 5/16 and 17/32 point, while intermediate 
maturities fell between 29/32 and 1 21/32 point, reported Bridge 
Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose from late Thursday's  
4.58 percent to 4.63 percent, while the discount rose 0.05 
percentage point to 4.51 percent. Six-month yields rose to 4.76 
percent, while the discount rose 0.08 percentage point to 4.58 
percent. One-year yields rose to 4.85 percent as the discount rose 
0.12 percentage point to 4.62 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.88 percent from late Thursday's 4.81 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 1 3/16 points to 121 25/32. The average 
yield to maturity rose to 5.38 percent, up from late Thursday's 
5.32 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
