<HEADLINE> Woman Convicted of Abusing Elderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- A former nursing home aide was convicted  
Friday of abusing Alzheimer's patients, including an 83-year-old 
woman she forced to eat feces. 
</P>
<P>
	Stacy Arruda, 26, of Derry, N.H., was found guilty by a judge of  
two counts of elder abuse and seven counts of patient abuse. The 
charges carry a total of up to 24 years in prison and $37,000 in 
fines. 
</P>
<P>
	``The patients' frail conditions and the unspeakable nature of  
the attacks make these the most disturbing incidents of elderly 
abuse ever encountered by my office,'' Attorney General Tom Reilly 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses, mostly co-workers, testified Arruda assaulted five  
residents, all over 80, while working at the Wilmington Woods 
Nursing Home. 
</P>
<P>
	She kicked, beat and spit on patients. In one incident, she  
kicked and stomped on the crotch of an 81-year-old resident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
