<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dell, Micron Settle FTC Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two of the largest computer makers have agreed  
to provide consumers with ``clear, readable and understandable 
information in their lease advertising,'' the Federal Trade 
Commission says. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell Computer Corp. and Micron Electronics Inc. settled  
government charges they misled consumers with Internet 
advertisements to lease new computers with low monthly payments. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC said Thursday that ads from Dell and Micron included  
important cost information in inconspicuous or unreadable fine 
print, or they omitted the information. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consumers want to know what's what, and advertisers have an  
obligation to tell them,'' said Jodie Bernstein, director of the 
FTC's Bureau of Competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC settlement, approved 4-0 by the commission, becomes  
final after a 60-day public comment period. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for Dell, Libba Letton, described the problems  
with the company's ads as ``relatively minor and isolated, and they 
were quickly and easily addressed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dell is the nation's top direct-sale computer maker, with sales  
last year of $1.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Micron, the third-largest direct-sales manufacturer, did not  
return calls. 
</P>
<P>
	Under lease offers, consumers pay little or no money up front  
for a new computer but pay a monthly fee of $150 or less, typically 
for two or three years. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the lease, consumers can return the machine and  
lease a new one with the latest technology, or they can buy the 
older computer for its market value, usually a set percentage of 
its original price. 
</P>
<P>
	But over the long term, leasing a computer is almost always more  
expensive than buying one -- even if the purchase is charged to a 
credit card. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC charged that ads from Dell failed to adequately explain  
to consumers that low monthly payments applied to a lease and not 
to a purchase. 
</P>
<P>
	Some pricing information on Internet ads from Dell and Micron  
actually was located on linked Web pages, the FTC charged. 
</P>
<P>
	``The consumer had to scroll down or click on a link to get the  
full information that Dell provided, and the FTC didn't think that 
was adequate,'' Letton said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 23:51:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parties Vie for Kosovo Bill Kudos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House and Republican-controlled  
Congress both claim victory in a $15 billion package paying for the 
air war against Yugoslavia, disaster aid to Central America and 
other needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers are expected to approve the package next week, capping  
weeks of maneuvering between the two sides. On Friday, the day 
after Senate-House negotiators struck a deal on a compromise 
measure, earlier White House veto threats all but dissolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's been significant progress in meeting the goals the  
president outlined,'' said Linda Ricci, spokeswoman for the White 
House budget office. ``We expect the president will be presented 
with a bill he can sign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans latched onto the bill's defense funds as a win for  
their side. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly $12 billion of the measure is for the U.S. role in the  
NATO campaign against Yugoslavia and other Pentagon programs, 
doubling the money President Clinton sought. Republicans were eager 
to use that to burnish their pro-defense reputation, arguing that 
the bill is a first step toward reinvigorating a military that 
Clinton has allowed to shrivel. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite our differences over the administration's Balkan  
policy, this bill sends a strong message to our troops in the field 
that the Congress supports them,'' said House Appropriations 
Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla., one of the bill's chief 
authors. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans were bragging about language forbidding the federal  
government from grabbing any of the $246 billion tobacco companies 
have agreed to pay states in a legal settlement. Clinton had been 
counting on using billions from that kitty for health and 
anti-smoking programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal conservatives scored two wins, though both were largely  
symbolic. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly $2 billion of the package's cost will be paid for with  
cuts in domestic programs. Clinton didn't want any cuts, preferring 
to use the federal surplus for the entire cost. 
</P>
<P>
	At the insistence of House and Senate GOP leaders, a provision  
offered by Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., was dropped that would have 
provided $140 million to back a $1 billion loan program for 
struggling steel companies. Byrd's prowess for winning home-state 
projects, unparalleled in Congress, has made his proposals an 
enticing target for conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., also benefited when he  
successfully pressured two House GOP negotiators to switch their 
earlier positions and vote to block Byrd's project. After five 
months as speaker in which he has passively let GOP strategy 
evolve, his action was seen by many Republicans as a rare act of 
decisiveness. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration officials claimed victories for limiting  
GOP-sought defense increases and environmental restrictions and 
winning funds for U.S. farmers and victims of domestic and overseas 
natural disasters. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials boasted that they blocked a loan-guarantee  
program for oil and gas companies, narrowed a bid to let mining 
companies expand toxic dump sites and blocked an effort to lift 
fishing restrictions in Alaska's Glacier Bay National Park. 
</P>
<P>
	But environmental groups complained that too many  
anti-environmental provisions survived. These included items 
offered by Western senators delaying new rules that would force 
mining companies to pay more for cleanups and boosting royalties 
owed by oil companies drilling on public lands. 
</P>
<P>
	``He really should veto this thing,'' said Marty Hayden,  
political director of the Earthjustice Legal Defense Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House may have scored the most points on the debate  
over how to use the budget surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	With most of the package paid for out of the surplus, which for  
now comes entirely from Social Security, it will be harder for the 
GOP to find money for the tax cuts it wants. It will also be 
tougher for Republicans to assert they are protecting every penny 
of the pension program -- a claim they want to drum into voters' 
minds in time for next year's elections. 
</P>
<P>
	``Republicans adopted the same tax-and-spend-policy Democrats  
used for many years,'' said Stanley Collender, a budget analyst for 
Fleishman-Hilliard Inc., a consulting firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats may also benefit from something that did not happen.  
</P>
<P>
	Republican bargainers blocked an amendment by Sen. Tom Harkin  
D-Iowa, that would have added $5 billion in emergency farm aid. 
Though they lost the money, Democrats hope they can use the vote as 
an issue in the 2000 congressional races. 
</P>
</TEXT>
