<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 12:12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Blamed for Anti-Hate Law Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Democratic legislators are blaming Gov.  
George W. Bush for the failure of a Texas hate crimes bill that 
would protect homosexuals, saying the Republican presidential 
prospect has shown no leadership on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is named for James Byrd Jr., the black man dragged to  
death behind a pickup truck in East Texas, and has the backing of 
President Clinton and Democratic presidential candidate Bill 
Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	It would toughen the state's hate crimes law by increasing the  
criminal penalties. It would also specifically include homosexuals 
for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked repeatedly about the bill, Bush has said only: ``I will  
look at the bill when it makes it to my desk, if it makes it to my 
desk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Rodney Ellis, a Houston Democrat, has suggested that  
presidential politics is playing a role, with the sexual 
orientation provision a sticking point. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since our governor is a leading presidential hopeful, the eyes  
of the world are on Texas,'' Ellis said. ``Everything we do now 
takes on national implications.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill sailed through the Democratic-controlled House but has  
languished for weeks in a committee of the Republican-controlled 
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats failed twice Thursday night to force the bill to the  
full Senate for a vote. The deadline for Senate committees to 
consider bills was midnight Friday, and the Legislature adjourns 
May 31. 
</P>
<P>
	``I beg the governor, get involved in this issue as you do tax  
reform,'' Democratic Sen. John Whitmire said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants the world to believe that he is a `compassionate  
conservative.' We want the world to know that his compassion does 
not extend to all the citizens of Texas,'' said the Rev. Michael 
Piazza of Dallas' Cathedral of Hope, which claims the world's 
largest homosexual congregation. 
</P>
<P>
	Dianne Hardy-Garcia, executive director of the Lesbian and Gay  
Rights Lobby of Texas, attacked Bush's neutrality. ``His 
unconscionable, immoral lack of leadership on this issue is both 
tragic and exasperating,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 16:35:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Loyalties of Russia Army Unknown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- If Boris Yeltsin is counting on the support of  
Russia's security forces in his latest showdown with parliament, he 
may be in for a surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin has not suggested he would use force against lawmakers  
who are trying to impeach him -- as he did in a political 
confrontation in 1993 -- and analysts say he's unlikely to resort to 
violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet he may not even have that option, since it's unclear how  
loyal Russian troops and generals are to their increasingly 
unpopular, erratic president. But it's also unclear whether they 
would go to battle in support of Yeltsin's parliamentary foes. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's military and police forces are a huge question mark  
amid the country's political turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no loyalty to anyone,'' defense analyst Pavel  
Felgengauer said Friday. Besides, he added, Russian troops are so 
broke, poorly prepared and splintered that they may not be able to 
come to anyone's aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is technically government-less, since Yeltsin fired the  
prime minister and Cabinet on Wednesday. Perhaps foreseeing a 
potential need for military backing, Yeltsin chose a new candidate 
for premier with a long security background, Sergei Stepashin. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin had headed the Interior Ministry, which is in charge  
of Russia's police and internal security forces. But Russian media 
have said Stepashin does not enjoy unflagging support of the rank 
and file. 
</P>
<P>
	The lower house of Russia's parliament is holding an impeachment  
debate expected to come to a vote Saturday. Even if lawmakers 
approve the motion, it is unlikely to win passage by the country's 
two top courts and upper house. But it would step up the stakes in 
Yeltsin's long-running feud with his Communist enemies. 
</P>
<P>
	Rumors are rife that Yeltsin could try to call up troops if  
legislators continue to defy him, or if the opposition stages mass 
protests against his rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Observers say Yeltsin would probably turn first for support to  
his presidential guard, as well as the Interior Ministry's OMON 
internal security troops, who have come to his aid before. Special 
units from the Federal Security Service, the main intelligence 
agency and perhaps the elite paratrooper forces would also likely 
be called on. 
</P>
<P>
	But they may not all comply. Yeltsin angered the OMON last year  
by trimming their ranks for budgetary reasons, and analysts say the 
paratroopers have long resented the president for favoring other 
forces. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone will turn against him. His bodyguard won't even fight  
for him,'' Felgengauer said. ``They're not ready to spill blood for 
Yeltsin as (military leaders) were willing to do in 1993.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin dissolved a rebellious parliament in 1993, prompting  
lawmakers to hole themselves up in the parliamentary headquarters. 
Yeltsin forced them out by sending tanks and troops to bombard the 
building after opposition supporters rioted in Moscow. 
</P>
<P>
	Even then, Yeltsin had trouble persuading the military to back  
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Few seem eager to repeat that showdown.  
</P>
<P>
	``The Russian armed forces cannot be dragged into internal  
political processes,'' acting Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev told 
reporters Friday while reviewing Moscow's 27th Motorized Rifle 
Brigade. He insisted the visit was not connected to Russia's 
political instability. 
</P>
<P>
	Sergeyev is a Yeltsin ally, but is reportedly unpopular among  
the army brass. 
</P>
<P>
	Communist parliament speaker Gennady Seleznyov told reporters  
Friday: ``The army will never again interfere in political 
affairs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many are hoping things won't come to blows.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think people studied the experience of 1993, and won't let  
it happen again,'' said Vladimir Kozar, observer with the military 
newspaper Red Star. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no specific evidence that the security forces won't  
support Yeltsin. But I don't think anyone wants to find out,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	There has been no increased military presence around Moscow and  
no signs of unrest. 
</P>
<P>
	One reason for Yeltsin's predicament is the dire condition of  
Russia's military. Pay is extremely low and usually delayed, and 
morale is dismal. It is made up largely of conscripts, many of whom 
are unfit or undernourished. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the impeachment counts against Yeltsin is that he  
destroyed the once-mighty Soviet military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
