<DOCNO> APW19990514.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 08:13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Toddler Rescued From Well in Kansas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MULVANE, Kan. (AP) -- Twenty feet below ground, Tim Deneen  
feverishly clawed through the last few inches of dirt to reach 
17-month-old Jessy Kraus, who had slipped into a narrow well and 
become trapped. 
</P>
<P>
	The firefighter caressed the boy's tiny, mud-encrusted feet and  
told him: ``Hang in there, just a few more minutes.'' Jessy was too 
tired to weep after spending five hours 16 feet under the surface 
of his back yard. 
</P>
<P>
	In a dramatic rescue broadcast nationwide Thursday night, the  
little boy was pulled free with only minor injuries. There was a 
cheer from rescuers and neighbors as he was lifted free of the hole 
that the rescuers had dug alongside the well to safely reach him. 
</P>
<P>
	Jessy was whisked away to HCA Wesley Medical Center in Wichita  
within a few moments and was in good condition early today. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Curt Pickert said at a news conference this morning that  
Jessy ate scrambled eggs for breakfast and looked like a healthy 
toddler. He said the child suffered only a little hypothermia and 
superficial abrasions and should be released from the hospital 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy's parents, Karen and Jerry Kraus, thanked rescuers,  
supporters -- and God. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jessy gave me a smile last night,'' Mrs. Kraus said today at a  
hospital news conference. ``He's doing great today and he's going 
home.'' The couple, looking emotionally drained, held up photos of 
the boy for reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The ordeal -- reminiscent of that of a Texas toddler more than a  
decade ago -- began at 6:55 p.m. Thursday when the boy slipped into 
the well his parents were digging behind their home in Mulvane, 20 
miles south of Wichita. The dirt well, only 8 inches to 10 inches 
wide and 25 feet deep, was probably being dug to water the yard, 
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kraus saw his son fall in, but couldn't reach him in time,  
Sedgwick County Fire Marshal Greg Thompson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The distraught parents mostly stayed inside the house as rescue  
workers dug their hole seven feet from the well. Oxygen tubes were 
lowered into the well and warm air was pumped in to keep the boy 
from getting too cold. Lumber shored up the well's sides to prevent 
rocks and dirt from falling on the child. 
</P>
<P>
	As the crowd gathered, a video camera lowered into the well  
showed that Jessy's arm was pinned above his head, but he was 
moving and crying and appeared to be unhurt. The boy even tugged on 
a rope during the rescue. 
</P>
<P>
	Occasionally, Mrs. Kraus or the boy's grandmother would come  
talk to him from the top of the well. The mother was ``calming him 
... telling him that she loves him,'' Thompson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under emergency flood lights, about 50 emergency workers dug the  
shaft and then tunneled over to the well, 2 feet below the boy. As 
they got closer, they could hear him whimpering. 
</P>
<P>
	``My stomach was churning the whole time, knowing what he must  
be going through,'' said Deneen. 
</P>
<P>
	Deneen meticulously pulled more dirt away from the toddler's  
legs, comforting him as he worked to let him know someone was with 
him. Finally, he cleared enough space behind Jessy's head to insert 
a backboard. 
</P>
<P>
	His rough hands snagged Jessy's hair and the toddler screamed.  
Deneen apologized. Jessy tightly clenched his little fists and 
curled up his feet when Deneen strapped him into the board and neck 
brace. 
</P>
<P>
	Above ground, firefighters watched the drama unfold on a monitor  
linked to the video camera. Deneen handed the boy, clad in a 
T-shirt and shorts, to waiting firefighters in the rescue shaft and 
away he went. 
</P>
<P>
	Deneen, who brought up the boy's sandals, told reporters: ``He's  
out. We did it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Midland, Texas, in 1987, the case of 18-month-old Jessica  
McClure created a nationwide sensation. 
</P>
<P>
	She fell into an abandoned well and became trapped 22 feet down  
in a hole 8 inches wide. It took emergency crews 2 1/2 days to reach 
the little girl. They rescued her -- a dramatic moment covered on 
live television -- after digging a parallel shaft and then breaking 
through the wall of the well. 
</P>
<P>
	Jessica's parents, now divorced, have kept a low profile in the  
years since, saying they wanted the girl to have a normal 
childhood. They did give a magazine interview for the 10th 
anniversary, in which Jessica was described as a healthy, active 
11-year-old with no memory of the ordeal, who makes A's and B's at 
school, plays the piano and French horn and whizzes through her 
neighborhood on skates. 
</P>
<P>
	In Wichita this morning, Sedgwick County Fire Chief Gary Curmode  
said his first thought Thursday evening had been of the Midland 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we were lucky in that we didn't have the kind of soil they  
had in Texas,'' Curmode said on NBC's ``Today'' Show. Where the 
Midland rescuers had to cut through rock, the yard in Mulvane 
consisted of the soft clay typical of southeast Kansas, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, firefighters worried that heavy equipment could compact  
the ground, possibly endangering Jessy further, Curmode said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our strategy was to dig mainly by hand and use just hand  
tools,'' he said. The fiber-optic video camera, borrowed from a 
nearby company, was critical in helping rescuers assess Jessy's 
condition and placement, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Midland Assistant Fire Chief Eddie Klatt said this morning said  
the Kansas situation was ``kind of deja vu'' for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of strange to see something so close'' to what  
Jessica went through, he said, adding he was ``tickled to death'' 
to learn of Jessy's safe rescue . 
</P>
<P>
	He said he would tell the Kansas rescuers: ``Praise the Lord.  
Congratulations for a job well done.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
