<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor Testifies in Lewis Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Weeks before Reggie Lewis collapsed and died while  
practicing jump shots, his doctor told reporters the Boston Celtics 
star had a minor fainting condition that should not impede his 
basketball career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am optimistic that under medical supervision Mr. Reggie  
Lewis will be able to return to professional basketball without 
limitation,'' Gilbert Mudge said at a May 10, 1993, news conference 
marking Lewis' release from the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	A video of that news conference was played Thursday for jurors  
at Mudge's malpractice trial as Lewis' widow, Donna Harris-Lewis, 
wept. Harris-Lewis is suing the renowned cardiologist, who treated 
the All-Star in the months before he died. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis was 27 when he died of cardiac arrhythmia while practicing  
at Brandeis University 11 weeks after Mudge's news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking publicly for the first time since Lewis died, Mudge on  
Thursday testified his assessment that Lewis had neurocardiogenic 
syncope, a condition that causes fainting spells and is not related 
to the heart, was never a ``definitive diagnosis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge also said there were ``ongoing concerns'' Lewis might have  
a potentially fatal cardiac ailment. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet at the news conference -- and, according to Harris-Lewis, in  
private -- Mudge did not say he was concerned about a heart 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``After extensive testing, evaluation and review of all data, I  
believe that Mr. Lewis has a normal athlete's heart with normal 
functions,'' Mudge said then. ``Our testing showed no evidence of 
cardiomyopathy or abnormal life-threatening arrhythmias.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Harris-Lewis' attorney, Robert Harley, asked Mudge if he  
lied at the news conference, the doctor replied, ``What I did say 
was very limited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harley suggested that Mudge, suddenly in charge of care for  
``the most famous patient in Boston,'' was under pressure to tell 
Lewis, his wife, the Celtics and the public what they wanted to 
hear: that Lewis' condition was not as serious as first believed, 
and that he would play in the National Basketball Association 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	A team of 12 doctors at New England Baptist Hospital initially  
diagnosed Lewis with cardiac arrhythmia after he collapsed during a 
playoff game in April 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lewises turned to Mudge at Brigham and Women's Hospital for  
a second opinion, and he initially agreed. But after further tests, 
Mudge revised the diagnosis and told Lewis he had neurocardiogenic 
syncope. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis sued Mudge and consultants Mark Creager and Peter  
Friedman, claiming they misdiagnosed and mistreated her husband's 
heart condition. A third consultant later settled for an 
undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge was expected to continue testifying today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 17:16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Fundraises Down West Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Stepping off on a $3 million fund-raising sweep  
down the West Coast, President Clinton told Democratic contributors 
Friday that his 6 1/2 years in the White House have been ``a labor of 
love.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But if party patrons, who were paying as much as $25,000 for a  
weekend meal with Clinton, like the soaring stock market, they need 
to be concerned about who follows him in the White House, the 
president said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, I won't be on the ballot in 2000. This is the first  
time in a long time I haven't been on a ballot,'' Clinton told 
Democrats with a laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it is terribly important to me that everyone in America  
understand that this (economy), on the one hand, didn't happen by 
accident -- but on the other hand, is not dependent upon any person 
alone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What matters, he said, is that Democrats win.  
</P>
<P>
	Democratic National Committee Chairman Joe Andrew said Democrats  
were counting on the economy to carry them to victory in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``While Republicans quadrupled the national debt, our president  
quadrupled the Dow Jones,'' Andrew said. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the work that those of us in our administration have done  
in the last six years has been a labor of love,'' Clinton said. ``I 
literally get up and try to live with the spirit of gratitude every 
day for the good things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke at a $200,000 Seattle luncheon before heading to a  
$500,000 dinner in the San Francisco Bay area. The president's 
four-day take for Democrats -- with events also in Beverly Hills, 
San Diego and Las Vegas -- was expected to top $3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was sweeping up at least $2 million in Beverly Hills, at  
an event hosted by some of movie-making's biggest names: Steven 
Spielberg, David Geffen and Jeffrey Katzenberg. 
</P>
<P>
	His fund-raising trip drew criticism from Senate Majority Leader  
Trent Lott of Mississippi, who referred to the gun control debate 
unfolding in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	``This weekend, the Clinton-Gore regime will be begging for cash  
from one of the polluters responsible for our nation's moral 
decline,'' he said. ``What's the message to our children? Democrats 
care about your safety, unless it's inconvenient to their partners 
in Hollywood?'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 175 people gathered on two corners near the Seattle  
luncheon site to protest the Clinton administration's handling of 
allegations that China stole nuclear secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters held signs labeling the president ``Made in  
China,'' and asking, ``Didn't China pay you enough?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Up the street, another 75 people carried signs protesting the  
NATO airstrikes in Yugoslavia, ``Stop bombing Yugoslavia,'' one 
sign said, and ``NATO bombs can't bring peace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the Rainier Club, Clinton passionately defended the NATO  
campaign against Yugoslavia's ethnic cleansing in Kosovo and 
apologized once more for the alliance's accidental bombing of the 
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	After being frozen out for days by President Jiang Zemin,  
Clinton spoke with the Chinese leader by telephone before leaving 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made a terrible mistake in bombing the Chinese embassy and  
I regret it more than I can say. I talked to the president of China 
today and told him,'' Clinton reported. 
</P>
<P>
	He interspersed his frenetic fund raising with plenty of rest  
and relaxation, planning to spend Saturday relaxing with his 
daughter, Chelsea, near the Palo Alto, Calif., campus of Stanford 
University, where she is a sophomore. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday was reserved for the golf courses of Las Vegas.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 17:16:02 </DATE_TIME>
