<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat Down Sharply; Coffee Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Wheat futures fell sharply Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade  
as forecasts for an end to heavy rains in winter wheat growing 
regions ignited fears the crop could undergo a later growth surge. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, coffee futures rose sharply, while cocoa  
futures sank. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat erased initial gains amid renewed pessimism about whether  
world demand will be strong enough to cut into ample supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Improved growing weather in winter wheat regions this weekend  
may prove beneficial to the crop and could boost yields. Wheat 
futures had found some strength this week amid concern that heavy 
recent rains will continue and leave the crops vulnerable to 
disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Beneficial rains also were expected over the weekend in Chinese  
growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures this week also found a measure of support from  
government projections that the crop will be 14 percent smaller 
than last year's, but the U.S. Agriculture Department also 
predicted inventories will swell to their highest since 1987 as 
farmers continues to suffer from cheaper competing crops and weak 
demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices also were pressured Friday by talk the active July  
contract could fall to $2.10 a bushel before it expires. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 10 cents to $2.60 1/2 a bushel.  
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures rose sharply on Board of Trade of the City of New  
York amid forecasts for the second cold snap of the year in Brazil, 
the world's largest producer. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee prices during the Brazilian winter weather months are  
extremely sensitive to the idea of a damaging frost that could 
reduce the harvest. The most recent damaging frost occurred in 
1994, boosting prices 230 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil produced mainly robusta beans not favored by gourmet  
coffee drinkers, but its large crop often is mixed with arabica 
beans that are. 
</P>
<P>
	July arabica coffee rose 3.75 cents to $1.074 a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures sank the New York Board of Trade as sales of  
recently harvested crops picked up, adding to already plentiful 
world supplies. Bumper crops from Ivory Coast, Ghana and Indonesia 
have left chocolate makers content to sit on the sidelines as 
arrivals continue to pour in to key ports and they await lower 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, ample rainfall in West African growing regions were  
likely to aid the fall crop, agronomists said. 
</P>
<P>
	July cocoa fell $27 to $961 a ton.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
