<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Veterans Lose Out in Bid for Bar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) -- Trader Jon's, a storied hangout for  
aviators from the Pensacola Naval Air Station, is being sold to a 
New Jersey businessman, disappointing veterans who had wanted to 
buy and refurbish the ramshackle bar. 
</P>
<P>
	Relatives of owner Martin ``Trader Jon'' Weissman signed a  
contract on Thursday to turn the place over to John Cave, a former 
Army drill sergeant who owns a small airport and entertainment 
complex in Lumberton, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is to become final within a month, after Cave inspects  
the bar, which needs thousands of dollars in repairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Cave, 52, gave assurances he will preserve the bar's character,  
including the rare aviation memorabilia. ``I have no intention of 
doing anything else,'' he said. ``That's the only reason I wanted 
to get involved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trader Jon's has been a favorite of naval aviators since it  
opened in the early 1950s. It was the model for the bar featured in 
the movie ``An Officer and a Gentleman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bar is filled with pictures, model airplanes, flight suits,  
aircraft parts and other aviation artifacts. It includes an 
adjoining building Weissman turned into a Blue Angels museum to 
honor the precision flying team, based at Pensacola. 
</P>
<P>
	Trader Jon's closed earlier this year. It had been open on and  
off ever since Weissman, 83, suffered a paralyzing stroke in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Two former aviators had formed the nonprofit Trader Jon  
Preservation Squadron to make a bid for the bar, raising more than 
$200,000 through hat and T-shirt sales. But Weissman's family 
turned down an offer made last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're stunned,'' said Bob Stumpf, a former Blue Angels flight  
leader and retired Navy commander who helped make the bid. He said 
he and his partner, Kent Bolin, a former Marine helicopter pilot, 
``really in our hearts had Trader Jon's best interests in mind.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
