<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Yelstin Debate Dominates Duma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Whether inside or outside Russia's parliament, the  
anti-Yeltsin din on Friday was both loud and scorching. 
</P>
<P>
	In the legislative chamber, hard-liners in the State Duma,  
parliament's lower house, disparaged President Boris Yeltsin -- 
sometimes in the loftiest of terms. 
</P>
<P>
	``Impeaching the president is the moral duty of every deputy,''  
Communist Svetlana Goryacheva told other legislators. 
</P>
<P>
	Other lawmakers weren't so high-minded, excoriating the  
68-year-old leader with bitingly personal attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The very image of that person -- his expression, his gestures --  
radiates a threat,'' actor and ex-Culture Minister Nikolai Gubenko 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the White House, the elephantine marble edifice where  
the Duma's chambers are located, Yeltsin's foes also had a field 
day. They chanted and waved red flags, drowning out the paltry 
crowd of Yeltsin supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The hearings began Thursday on a dull, almost soporific note,  
but the second day brought a series of impassioned speeches. Most 
spoke in favor of impeachment, and many mentioned the bloody 
1994-96 war in Chechnya as the key charge against Yeltsin. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has money for everything ... except for burying the last  
soldiers killed in Chechnya. If only for that, he should be 
impeached,'' said Stanislav Govorukhin, a filmmaker, whose screed 
against Yeltsin was frequently interrupted with applause. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't you hear the wail of entire Russia -- free us from him,  
save our children!'' the mustachioed Govorukhin implored. 
</P>
<P>
	Apocalypse was on Vladimir Lysenko's tongue. In perhaps the most  
unexpected and impassioned speech of the day, the lawmaker charged 
Yeltsin with betraying democratic ideals and urged him to resign 
immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tomorrow might be too late,'' Lysenko said.  
</P>
<P>
	For sheer political theater, the prize may have gone to  
ultranationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky. Long known for angry and 
dramatic outbursts, he grabbed the Duma's attention as Communist 
opponents and even speaker Gennady Seleznyov tried in vain to 
silence him. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhirinovsky first demanded to speak alone for the entire 28  
minutes given to four of his party lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Duma voted down the proposal, after which each of  
Zhirinovsky's allies surrendered his time to the leader -- claiming 
inability to speak because of upset stomachs or sore throats. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you, the best 450 people in the great country of Russia,  
are afraid of me, I must be the greatest man on Earth,'' 
Zhirinovsky told the lawmakers. ``Well, we'll continue tomorrow. 
You shall all go crazy tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Behind the scene, Zhirinovsky has been negotiating with the  
Kremlin over posts in a new Cabinet. In a rambling speech before 
the cameras, however, he left subtlety behind, urging the Duma to 
end debate and unite against common foes -- NATO and the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	``World War III against Russia may start in June,'' shouted  
Zhirinovsky. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 08:31:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Passes Gun Background Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reversing a position taken earlier in the  
week, Senate Republicans pushed through a provision today they 
claimed would establish a system of background checks for all 
buyers of firearms at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	But even in advance of the 48-47 vote, President Clinton and  
Senate Democrats cited numerous loopholes and Republicans agreed to 
consider further changes. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote came after a clash over the role the National Rifle  
Association has played in the legislation, which was brought to the 
Senate floor less than a month after the Columbine High School 
shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., accused Republicans of faking an  
effort to pass tougher gun laws, at the behest of the NRA. 
</P>
<P>
	``National Rifle Association hasn't had a thing to do with it,''  
snapped the Senate Judiciary Committee chairman, Sen. Orrin Hatch, 
sponsor of the legislation. ``I don't care whether they accept it 
or not'' said the Utah Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch and other Republicans struggled to amass a majority,  
lobbying GOP colleagues on the Senate floor as the roll call 
proceeded. In the end, 47 Republicans and Sen. Robert Byrd, 
D-W.Va., supported the proposal, while 40 Democrats and seven 
Republicans opposed it. 
</P>
<P>
	The uncertainty on the Senate floor -- lawmakers voting on a  
proposal that everyone knew would be changed later -- underscored 
the political stakes involved in the gun-control debate in the 
aftermath of the Colorado shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes after the background-check vote, the Senate killed  
Schumer's amendment, 50-43. It would have required Web sites 
selling guns to be federally licensed. 
</P>
<P>
	Prodded by some in their own ranks, Republicans offered  
concessions on the background check amendment Thursday, but Clinton 
ridiculed the proposals today. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new Senate Republican bill is still riddled with  
high-caliber loopholes,'' the president said at the White House. 
``It won't stop criminals from buying guns at gun shows. At the 
same time, it will open up a new pawnshop loophole that lets 
convicted felons get guns at a local pawnshop. That's actually 
worse than current law. I simply can't believe the Senate will make 
the same mistake twice. 
</P>
<P>
	``So, once again, I ask them to reject this phony proposal and  
to pass real legislation that requires the background checks 
necessary to prevent criminals from buying guns at gun shows which 
they cannot buy at gun stores,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republicans' abrupt U-turn underscored the shift in the gun-  
control debate following last month's shooting spree in Littleton, 
Colo., that left 14 high school students and a teacher dead. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the Senate agreed to prohibit the import of  
high-capacity ammunition clips not included in a 1994 assault 
weapons ban. An effort to kill the measure was rejected, 59-39, 
with almost all votes in opposition cast by Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats called it a victory over the NRA.  
</P>
<P>
	``The NRA said no and it passed anyway,'' Sen. Dianne Feinstein,  
D-Calif., said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate also agreed to a proposal by Sen. John Ashcroft,  
R-Mo., to ban juvenile possession of semiautomatic weapons and 
high-capacity ammunition clips. That vote was 96-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite this week's action, a big backlog of amendments  
threatened to derail Hatch's underlying bill, which would stiffen 
prosecution standards for juvenile offenders. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in such a doggone log jam here that we might have to  
pull this bill down,'' Hatch, R-Utah, sputtered from the floor late 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate on Wednesday approved an amendment by Sen. Larry  
Craig, R-Idaho, to make instant background checks of private sales 
at gun shows voluntary. But a half-dozen Republicans later 
complained to Craig, a member of the NRA's board of directors, that 
his amendment should go further to ensure that background checks 
are performed even in private sales at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Several GOP sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said  
private polling in recent weeks has shown very strong support for 
gun control, even among potential voters in Republican presidential 
primaries. That is a marked shift from the past, in which base GOP 
voters were less supportive of gun control than the nation as a 
whole. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration also pounced on Wednesday's vote.  
Clinton, joined by Attorney General Janet Reno in some of the 
harshest terms she's used on congressional action, accused the 
Senate of ignoring the threat highlighted less than a month earlier 
by the shootings at Columbine High School. 
</P>
<P>
	By midafternoon Thursday, Craig announced that he would propose  
an amendment that would require background checks for all transfers 
of firearms at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats at first rejoiced. But later, they accused Craig of  
not strengthening gun laws. Democrats said Craig's new proposal 
still would leave a group of people who would not be required to do 
background checks of purchasers. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig disagreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Every gun transfer at gun shows would have a background check  
performed,'' Craig told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics also said that under Craig's new proposal, a sale would  
be approved automatically if the background check was not completed 
within 24 hours, rather than the three days in current law. They 
also said the proposal would continue to allow an individual to 
pawn a gun and reclaim it without undergoing a background check. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans who voted no on today's 48-47 vote: Sens. John  
Chafee of Rhode Island, Mike Enzi of Wyoming, Peter Fitzgerald of 
Illinois, Bob Smith of New Hampshire, Craig Thomas of Wyoming, Fred 
Thompson of Tennessee and John Warner of Virginia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
