<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Acting Russia P.M. Sets Out Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Boris Yeltsin's nominee for prime minister  
announced plans Friday for a new government, including measures 
designed to help the country out of its economic crisis and win 
approval from the State Duma, parliament's lower house. 
</P>
<P>
	Sergei Stepashin, a staunch Yeltsin ally, will face a tough  
battle for confirmation in the Duma, dominated by Communists and 
hostile to the Russian president. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin was appointed acting prime minister Wednesday after  
Yeltsin ousted Yevgeny Primakov from the job. On Thursday, 
parliament began impeachment hearings against Yeltsin. 
</P>
<P>
	The Duma will hold its vote on Stepashin's nomination next week.  
If he is rejected three times, Yeltsin is required by law to 
dissolve parliament and new elections will be held. 
</P>
<P>
	Vladimir Ryzhkov, a pro-Kremlin lawmaker, saw little chance that  
Stepashin would be confirmed as prime minister. ``People who are 
sure he will be approved the first time around are living in a 
parallel universe,'' he said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	However, former prime minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said he  
believed Stepashin would ultimately be confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	``He will pass through the State Duma, and it does not matter at  
which time,'' Chernomyrdin told the ITAR-Tass news agency. ``It 
would be desirable to have the earliest approval.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gennady Zyuganov, the Communist leader, said Stepashin would  
meet with the leaders of several parties on Tuesday to discuss his 
agenda for taking the country out of its political and economic 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Zyuganov, who said he had not been offered a job in the new  
government, was asked how Communist deputies will vote on 
Stepashin's nomination. ``It's too early to guess,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin met with his staff on Friday and set out a three-part  
program for his new government, the Interfax news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	First, the government ``must guarantee the speedy approval of  
the package of economic bills drafted by the government of Yevgeny 
Primakov,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the bills are not passed, or if the new Cabinet is not  
approved, all existing and future agreements with international 
lending institutions, including the International Monetary Fund and 
the World Bank, would be threatened. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Monetary Fund has tentatively agreed to lend  
Russia $4.5 billion, but is waiting for parliament to pass a 
legislative package on economic policy before disbursing the first 
installment. 
</P>
<P>
	The second task for the government would be drafting the budget  
for the year 2000. The third proposal was for the government to 
assure the payment of wages, pensions and subsidies to the 
provinces, Interfax said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin said many members of his new government would be  
holdovers from Primakov's Cabinet. ``The backbone of the Cabinet 
will undoubtedly remain, and there will be no overhaul,'' he said, 
according to Interfax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
