<DOCNO> APW19990514.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 01:22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Martinez Pays Off For Red Sox </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- When the Boston Red Sox made Pedro Martinez the  
highest-paid player in baseball history in November 1997, general 
manager Dan Duquette thought he had the best pitcher in baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	It looks like Duquette was right.  
</P>
<P>
	Boston's Martinez has the most wins and strikeouts in the major  
leagues and he doesn't appear to be slowing down. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez (7-1) is off to one of the best starts of his career,  
and his 91 strikeouts leads the majors. Randy Johnson is second 
with 78. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the best I've seen in all my years,'' Seattle designated  
hitter Edgar Martinez said. ``I faced Roger Clemens in his early 
years and Nolan Ryan. They were tough, but Pedro is better. He's 
very tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With his 15-strikeout, 9-2 win over the Mariners on Wednesday  
night, Martinez tied a record for the most strikeouts in three 
consecutive nine inning games with 43. He struck out every Seattle 
starter -- including Ken Griffey Jr. and Jay Buhner three times each 
-- except John Mabry. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez also struck out 15 on May 7 against Oakland and 13 on  
May 1 against Anaheim. Dwight Gooden of the New York Mets had 43 
strikeouts from Sept. 7-17 in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a strong performance,'' Red Sox manager Jimy Williams  
said. ``They have an outstanding club with a lot of power. When you 
talk about being overpowering and striking out a lot of people -- at 
this level -- it's hard to do. I've seen some other teams, but I 
haven't seen the kind of power this man has.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez had nine strikeouts in each of his first two games and  
reached double figures for the sixth straight start -- a feat only 
he and Johnson have accomplished since 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1997 National League Cy Young Award winner also had six  
straight games with 10 or more strikeouts with Montreal in June of 
that year. Johnson did it with Seattle last June 19-July 16. 
Martinez also had his best start in 1997, when he went 8-0. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, he allowed two runs, four hits and one walk in  
eight innings. Martinez, whose ERA is 1.81, didn't allow a hit in 
the first four innings, striking out nine with a nasty changeup and 
an overpowering fastball before David Segui's leadoff double in the 
fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 59 2-3 innings he has pitched since April 7, Martinez has  
yielded only 11 walks. The most he has walked in a game is three. 
</P>
<P>
	When was the last time the Mariners' Martinez had seen a pitcher  
so dominant? 
</P>
<P>
	``The last time we played him,'' Edgar Martinez said. ``He has  
three quality pitches with great control. Nobody intimidates him. 
He feels like he is running the show -- and he did (Wednesday) 
night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``So far this year, I've been healthy,'' Pedro Martinez said.  
``I've been making my pitches and I happen to get away with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's good for the Red Sox, whose other starters have  
struggled. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez hopes to continue to please the Fenway Park crowd,  
which booed when Williams made his first trip to the mound after 
Martinez had thrown 125 pitches, 83 for strikes. The fans, many of 
whom wave Dominican Republic flags in the stands when Martinez 
pitches, hoped to see the ace surpass his career high 15 strikeouts 
before being lifted from the game. 
</P>
<P>
	But that will have to come another day.  
</P>
<P>
	``I just pray that I can keep it going, that I can give them  
that strikeout whenever they root for it,'' Martinez said. ``I know 
it's not always going to be like that. But I'm always going to try 
to please them whenever they ask for it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
