<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> At Home, Microsoft in Cable Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. will partner with At  
Home Corp. to help small and medium-sized cable companies provide 
high-speed Internet connections for customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft will become a strategic technology partner in At Home  
Solutions, a private venture that uses At Home's nationwide 
network. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, based in Redmond, Wash., will contribute its Window  
NT Server operating system and support and resources to assist in 
marketing the service, the companies said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Sources close to the deal said Microsoft's investment was worth  
$5 million, The Wall Street Journal reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	At Home estimates 15 million homes and businesses are served by  
smaller, local cable companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We very much welcome Microsoft's involvement, which will help  
us to establish At Home Solutions as the clear broadband leader in 
the small and mid-sized cable markets,'' said At Home Solutions 
chairman Dean A. Gilbert. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft and the Redwood City-based At Home had been seen as  
rivals since they both operate Internet portal sites. 
</P>
<P>
	3Com Corp., Cisco Systems Inc., Motorola Inc. and Falcon  
Communications Inc. are also investors in At Home Solutions. 


</P>
</TEXT>
