<DOCNO> APW19990514.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 00:12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Silverbulletday Pulled From Pimlico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- No one will ever confuse the Black-Eyed Susan  
Stakes for the Preakness. They're as different as lining up against 
the rail and running from the 14th post position. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Pegram, the owner of Silverbulletday, would have preferred  
seeing his filly run in the prestigious Preakness. But after his 
horse drew the 14th post, Pegram pulled her from the race and 
entered Silverbulletday in today's Black-Eyed Susan, a 1 1/8-mile race 
for 3-year-old fillies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hurts, but it was the right thing to do. It was really  
unexpected, though,'' Pegram said Thursday. ``We had to look at the 
book to see how far the Black-Eyed Susan was. She was entered, but 
I never thought of anything but the Preakness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday, winner of 10 of 11 career races, was the  
overwhelming 1-5 early favorite in the $200,000 Black-Eyed Susan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to take care of her,'' trainer Bob Baffert said. ``With  
the good ones, you've got to be so careful. This was a hard 
decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Black-Eyed Susan essentially served as an insurance policy  
for both the fillies he brought from Kentucky to Pimlico. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert would have preferred to saddle Silverbulletday and  
Excellent Meeting for the Preakness. But only Excellent Meeting 
will run Saturday -- from the No. 7 spot. 
</P>
<P>
	The Grade II Black-Eyed Susan shapes up as Silverbulletday and  
seven other horses. Silverbulletday, coming off a dominant victory 
in the Grade I Kentucky Oaks, has won seven straight. 
</P>
<P>
	Dreams Gallore, who finished second in the Kentucky Oaks, and  
Madison's Charm opened at 6-1. 
</P>
<P>
	The Happy Hopper, who won the Dixie Belle and Martha Washington  
Stakes at Oaklawn Park and finished second behind Excellent Meeting 
in the Fantasy, is also considered to be a contender. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner of the race will receive $120,000. Other entrants  
are: Mysterious Jak, who hasn't run outside of Maryland this year; 
Waltz, who has won two of three races in 1999; Vee Vee Star and 
Magic Broad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
