<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Plot in Embassy Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- From irate workers who hurled bits of concrete at  
the U.S. Embassy for four days to sophisticated scholars of 
international affairs, Chinese are embracing a slew of conspiracy 
theories over NATO's bombing of their embassy in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	For many, the missiles that slammed into the building in  
Belgrade symbolized a 100-year struggle to build a modern country 
in the face of bullying from foreign powers. Thrown into the mix 
are deep pride in China's long civilization and shame that it lags 
behind the West technologically. 
</P>
<P>
	The communist government has kept those emotions raw through  
five decades of propaganda outlining what it maintains are the 
humiliations visited on China by predatory foreigners. The 
leadership has urged Chinese to build a strong country that can 
never be humiliated again. 
</P>
<P>
	Western powers led by the United States are ``using all methods,  
including political, economic, military and diplomatic means to 
obstruct and destroy China's development,'' the People's Daily, the 
Communist Party's most authoritative newspaper, said in a 
commentary Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Far from accidental, the NATO bombing was a provocation to see a  
``united, advanced, hope-filled China pushed into chaos and an 
abyss,'' the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Books and media reports that have railed against the United  
States off and on for the past decade have resonated with the 
public. From what China maintains were questionable calls that kept 
it from winning gold at the Atlanta Olympics to hectoring about 
human rights, many feel the United States has frustrated China's 
rise and overlooked progress in improving living standards and 
personal freedoms. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout NATO's air campaign, the entirely state-controlled  
media have focused on the U.S. role and civilian casualties in the 
airstrikes, while scarcely mentioning the killings and expulsions 
of ethnic Albanians in Yugoslavia's Kosovo province. 
</P>
<P>
	When NATO mistakenly attacked the Chinese Embassy on May 7,  
strong nationalist feelings unified China's people behind its 
government. Biased media coverage and partial, changing 
explanations from NATO fed a belief that the West wasn't telling 
the truth. 
</P>
<P>
	As students, workers and others poured into the streets last  
Saturday, a mix of propaganda, patriotism, indignation and 
suspicion generated an array of conspiracy theories in the official 
media. 
</P>
<P>
	According to one, the United States wants to use the Yugoslav  
war to dominate Europe and then move on to Russia and China. 
Another says the embassy bombing was designed to push China into 
blocking recent peace moves in the United Nations and give NATO 
more time to pummel Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Either way, the bombing was seen as a test of China's resolve.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is part of the United States' global strategy,'' said  
foreign policy expert Shen Jiru. ``The United States thinks we're 
weak and believes it will be unbeatable for another 15 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leading newspapers carried articles last week asking  
incredulously how U.S. spy satellites, the most advanced in the 
world, could have failed to recognize the prominent Chinese Embassy 
with its red flag flying. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people still question the explanation that it was an  
accident. Not because they have any hard evidence of conspiracy, 
but because the current evidence supplied by NATO and the United 
States is very shaky so far,'' said Jia Qingguo, a professor of 
international studies at Peking University. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was definitely done on purpose. How could it be anything  
else? They were using the most sophisticated weapons. This was 
Clinton's attempt to keep China down,'' said one protester taking a 
break from hurling bits of broken concrete at the British Embassy 
last Sunday. When asked his name, he replied ``Man of China.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Entertainment and news programs backed up the image of a China  
standing firm. 
</P>
<P>
	A memorial concert for the three journalists killed in the  
bombing was held Thursday night in the southern city of Shenzhen 
and broadcast by Hong Kong's Phoenix Television, which is widely 
viewed in southern and eastern China. 
</P>
<P>
	The concert, titled ``Today the Chinese can say No,'' featured  
refutations of NATO's explanation interspersed with pop songs and 
dances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
