<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Faults 2 US Tobacco Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- U.S. tobacco giant Phillip Morris,  
responding to pressure from government officials, says it is doing 
all it can to attack the sale of contraband cigarettes in Colombia. 
</P>
<P>
	The country's governors are threatening to file suit in a U.S.  
court against the maker of Marlboro cigarettes and British American 
Tobacco -- the two leading exporters of cigarettes to Colombia. The 
governors allege the companies are avoiding hundreds of millions of 
dollars in sales taxes by intentionally fostering illegal imports 
and sales of their cigarettes. 
</P>
<P>
	Miguel Raad, the governor of northern Bolivar State and head of  
the national governors' association, said Wednesday the companies 
``have collaborated by action or omission'' in illegal cigarette 
sales which cost the government as much as $305 million annually. 
</P>
<P>
	States levy a 48 percent sales tax on imported cigarettes,  
however the widespread contraband sales mean that taxes are evaded. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Cho, a spokesperson for Phillip Morris International  
in New York, said Thursday the company has tried to discourage 
contraband sales through advertising campaigns helping Colombians 
identify black market cigarettes and by tightening controls through 
its distributors. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem, however, is largely the Colombian government's to  
resolve, she said. ``We don't have either the resources of the 
authority to substitute ourselves for the customs administration, 
border security forces or the law enforcement departments of any 
country,'' Cho said by telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	British American Tobacco, which distributes Kent, Kool, Belmont  
and Free cigarettes in Colombia, did not return several telephone 
calls to its Bogota offices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
