<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baltimore Mourns Loss of 'Homicide' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- ``Homicide: Life on the Streets'' gave John  
Wayne Smyth the chance to spread his wings as an actor. It wasn't 
much of a stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	The bartender was hired six times as an extra on the NBC drama  
that was set and shot in Baltimore. His biggest role was a 
90-second appearance as a bar patron. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was typecasting,'' Smyth said as he nursed a hangover at  
The Cat's Eye Pub, across the street from the show's made-for-TV 
police station. Come to think of it, he had a hangover when the 
scene was shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just nice memories,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Residents of Baltimore will have only memories of ``Homicide''  
from now on. The critically acclaimed but consistently low-rated 
show was canceled on Thursday after seven seasons. The last episode 
will air May 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Belzer, who played the cynical yet surprisingly likable  
Detective John Munch, said the network based its decision to cancel 
the show, which won three Peabody awards, on the bottom line -- 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were always on the edge and always the critical favorite  
and had a great core audience that seemed to be there. But the 
brutal dollars and cents reality of television today... it didn't 
come down to artistic content but financial reality. It wasn't 
making enough money,'' Belzer said Friday, speaking from his home 
in France. 
</P>
<P>
	The show made a lot of money for Baltimore, about $28 million a  
year. It also brought people to Baltimore, and the colorful 
waterfront neighborhood of Fells Point where much of the show was 
filmed. Between 80 and 100 extras were hired per show. 
</P>
<P>
	Sona Gandhi-Brown, leasing manager of the upscale Henderson  
Wharf's apartments where several cast members lived, now must try 
to find renters for seven or eight units at $2,200 a month. She 
said that's pretty pricey for Baltimore, even for the waterfront. 
</P>
<P>
	But the city's affection for the show and the crew's love for  
Baltimore went beyond economics. 
</P>
<P>
	David Burman owns the Waterfront Hotel and Restaurant, the bar  
that Munch and Detective Meldrick Lewis ``owned'' in the show. He 
said he will miss ``Homicide'' because the business got paid every 
time the show took it over to shoot a scene. Not to mention the 
patrons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to miss it. We got a lot of people from all over the  
country, from Europe, from Australia. They just want to come here 
and see the `Homicide' bar,'' said Burman, who sells black T-shirts 
with the image of a chalk outline of a body and the logo: 
``Homicide Witnessed at the Waterfront.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Fontana, the show's executive producer along with Hollywood  
movie producer Barry Levinson, said filming every one of the 122 
episodes in Baltimore brought the show realism. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that just by the nature of the fact it wasn't being  
shot on a back lot in Los Angeles, it allowed the city to be a full 
character on the show,'' he said. ``We showed the city as a 
breathing, living thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Producer David Simon, a former (Baltimore) Sun reporter who took  
a year off from the paper in 1988 to research ``Homicide: A Year on 
the Killing Streets,'' on which the drama was based, said there 
were concerns the series would make Baltimore look bad. They soon 
disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	``You would think it improbable that a show that is about murder  
and violence, and morality confronting immorality, would reflect 
well on a city, but somehow it did,'' Simon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Housekeeper Shirley Williams took the cancellation news hard.  
She cleaned for several cast members and is especially fond of 
Clark Johnson, who played Lewis, because he insisted on getting a 
hug from her each morning before he went off to the set. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of superstars are arrogant,'' she said. ``They were down  
to earth ... They drank in the bars around here, they mingled, they 
socialized.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said now he's going to have to find another place to  
berth his sailboat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Baltimore was such a part of the show. The city was more  
important than any of us actors,'' Johnson said. ``I think 
Baltimore is really going to miss us.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
