<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Need for Finance Aid Wanes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand might not have to withdraw the  
remaining $4.25 billion available under its $17.2 billion rescue 
program from the International Monetray Fund, a top finance 
ministry official said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Ministry permanent secretary Suppachai Pisitvanich said  
that International Monetary Fund officials told him the Thai 
government has made progress in reviving the economy and can soon 
graduate from the program. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, he said he doesn't think Thailand will have to  
withdraw any more from the IMF program. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision rests with the central bank and Finance Minister  
Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thailand accepted the rescue program in August 1997, one month  
after the government abandoned its fixed foreign exchange system, 
triggering financial turmoil in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	The Thai government's most recent withdrawal was $490 million  
from the program in April, leaving $4.25 billion available. 
</P>
<P>
	The government now has other sources for its borrowing, such as  
Japan's Miyazawa regional aid fund and the World Bank's aid 
programs, Suppachai said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry is expected to conclude this round of IMF  
discussions next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
