<HEADLINE> Hercules' Star To Blast Into Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Hercules is blasting into space.  
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Sorbo, star of TV's ``Hercules: The Legendary Journeys,''  
will trade mythology for a science fiction-action series based on 
the work of the late ``Star Trek'' creator Gene Roddenberry. 
</P>
<P>
	The new syndicated series, expected to debut in the fall of  
2000, is being developed by Roddenberry's widow, Majel Barrett 
Roddenberry, with Tribune Entertainment Co. and Sorbo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since my pre-teen days, I have been a fan of Mr. Roddenberry  
and the worlds he created in `Star Trek,''' Sorbo said. ``I guess 
you could say I'm trading the past for the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two Roddenberry projects are under development. Sorbo can choose  
which he wants to star in. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gene Roddenberrry's Andromeda'' is about a scientist on a  
distant planet who is inadvertently transported 500 years into the 
future. The other show, ``Gene Roddenberry's Starship,'' tells the 
adventures of an exploratory space vessel. 
</P>
<P>
	Sorbo's ``Hercules'' will wrap its five-year run in December.  
</P>
</TEXT>
