<HEADLINE> Former POW To Throw Out Pitch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- A parade, belated birthday party -- and, now, the  
Houston Astros. 
</P>
<P>
	Army Spc. Steven Gonzales, one of three American soldiers held  
captive 32 days by Yugoslav authorities, is set to throw out the 
ceremonial first pitch at Sunday's game against the San Francisco 
Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Astros are privileged to have the opportunity to honor an  
American hero,'' owner Drayton McLane said Friday. ``Specialist 
Gonzales has inspired us all through his remarkable courage, 
bravery and steadfast patriotism through a difficult and 
challenging ordeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzales, who grew up in Palestine, returned to Texas May 7  
after Yugoslav authorities released the POWs. He has been spending 
some quiet time at his parents' home in Huntsville. 
</P>
<P>
	That city is planning a parade and a birthday party for Gonzales  
on May 22. The solider turned 22 while in captivity. 
</P>
