<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rules on Race, Border Stops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Border Patrol agents can consider ethnicity  
when they make traffic stops, a federal appeals court ruled in a 
case involving two Hispanic men who turned their cars around to 
avoid a checkpoint. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling comes at a time when the use ethnic background as the  
basis for traffic stops is receiving increasing attention across 
the country. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 2-1 ruling, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on  
Thursday upheld the detention of two Hispanic men stopped 50 miles 
inside the United States after they tried to avoid a highway 
checkpoint. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said it was appropriate that among the things the  
officers considered in making the stop was the fact the men turned 
around, and that they were Hispanic. 
</P>
<P>
	Writing for the majority, visiting U.S. District Judge Frank C.  
Damrell of Fresno pointed to a Supreme Court decision in a 1975 
case, in which the court listed a number of things the police could 
consider in such an instance. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them were the character of the area; nearness to the  
border; traffic patterns; previous smuggling problems in the area, 
the officer's experience; and the behavior of the passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	After a motorist told authorities that two cars with Mexican  
plates turned around a mile from the checkpoint, they were stopped. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents searched the cars of German Espinoza Montero-Camargo and  
Lorenzo Sanchez-Guillen and found two large bags of marijuana and a 
.32-caliber pistol. The men were charged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 10:12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Witness Shows Crack in 'Blue Wall' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- He's just one cop, sitting in one courtroom,  
testifying in one case. But Detective Eric Turetzky's testimony 
against fellow cops in the alleged torture of a Haitian immigrant 
signifies a crack in the so-called ``blue wall of silence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He's doing what all police officers should do, but it takes a  
great deal of courage to do it,'' Police Commissioner Howard Safir 
said Thursday as Turetzky spent a second day on the stand in the 
explosive case. 
</P>
<P>
	The 28-year-old Turetzky was an eyewitness to what federal  
prosecutors say was a brutal attack on Abner Louima in the bathroom 
of the 70th Precinct stationhouse two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Four police officers are accused of violating Louima's civil  
rights by beating and sexually brutalizing him following a brawl at 
a Brooklyn nightclub. The officers were allegedly upset that one 
had been punched in the melee. A fifth officer is accused of 
covering up the beating. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors have used testimony by Turetzky in a bid to bolster  
Louima's claim that Officer Charles Schwarz held him down on the 
bathroom floor while Officer Justin Volpe rammed a broken broom 
handle into his rectum. 
</P>
<P>
	Louima, who is black, suffered a ruptured colon and bladder. The  
case sent shockwaves through the city and strained already 
difficult relations between police and New York City's minority 
community. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys have tried to portray Turetzky as an  
opportunist, pointing out that the former patrolman was promoted to 
detective for cooperating with the investigation into the case. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point Thursday, defense attorney Stephen Worth asked  
Turetzky: ``Do you consider yourself a hero cop who's broken the 
`blue wall of silence?''' 
</P>
<P>
	``No, sir,'' Turetzky said, later adding, ``I came forward to  
say what happened. ... It was my duty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not every police officer shares that sentiment. Often, critics  
say, officers refuse to testify against other cops -- the ``blue 
wall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Usually, everyone is Sgt. Schultz from `Hogan's Heroes' -- `I  
know nothing, I saw nothing,''' said lawyer Ron Kuby, a frequent 
police critic. ``Those not willing to actually come forward and lie 
in defense of their brutal brethren usually suffer memory 
failure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Turetzky had his memory challenged Thursday. The officer was  
confronted with evidence that he changed key parts of his story 
about the night of Aug. 9, 1997, when police arrested Louima. 
</P>
<P>
	He also admitted threatening to kick a pregnant woman in the  
stomach for refusing to leave the scene. But he did it with 
composure, sitting straight and addressing combative defense 
attorneys as ``sir.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Reppetto, head of the watchdog Citizens Crime Commission,  
suggested that the ``blue wall'' was never as absolute as some 
suggest. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have always been officers willing to speak up,''  
Reppetto said, harking back to Frank Serpico's landmark testimony 
before the Knapp Commission. ``Perhaps there have not been as many 
as there should have been.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Serpico was a plainclothes officer who was labeled a traitor by  
many of his colleagues in the 1970s for turning in crooked cops. 
His story was turned into a best-selling book and a hit movie, both 
called ``Serpico.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two decades later, he surfaced at the Mollen Commission's police  
corruption probe and criticized the department. After 20 years, he 
said, few bricks were missing from the ``wall of silence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mollen Commission had no Serpico-esque do-gooders -- just  
cops who publicly implicated their fellow crooks. Kuby said a lack 
of police cooperation is often responsible for crooked cops going 
free. 
</P>
<P>
	``Almost every police case that has failed has failed in large  
part because the blue wall has held,'' Kuby said, citing the 1983 
slaying of graffiti artist Michael Stewart as a perfect example. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart died after his 1983 arrest in a Manhattan subway  
station. Although 11 officers were in the station and a half-dozen 
were indicted in the incident, no one was ever convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eleven officers,'' Kuby said. ``And none of them came  
forward.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
