<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Hero Cop' in Louima Case Attacked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The detective who prosecutors say shattered a  
police code of silence in the alleged bathroom torture of a 
prisoner denied Thursday that he talked to save himself and gain 
glory. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do you consider yourself a hero cop who's broken the `blue  
wall of silence'?'' defense attorney Stephen Worth asked Detective 
Eric Turetzky during cross-examination at the brutality trial of 
five fellow officers. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, sir,'' Turetzky said, adding later, ``I came forward to  
say what happened. ... It was my duty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four police officers are accused of beating Abner Louima  
following a brawl at a Brooklyn nightclub. Two of the officers are 
accused of using a broom handle to sodomize Louima, a Haitian 
immigrant, in a precinct bathroom. A fifth officer is charged with 
covering up the beating. 
</P>
<P>
	The brutal nature of the allegations shocked many and has  
strained relations between police and minorities. The accused 
officers are white; Louima is black. 
</P>
<P>
	A multimillion-dollar lawsuit filed on Louima's behalf alleges  
rogue cops were shielded by the ``blue wall of silence'' -- a 
supposed code among some officers never to turn each other in. 
</P>
<P>
	Turetzky, 28, was accused by the defense of changing key parts  
of his story about the August 1997 night Louima was arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	In testimony, Louima said Officer Justin Volpe mistakenly  
thought he had punched him outside a nightclub the night of his 
arrest. He said Volpe later rammed a wooden stick into his rectum 
and mouth while Officer Charles Schwarz held him down on the 
precinct's bathroom floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwarz and three other officers are charged with taking turns  
beating Louima. Volpe and Schwarz are additionally charged with the 
bathroom attack. A fifth officer, Michael Bellomo, is charged with 
covering up the assault. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Turetzky testified seeing Schwarz lead a  
handcuffed Louima, whose pants were at his ankles, toward the 
bathroom. He said he later spotted Volpe marching Louima away from 
an area outside the bathroom, holding what appeared to be a broken 
broom handle. 
</P>
<P>
	After putting the prisoner in a holding pen, a disheveled and  
sullen Volpe ``was swinging the stick around like a sword and 
hitting it against the wall,'' the detective said. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Thursday, Volpe's attorney, Marvyn Kornberg, produced a  
transcript of a departmental investigation interview in which 
Turetzky indicated Schwarz -- who denies ever being in the bathroom 
-- or Wiese may have brought the prisoner out. 
</P>
<P>
	In the interview, Turetzky said, ``Like I said before, I wasn't  
sure who removed the defendant from the bathroom, but I distinctly 
remember Officer Volpe standing there with a stick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Turetzky conceded in cross-examination that he came forward only  
after the case was making headlines, Volpe was in custody, 
superiors were being transferred and departmental investigators 
were scheduling involuntary interviews with all 70th Precinct 
officers on duty that night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Isn't it true that you were scared to death about what would  
happen to you?'' Worth asked the detective, who received a 
promotion after cooperating with investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, sir,'' he replied.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
