<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Third-Graders Save Classmate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE VILLAGE, Ind. (AP) -- Two third-graders who ignored their  
classmates' cries to wait for an adult are being hailed as heroes 
for saving a 9-year-old from accidentally hanging himself on a 
flagpole rope at their school. 
</P>
<P>
	Sam Mahone was unconscious when Kasey Perkins and Tommy  
Richardson lifted the rope from around his neck, saving him from 
choking to death. 
</P>
<P>
	``My son is alive because of those two little boys,'' said Sam's  
mother, Catherine Mahone. ``They're tiny heroes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Mahone said her son told her he was ``goofing around'' with  
the rope during a Tuesday recess at Lake Village Elementary School 
in the small town of Lake Village, about 50 miles southeast of 
Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The second-grader told her he remembered putting the rope around  
his neck before becoming unable to breathe. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said he saw a bright light, then everything went black,''  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasey, 10, and Tommy, 9, were playing soccer when they saw Sam  
hanging by the rope from a flagpole, which was attached to a nearby 
scoreboard. The boy was blue and foaming at the mouth. 
</P>
<P>
	Ignoring their classmates' cries to wait for an adult, Kasey  
lifted Sam while Tommy undid the rope. 
</P>
<P>
	``My son knew enough to not move him after he was down,'' said  
Tiffany Perkins, Kasey's mother. ``We watch a lot of the 911 TV 
shows, and they learn a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sam was rushed to a hospital and was released on Wednesday. The  
boy is ``doing well,'' Mrs. Mahone said, but he has a red ring 
around his neck and broken capillaries around his eyes and ears. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mahones gave each boy a stuffed animal as a reward, and the  
school plans to recognize the boys with a merit award. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're proud the boys had the foresight to do something  
immediately,'' said Steve Sharp, the school's principal. ``They 
were scared, but they did a heroic deed.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
