<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Actor Fighting Navajo Court Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The Navajo Supreme Court has ruled against Sioux  
actor and activist Russell Means in a case that could define the 
power of tribal courts across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ruled it had criminal jurisdiction over all Indians on  
the Navajo Reservation, regardless of their tribal affiliation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every tribe is going to take a careful look at this,'' said  
Robert Williams, professor of law and American Indian studies at 
the University of Arizona. ``The stakes are very big.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Means, a member of the Oglala Sioux Nation, was charged in a  
Navajo court in December 1997 with threatening and beating his 
father-in-law. 
</P>
<P>
	The former American Indian Movement leader, who led a 1973  
uprising at Wounded Knee, S.D., had lived on and off the Navajo 
Reservation for 10 years with his former wife, who is Navajo. 
</P>
<P>
	Means challenged a 1991 law passed by Congress authorizing  
tribal courts to try Indians who are not members of their tribe. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 3-0 ruling Tuesday, the Navajo Supreme Court cited a 1977  
U.S. Supreme Court decision that defined ``Indian'' as a political 
rather than a racial category. 
</P>
<P>
	The law discriminates against Indians not belonging to the  
ruling tribe, said Means, who has appeared in such films as 
``Natural Born Killers'' and ``The Last of the Mohicans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't any rights on any reservation in America except my  
own, so I want to be treated like any other American,'' Means said 
Thursday from his home in Santa Fe, N.M. 
</P>
<P>
	Means, 59, has vowed to fight the Navajo, the nation's largest  
tribe, all the way to the U.S. Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	``Non-Indians on reservations are already clearly not subject to  
tribal courts (under the 1991 law),'' said his lawyer, John Trebon. 
``Why would tribal courts have criminal jurisdiction (in this 
case)? The only difference being race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case has drawn the attention of legal experts and Indian  
officials throughout the country. Oral arguments were heard in 
February at Harvard Law School. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said removing tribal jurisdiction over all Indians on  
reservations could pose significant problems. At some reservations, 
up to half the residents are not members of the tribe. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1973, Means emerged as a leader in the two-month standoff  
that followed AIM's takeover of Wounded Knee. The group was 
protesting reservation conditions and the federally backed tribal 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Shootouts left two protesters dead and a federal marshal  
paralyzed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
