<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nairobi Renovations Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- These are rare sights for Nairobi  
residents: tractors plowing new roads, construction workers 
painting buildings, gardeners planting trees and flowers. 
</P>
<P>
	Such scenes have become familiar in recent weeks, all part of a  
$59.7 million rehabilitation project that officials say has been on 
the table for some time. 
</P>
<P>
	But many in this bustling but badly atrophying East African  
capital are skeptical of the timing of the repairs, which come just 
as political and business leaders from all over central and 
southern Africa stream into Nairobi for a regional trade summit. 
</P>
<P>
	The improvements, critics say, are more of a quickie facelift  
for the benefit of visiting dignitaries than a substantive 
renovation for the city's residents or its future. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's insulting! They won't do it for us, but they'll do it for  
them,'' Linda Mukherjee, 42, a Nairobi housewife, said in the 
health spa locker room of the swank Serena Nairobi Hotel. ``It's a 
joke.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Work began downtown last month and has continued at a pace  
residents find hard to believe in a city where mammoth potholes, 
busted traffic lights, rock-dirt sidewalks and a sporadic power 
supply are the norm. 
</P>
<P>
	But government officials say the much-needed improvements were  
already planned and just got bumped up because of the Common Market 
for Eastern and Southern Africa meeting, which opened Thursday and 
is scheduled to run through May 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventeen African heads of state are expected to attend the  
COMESA meeting, as well as hundreds of other public officials and 
businesspeople. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is an impression being created that we are spending four  
billion Kenya shillings for COMESA, while this is not true,'' 
Minister of Local Government Sam Ongeri said on the private Kenya 
Television Network this week. ``It so happens that COMESA is coming 
when these improvements are taking place and we are taking 
advantage of this situation to speed up the beautification 
process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Evidence of the improvements were everywhere this week, with  
workers furiously plowing away rubble and planting trees and 
flowers along the city's main thoroughfares. 
</P>
<P>
	They also were busy at the Kenya International Conference  
Center. The center, which is owned by President Daniel arap Moi's 
ruling KANU Party, has fallen -- like much of the city -- into a 
state of dire disrepair in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	On a recent business day, repairmen painted new lines at a  
jammed traffic circle at the entrance to downtown, blocking one 
lane on a road many already consider a deathtrap because of its 
poor condition. 
</P>
<P>
	The lines trailed off just outside the traffic circle heading  
away from downtown -- leading to areas COMESA delegates are less 
likely to travel. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Nairobi City Council's idea of roads are only those to be  
used by the COMESA delegates,'' a cartoon in the private East 
African Standard newspaper said this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The 21-nation COMESA was created in 1993 with the goals of  
achieving regional free trade areas by 2000, common tariffs by 2004 
and monetary union by 2025. 
</P>
<P>
	Ongeri said the repairs are being funded by private donors and  
will benefit the entire city, not just the square-mile area that 
makes up downtown Nairobi. But the remote industrial areas -- and 
the even more distant slums where the majority of Nairobi residents 
live -- have not seen any attention so far. 
</P>
<P>
	Nairobi officials have refused to disclose who is funding the  
repairs. 
</P>
<P>
	But one city council official, speaking on condition of  
anonymity, said that because of the makeover council members won't 
be receiving their salaries on time this month and were planning to 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Civil servants in Kenya often don't get paid on time, and  
government promises to fight corruption have not been kept. All of 
that stokes Kenyans' skepticism about the repairs. 
</P>
<P>
	So while the government here views the COMESA conference and the  
trade show that comes with it as a chance to spruce up the city, 
many residents believe it will only create more headaches -- 
particularly for Nairobi's poor. 
</P>
<P>
	Police haven't disclosed their public transportation plan for  
next week, when the conference kicks into high gear, but residents 
expect city buses and ``matatus'' -- the jammed and decrepit 
minibuses that ferry Kenyans around Nairobi -- to be banned from 
downtown, as is typical during major events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
