<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Hopkins Official Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A former Johns Hopkins University administrator  
has admitted he failed to pay taxes on nearly $350,000 he got from 
an alleged billing fraud and kickback scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Schuerholz pleaded guilty Thursday to a count of tax  
evasion, saying failed to pay $97,962 in federal income taxes from 
1992 to 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge set sentencing for Sept. 3.  
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors will seek a jail sentence of 15 to 18 months  
for Schuerholz, who was fired from Hopkins in 1997 after 
allegations of kickbacks surfaced in a lawsuit involving a 
university contractor. 
</P>
<P>
	The maximum penalty is five years in prison and a $250,000 fine.  
</P>
<P>
	Schuerholz also must pay back taxes and penalties on the amount  
he failed to report, said Domenic J. LaPonzina, spokesman for the 
Internal Revenue Service in Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say Schuerholz had the sole authority to award  
contracts up to $500,000. He set up bogus bank accounts in the 
names of two shell companies, according to court papers. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents show a series of transactions between Hopkins and  
Elco Electric Inc., an electrical contractor headed by Schuerholz's 
cousin, Donald. 
</P>
<P>
	After the university paid Elco, Schuerholz asked Donald to write  
checks to the shell companies and provided bogus invoices to cover 
the payments, court papers show. 
</P>
<P>
	Schuerholz's attorney, James P. Ulwick, acknowledged his client  
failed to report money he received from Elco. But Ulwick disagreed 
with the government's characterization of ``kickbacks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's another side to this,'' he said. ``I hope it will come  
out at sentencing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
