<HEADLINE> Boxer Guilty in Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANTON, Ohio (AP) -- Professional boxer Dezi Ford was convicted  
of involuntary manslaughter in the beating death of his toddler 
son, and was sentenced today to eight years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stark County Common Pleas Court jury, which began  
deliberations late Thursday, could have convicted Ford of murder. 
The sentence was imposed by Judge John Haas. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said the 30-year-old lightweight caused massive  
internal injuries to his son, Zontius, as he playfully boxed with 
the 14-month-old last Christmas. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford initially admitted to police that he killed his son  
accidentally, but on the witness stand Thursday recanted statements 
he made to officers. He said he shadowboxed with the boy but never 
connected. 
</P>
<P>
	The baby's mother, Alvina Harris, 33, testified that she had  
left the baby in Ford's care while she went to shop. When she 
returned, she found the baby's eyes rolled back and his tongue 
flailing. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford won a Gold Gloves title in 1990 and turned pro two years  
later. He has a record of 23-13. 
</P>
</TEXT>
