<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NHL's Blues-Stars Series Is Even / Hockey Game Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Proving again that nothing in the regular season  
matters when the NHL playoffs begin, the fifth-seeded St. Louis 
Blues and the top-seeded Dallas Stars are deadlocked in a series 
that is far more even than anyone predicted. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars, who finished the season with a league-best 114 points  
to the Blues' 87, suddenly find themselves with a tough assignment 
heading into Saturday's Game 5 in Dallas -- if they want to 
recapture the momentum from the Blues. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues took a two-game deficit in the best-of-7 series back  
to their home ice, and surprised Dallas by taking two straight 
overtime games by scores of 3-2. Overtime has been good to the 
Blues, who are 4-2 through 11 playoff games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning in overtime gives us a great feeling,'' winger Geoff  
Courtnall said. ``When games are that close all the way through, 
and you get a big goal at the end, it lifts the room and lifts all 
the guys and gives the guy who scores a lot of confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Confidence that may carry the series to a full seven games,  
Stars coach Ken Hitchcock thinks. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got two good teams going at it. We knew that going  
in,'' Hitchcock said. ``I just don't see anything different the 
next three games. I think it's going to come down to the wire, and 
hopefully our home ice is an advantage for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blues coach Joel Quenneville is similarly modest-yet-optimistic.  
``It's been a heck of a run so far,'' he said. ``We think we have a 
chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock, a master of turning a molehill opponent into a  
mountainous enemy with his rhetoric, may not have been exaggerating 
when he said St. Louis was going to be a very tough matchup. 
</P>
<P>
	The tied series should be less of a surprise because -- rankings  
aside -- the numbers are very similar for both teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Both squads' power plays are looking futile: Dallas is 1-for-21,  
while St. Louis is 2-for-21. That's a credit to the Stars' penalty 
killing, because the Blues had the best power play in the first 
round. Keeping Al MacInnis' atomic shot from the point a non-factor 
is a big reason why. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams are getting points from all over the lineup, not just  
from the expected big guns. St. Louis sniper Pierre Turgeon has 
four goals and 11 points and Dallas' Joe Nieuwendyk has five goals 
and eight points. 
</P>
<P>
	From the lower-paid side of the rosters, consider Blues rookie  
Jochen Hecht's two goals in the last two games or Dallas grinder 
Mike Keane's two goals. 
</P>
<P>
	Where they are not even is in expectations. The pressure is  
squarely on the Stars, who can only be marked failures if they 
don't make the Stanley Cup finals. The Stars said they are not 
exactly shaking in fear of the persistent Blues. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team has dealt with adversity all year,'' defenseman  
Richard Matvichuk said. ``With the experience we have, there no 
doubt in my mind we're going to bounce back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few things should help their planned rebound.  
</P>
<P>
	Faceoff master Guy Carbonneau is due back Saturday, as is  
defenseman Shawn Chambers. Both have been out with knee injuries. 
It will be the first time Carbonneau has played in this series. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you get a guy like Guy Carbonneau back in your lineup,  
it's nothing but good,'' Matvichuk said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the Stars have not lost at home yet. If the series goes to  
seven games, they will play there for two of the three remaining 
games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 15:59:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cannes Parties Get Great Reviews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANNES, France (AP) -- There may be grumbling about the quality  
of some films at Cannes, but no one will ever complain about the 
festival's ability to throw a good dinner party. 
</P>
<P>
	The banquet for 600 guests following the opening film, ``The  
Barber of Siberia,'' was an extravagant tribute to the movie's 
Russian origins. 
</P>
<P>
	Once guests could make their way past the photographers begging  
Claudia Schiffer to keep posing -- ``One more, Claudia, PLEASE!!'' -- 
they entered a huge tent on the beach and were handed a perfectly 
chilled flute of champagne. 
</P>
<P>
	They dined on blinis with caviar (the chef needed 50 pounds of  
the stuff); lobster (he needed 600 of them) and ombrine cuite (a 
fish dish). For dessert, a sublime creme brulee and, with coffee, 
tiny raspberry tarts. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the generously flowing wines, each guest had a vodka  
glass, promptly refilled all evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those enjoying the meal were jury members Holly Hunter and  
Jeff Goldblum, as well as Jeremy Irons and Faye Dunaway. 
</P>
<P>
	The next day, even the trade papers raved about the food. If  
only the film itself had garnered the same raves. (It didn't come 
close.) 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Actor Guillaume Depardieu, son of the prolific French star  
Gerard Depardieu, was forced to blush at the news conference for 
his film, ``Pola X.'' In the movie, the young Depardieu has what 
they call a ``non-simulated'' sex scene. 
</P>
<P>
	The film's director, Leo Carax, said it wasn't difficult to film  
such a realistic tableau. 
</P>
<P>
	Easy for him to say, his actor countered.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was difficult ... to be on form, if you know what I mean,''  
he said diplomatically. 
</P>
<P>
	Could such scenes be turning into a trend? One of the most  
talked-about items at last year's festival was a similarly 
``non-simulated'' sex scene -- actually, an orgy -- in the respected 
director Lars von Trier's ``The Idiots.'' It evoked a gasp even 
from the most jaded spectators. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking of von Trier, Fine Line Pictures has just paid an  
estimated $5 million for the U.S. rights to his next film, ``Dancer 
in the Dark,'' an English-language musical starring the Icelandic 
singer Bjork and the French perennial favorite, Catherine Deneuve. 
</P>
<P>
	Von Trier, a reclusive Dane, won the 1996 Golden Palm at Cannes  
for ``Breaking the Waves.'' Last year's ``The Idiots,'' about a 
group of young people trying to get in touch with their ``inner 
idiots,'' was less successful. 
</P>
<P>
	Bjork is to play a Czech immigrant who works in a factory but  
dreams of a life in classic Hollywood musicals. In the dream 
numbers, according to the Hollywood Reporter, she will be joined by 
co-workers in the factory, including Deneuve. (Deneuve as a factory 
worker?) 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Everybody gets something different out of Cannes. Take Peri  
Gilpin, the American TV actress from ``Frasier.'' She's getting ... 
decorating tips. 
</P>
<P>
	On this glitzy, overpriced strip of the Riviera?  
</P>
<P>
	Well, Gilpin says, she's about to get married and she's thinking  
about decorating a lot. And landscaping. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the mixture of Roman pines and palms,'' she said. ``My  
fiance and I were jumping with glee. All the shutters, and the 
details. You just want to copy everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gilpin is in town for a more serious reason: she's participating  
in Cure by the Shore -- a fundraiser to fight cancer -- organized by 
Lily Tartikoff, widow of the late TV executive Brandon Tartikoff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
