<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *Ricardo Gangeme    	
</P>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Ricardo Gangeme, a prominent  
Argentine journalist, died Thursday after being shot in the head in 
the Southern city of Trelew. He was 56. 
</P>
<P>
	Gangeme was editor of El Informador Chubutense and former editor  
of the Buenos Aires daily Cronica. 
</P>
<P>
	Gangeme's wallet was left untouched and robbery did not appear  
to be a motive, police said. Colleagues reported that Gangeme, a 
crusading crime-fighting journalist, recently had received threats. 
</P>
<P>
	Jorge E. Fascetto, president of the Inter American Press  
Association, told a local radio station that hundreds of 
journalists have been killed worldwide through the years, with few 
cases getting solved. 
</P>
<P>
	Gangeme was the first journalist killed in Argentina since the  
January 1997 slaying of Jose Luis Cabezas, a photojournalist for 
the newsweekly Noticias, whose killing remains unresolved. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombia and Brazil have recently led the list of journalists  
slain in Latin America. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Jack Lowe    	
</P>
<P>
	SIDNEY, Neb. (AP) -- Jack Lowe, a former publisher of the Sidney  
Telegraph, died Friday at age 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe began working at the newspaper while in high school and  
continued his association with the paper throughout his life. He 
rose to editor of the Telegraph and was a co-owner and co-publisher 
from 1950-1971. He continued to write a column for the paper after 
his retirement until shortly before his death. 
</P>
<P>
	He was honored by the Nebraska Press Association with its Master  
Editor and Publisher Award. He was inducted into the Nebraska 
Newspaper Hall of Fame in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Known affectionately in western Nebraska as ``Mr. Sidney,'' Lowe  
was mayor of Sidney from 1952-1954 and served three times as 
interim city manager in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the first executive director of Panhandle Growth Inc.  
from 1973 to 1978 and then served as the first president of the 
shortline Sidney &AMP; Lowe Railroad until its construction was 
completed in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, daughter and son-in-law.  

</P>
<P>
                            *Leon Thomas    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Leon Thomas, a jazz singer known for his  
wordless yodeling style, died May 8 of heart failure as a result of 
leukemia. He was 61. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas developed the technique -- which he later called  
``soularphone'' -- in the late 1960s when he performed with musician 
Pharoah Sanders. His throat articulation was compared to African 
pygmy and American Indian singing techniques. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with Sanders, Thomas helped develop ``kosmigroov,'' a type  
of spiritual African-tinged soul-jazz exemplified in recordings 
like ``The Creator Has a Master Plan'' (1969) and 
``Hum-Allah-Hum-Allah-Hum Allah'' (1970). 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Illinois, Thomas moved to New York in 1958 and worked as  
a straight blues-jazz singer. By the mid-1960s he was performing 
with Count Basie and Mary Lou Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in his career he recorded albums for the Flying Dutchman  
label, and spent two years with the band Santana. In recent years, 
he often sang at the Lenox Lounge in Harlem. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Karl Yoneda    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Karl Yoneda, a Japanese-American  
longshoreman who was vilified for his marriage to a white woman, 
died Sunday at age 92. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in the United States but educated in Japan, Yoneda opposed  
Japan's rising militarism and dodged being drafted into the 
Imperial Japanese Army by returning to America in 1926. 
</P>
<P>
	He adopted the name Karl, after Karl Marx.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1931, while taking part in an unemployment demonstration, he  
was beaten and thrown into a Los Angeles jail. Elaine Black, then 
secretary of the Community International Labor Defense Committee, 
bailed him out. 
</P>
<P>
	The two began living together -- they could not legally  
intermarry in California. Dubbed ``Tiger woman'' by the Hearst 
papers and revered as the ``Red Angel'' by her admirers, she later 
married Yoneda. Their lifelong partnership ended only when she died 
at age 81 a decade ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoneda later became a longshoreman, his wife an office worker.  
Both continued their activism, opposing the Vietnam War and the 
neutron bomb and joining in the ``Free Angela Davis'' campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
