<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Drops Gondola Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress has decided not to provide $40  
million in compensation for last year's accident in which a U.S. 
Marine jet killed 20 skiers in an Italian cable car, a move an 
Italian official derided as ``another insupportable slight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate and House negotiators dropped the provision this week  
from a wide-ranging package financing the air campaign against 
Yugoslavia, aid to hurricane-ravaged Central America and other 
items. It had been approved in March by the Senate, but ran into 
opposition in the House and from the Defense Department. In 
addition to the now-canceled congressionally mandated compensation, 
the United States is paying other money to the Italian government 
to help the victims' families 
</P>
<P>
	The decision angered officials in Italy, where the accident  
prompted calls for the expulsion of U.S. forces from bases in 
Italy. The bases are now used for the airstrikes on Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have made fools of us for the second time,'' Italian  
Justice Minister Oliviero Diliberto said. 
</P>
<P>
	Referring to Italy's belief that the crew of the Marine jet had  
been given overly lenient sentences, Diliberto said, ``It's another 
insupportable slight to the ... victims of a slaughter that still, 
today, one year later, hasn't found justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roberta Synal, the Washington spokeswoman for families of the  
seven German victims of the accident, said that while Congress is 
spending billions of dollars to protect Kosovars in Yugoslavia, 
``For some strange reason they don't find it necessary to support 
the human rights of the families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Feb. 3, 1998, a Marine Corps EA-6B Prowler jet on a training  
mission in the Italian Alps sliced the gondola cable, sending the 
20 skiers on an eight-second, 370-foot plunge to their deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	The jet's pilot, Capt. Richard Ashby was acquitted of 20 counts  
of involuntary manslaughter for the deaths of the passengers aboard 
the Mount Cermis gondola cable, though he was later sentenced to 
six months in prison and dismissed from the corps for helping 
destroy a videotape of the flight. 
</P>
<P>
	The congressional provision had been sponsored by Sen. Chuck  
Robb, D-Va., a former Marine who since last summer has been trying 
to persuade the Pentagon to compensate the families. Pentagon 
officials have said they support compensating the families, but 
under a treaty that requires such matters to be pursued in Italy's 
courts. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Robb's provision, up to $2 million would have been paid  
for the family of each victim. The House did not approve that 
provision. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has said the United States would make amends  
for the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	In Rome, the U.S. Information Service issued a statement saying  
``The United States reaffirms its commitment to provide 
compensation for the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bill for direct U.S. payments to the victims that was just  
rejected by Congress does not in any way reduce or alter the 
commitment of the United States to fulfill its commitment to 
provide compensation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the NATO treaty, the United States will reimburse Italy  
for 75 percent of whatever it decides to pay families who file 
claims, the USIS said. Italy has already given the families 
$55,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has reimbursed Italy for 75 percent of that,  
and the Defense Department has funds available now to pay ``any 
additional requests for reimbursements,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal that lost out in Congress would have provided  
immediate compensation to the victims' families instead of waiting 
for Italian courts to act first. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
