<DOCNO> APW19990514.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 10:12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CDC Says Driving Is Safer Now </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Even though there are now about 215 million  
vehicles on the roads, cruising down the highway today is far safer 
than it was during the early part of the century, according to 
statistics on traffic deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Safety measures such as seat belts, bumpers and the yellow  
center line have contributed to a 90 percent drop in U.S. motor 
vehicle deaths per miles traveled since 1925, the Centers for 
Disease Control and Prevention said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sum of those is what has helped to reduce the motor  
vehicle fatality rate -- things that we really take for granted,'' 
said Dr. Bruce Jones of the CDC's National Center for Injury 
Prevention and Control. 
</P>
<P>
	Rigid steering wheels have been replaced by more  
energy-absorbent ones. Shatterproof windshields and seat belts have 
become the norm, as have cushioned dashboards. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were cars with dashboards made from hard material with  
edges and knobs and stuff sticking out that aren't there any more 
because it was hazardous,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	The result has been a drop in deaths from 18 per 100 million  
vehicle miles traveled in 1925 to 1.7 in 1997, the CDC said. At the 
same time, total miles driven has increased tenfold, and there are 
11 times as many vehicles on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	The vehicle safety report was part of the CDC's series on this  
century's greatest achievements in public health. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes came about as part of the National Safety Act,  
passed in 1966 after vehicle fatalities had risen for five straight 
years. The legislation paved the way for the National Highway 
Traffic Safety Administration. It was the first time the government 
established federal regulations for automobiles and roads. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon narrow, unmarked roads from the days of the Model T became  
well-lit thoroughfares with painted lines, concrete barriers and 
guardrails. And child safety seats and motorcycle helmets 
eventually became required by law. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 11 percent of drivers and passengers wore seat belts in the  
early 1980s. Now, about 68 percent of drivers wear them. 
</P>
<P>
	Approximately 40,000 people are killed in the United States each  
year in auto crashes, which remain the leading cause of death among 
people ages 1 to 24. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite all the successes we've had, this is still a leading  
major public health problem,'' Jones said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
