<DOCNO> APW19990514.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 10:12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Adidas Plans To Open More Stores </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEAVERTON, Ore. (AP) -- Adidas America is looking for possible  
locations for high-profile stores in major U.S. cities despite a 
slowdown in sneaker sales growth this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Adidas is scouting in New York, Boston, Philadelphia, Miami, San  
Francisco, Los Angeles and Seattle and hopes to begin work soon on 
new stores in at least two of those cities. It hasn't signed leases 
for any location. 
</P>
<P>
	The new retail shops will adopt a format similar to the  
5,000-square-foot store Adidas opened in Portland two years ago. 
``The stores will follow that template,'' said Adidas spokesman 
John Fread. 
</P>
<P>
	Adidas already operates 38 outlet stores, which are intended  
primarily to sell off excess inventory at a discount. It has been 
considering a move into higher-end retailing for more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Adidas' move comes as many retailers are battling sluggish  
consumer demand for athletic footwear and apparel. 
</P>
<P>
	Adidas anticipates sales growth in 1999 to be less than 10  
percent, down from the 68 percent surge last year when its North 
American revenues topped $1.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Fread said the stores will allow the company to test products,  
signage and merchandising techniques with a variety of customers. 
It will in turn pass on effective ideas to its retail customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``When things become more challenging, you need to do business  
better,'' Fread said. ``This is an investment in how to do 
business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adidas America is the Beaverton-based subsidiary of German  
athletics giant Adidas AG. The parent company owns the Salomon 
brand of ski and snowboard gear and the Taylor Made brand of golf 
equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Its rival Nike Inc., the best-selling sneaker marketer, already  
has 13 NikeTown stores. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't even say that word,'' Adidas spokesman John Fread  
said when asked about NikeTown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
