<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MacArthur Returns in Movie Biography </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- What a difference a uniform makes.  
</P>
<P>
	Even now, decades later, few would fail to recognize that  
austere figure in officer's cap and sunglasses, with the corncob 
pipe jutting from his mouth. 
</P>
<P>
	But how many would recognize the mild-looking fellow with  
thinning, neatly combed hair, frolicking in the garden with his 
little son? 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides of Gen. Douglas MacArthur -- American war hero and  
loving family man -- emerge in vivid close-up in ``MacArthur,'' an 
enthralling and wonderfully straightforward biography from producer 
Austin Hoyt. It airs Monday and Tuesday, May 17 and 18, at 9 p.m. 
EDT (check local listings) in the PBS ``The American Experience'' 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	``MacArthur'' offers no startling revelations, nor does it need  
to. Like an ancient Greek drama, this is a tale to be handed down 
through the generations. The opening line of the narration says it 
all: ``In the theater of war he was producer, director and star. 
But brilliant military victories were shadowed by crushing personal 
defeats.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Facing the Japanese in the Philippines in World War II,  
MacArthur presided over the worst defeat in American military 
history. Three years later, he would orchestrate Japan's surrender 
aboard the battleship Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	For his role in quelling the Bonus March on Washington by  
impoverished World War I veterans during the Depression, he became 
a symbol of oppressive authoritarianism. Yet as a military 
occupier, his foresight and magnanimity helped create today's 
peaceful, democratic Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	When the atomic bomb was dropped on Hiroshima, MacArthur was  
heard to say, ``Men like me are obsolete. ... There will be no more 
wars.'' Yet five years later, at the age of 70, he masterminded the 
Inchon landings, the highly risky amphibious invasion that reversed 
the course of the Korean War. 
</P>
<P>
	And still the wild ride wasn't over. In April 1951, after a  
series of clashes with President Harry S. Truman over the conduct 
of the Korean War, MacArthur was fired. He came home a hero with 
presidential ambitions. But that high office would go to his former 
clerk, an equally gifted but less disputatious soldier, Dwight D. 
Eisenhower. 
</P>
<P>
	``Old soldiers never die,'' MacArthur declared in his memorable  
farewell speech to Congress, ``they just fade away.'' And fade away 
he did, dying in 1964, age 84, just as Vietnam was becoming 
America's next great war. 
</P>
<P>
	The film shows the general as a deeply human figure: vain,  
publicity-hungry, given to flights of lyrical oratory. (As 
superintendent of West Point, he encouraged cadets to write 
poetry.) After his first marriage failed, he set up house with 
Isabel Rosario Cooper, aka ``Dimples,'' his half-Filipino mistress, 
in Washington D.C., coolly ignoring the racial hang-ups of the 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	His second marriage, to Jean Faircloth, 20 years his junior,  
lasted 27 years until his death in 1964. They had one son, Arthur, 
who would become a musician. 
</P>
<P>
	The seeds of MacArthur's greatness, and his downfall, probably  
were planted in his boyhood on a U.S. Army base in New Mexico. It 
was there, historian Geoffrey Perret surmises, that young MacArthur 
absorbed the idea that ``it is the military that pushes the 
frontier back, and the civilians come afterward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His father, Arthur MacArthur, was a Civil War hero who felt  
cheated of his due by know-nothing politicians and transmitted that 
grudge to Douglas. Disdain for superiors, especially civilian ones, 
would become a recurring theme of MacArthur's life, culminating in 
his clash with Truman. MacArthur saw no substitute for total 
victory in Korea, even if that meant full-scale war with China. 
Truman wanted to limit the war lest it escalate into World War III. 
</P>
<P>
	Where might MacArthur find an American military hero today? The  
Gulf? Yugoslavia? He might have to settle for Scott Ritter, the 
Marine major who resigned last year as a U.N. weapons inspector in 
Iraq, protesting that the U.S. government was thwarting his 
mission. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchanges eerily reminiscent of the past, a Republican  
senator called Ritter a hero, while a Democrat said he should leave 
the big decisions to the politicians. 
</P>
<P>
	In the MacArthur-Truman struggle of wills, the public sided  
overwhelmingly with MacArthur. Yet ultimately, history would be 
kinder to Truman, viewing the man from Missouri as having defended 
a hallowed principle: that the elected government, not the brass, 
makes policy. 
</P>
<P>
	How will future generations view the debate over Iraq? Or  
Kosovo, or anywhere else where politicians must weigh military 
action against the diplomatic realities of the day? ``MacArthur'' 
steers clear of preaching lessons for the 1990s. It leaves viewers 
to draw their own lessons from this remarkable American life. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`20/20': Marking the end to the official period of mourning,  
Queen Noor of Jordan sits down with Barbara Walters on ``20/20'' 
tonight. In her first network TV appearance since the Feb. 7 death 
of her husband, King Hussein, Queen Noor reveals details of his 
poignant last days. In the interview, conducted recently in the 
Jordanian capital of Amman, she speaks of how she is coping with 
the loss, her feelings on the controversial succession to the 
throne, and of her own future. ABC News' ``20/20'' airs at 10 p.m. 
EDT. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
