<HEADLINE> Andrews Denies Tabloid Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- Julie Andrews is denying a tabloid  
report that she was treated for drug dependency, saying she 
received care to help her cope with grief related to throat surgery 
and the death of an aunt. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Andrews, 63, recently checked in at the Sierra Tucson  
facility in Arizona for ``guidance and management of emotional 
issues related to grief,'' her lawyers said a statement Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I identified emotional issues surrounding my grief that made  
me wish to take action sooner rather than later,'' Ms. Andrews 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The May 25 issue of The Globe reports she was treated for drug  
dependency, the statement said. Representatives for the tabloid did 
not return calls seeking comment after business hours Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Her lawyers, Peter Parcher and Orin Snyder, said the singer and  
actress ``does not have, and never has had, a drug or alcohol 
dependency problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Andrews has been unable to sing since she underwent a  
procedure to remove noncancerous throat nodules two years ago. She 
starred in Broadway's ``My Fair Lady,'' and ``Victor/Victoria,'' 
and in such film classics as ``The Sound of Music'' and ``Mary 
Poppins.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
