<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 06:13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PAL Investors Want No-Strike Promise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Philippine Airlines chairman Lucio  
Tan said Friday that prospective investors want a guarantee that 
airline workers will not strike for 10 years before they invest in 
the troubled carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan is negotiating with several potential investors from Europe,  
Singapore and Hong Kong in hopes of raising $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan, who owns 70 percent of PAL's stock, has pledged to put in  
$100 million and is looking for investors to provide the other 
half. 
</P>
<P>
	``If our labor is cooperating 10 years, no strike, then  
foreigners will come in with $100 million,'' Tan told reporters 
after meeting PAL's board of directors. 
</P>
<P>
	The capital infusion is a key element of a rehabilitation plan  
that also calls for a reduction of PAL's fleet from 54 to 22 
aircraft and a drastic cut in its workforce. 
</P>
<P>
	Manila's corporate regulator, the Securities and Exchange  
Commission, has said it will order the liquidation of Asia's oldest 
airline, if airline officials cannot raise the money by June 4. 
</P>
<P>
	Airline president Avelino Zapanta said company officials will  
meet with leaders of the airline's two unions, representing flight 
and ground personnel, to obtain the no-strike guarantee in exchange 
for stock in the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the 8,000 PAL workers agreed in September not to launch  
any work stoppage, but Zapanta said many still resist giving up 
their right to strike. 
</P>
<P>
	President Joseph Estrada has said the government will not bail  
out PAL but has ordered officials to help the flag carrier seek new 
investors because of the potential economic impact if the airline 
shuts down. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline has been unable to pay $2.2 billion in debts largely  
incurred in an ambitious but ill-timed fleet modernization program. 
The carrier has been unable to service its loans as a result of 
Asia's economic crisis and a debilitating pilots' strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
