<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 16:41:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arkansas Derby Hearing Set </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The Arkansas Racing Commission is to  
hear an appeal May 24 from jockey Billy Patin, who was suspended 
from racing for a year after a ruling that he carried an illegal 
electrical device when the horse he rode finished first in the 
Arkansas Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	The hearing originally was set for last Wednesday but was  
postponed because of lawyers' scheduling conflicts. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewards for Oaklawn Park last week disqualified Patin's mount  
Valhol and ordered the $300,000 first-place share of the purse to 
be redistributed. Second-place finisher Certain was declared the 
new winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Patin was fined $2,500 and suspended through the end of 1999 --  
the maximum punishment available to stewards. The three-member 
panel referred the matter to the state Racing Commission with the 
suggestion that it extend Patin's suspension through May 5, 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewards reached their decision after reviewing a videotape that  
showed a black item falling from Patin's hand shortly after 
Valhol's victory. A tractor driver testified that he found an 
electrical device on the track in the same vicinity as the object 
was shown falling from the video. 
</P>
<P>
	Patin, testifying before stewards, suggested that the falling  
black object may have been a black rubber band used to hold his 
shirt sleeves closed. Patin said he noticed he was missing one of 
the four bands when he returned to the jockeys' room after the 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	Patin's attorney also suggested that the electrical device could  
have been dropped from any of the other jockeys in the race, or 
been dropped sometime in the past and then turned up by tractors 
and disks reworking the track's loose dirt after the derby was run. 
</P>
<P>
	Racing Commission attorney Byron Freeland said the hearing will  
include witnesses, questioning and evidence -- much like the 
stewards' hearing. A majority of the five-member commission is 
needed to uphold the stewards' ruling. An appeal then could be 
filed in circuit court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
