<HEADLINE> Byrd Waives Immunity in Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) -- Sen. Robert C. Byrd, the proud guardian of  
the historic rights and privileges of the Senate, has waived 
congressional immunity and offered to face the consequences for 
causing a fender-bender. 
</P>
<P>
	The 81-year-old West Virginia Democrat told prosecutors that he  
doesn't want special treatment in connection with the May 7 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
	He could be fined an amount to be determined by a judge.  
</P>
<P>
	The senator had been given a ticket for following too closely,  
but the citation was dropped under the constitutional provision 
that grants members of Congress immunity from arrest while Congress 
is in session. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd spokeswoman Ann Adler said the senator ``wants to do the  
right thing legally. He wants to appear in court -- the whole 
thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A summons was reissued and Byrd is scheduled to appear in court  
July 19. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd rear-ended a van in a rented Cadillac, police said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
