<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises, Tokyo Stocks Fall / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Signs of a healthy American economy helped send the  
dollar higher against the Japanese yen today. Tokyo share prices 
fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar cost 122.18 yen as of late today, up 0.60 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
121.85 yen overnight. It ranged during the day from 121.63 yen to 
122.23 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at 16,810.39  
points, down 40.86 points, or 0.24 percent from Thursday. On 
Thursday, the index lost 96.11 points, or 0.57 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar was well-supported by U.S.  
economic data released late Thursday, which indicated inflation is 
still nascent in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Shuji Takano, assistant foreign exchange manager at ABN AMRO  
Bank in Tokyo, said that the strong U.S. economy as well as rising 
share prices on Wall Street favor a strong dollar. ``Japanese are 
even buying at these high levels,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average on Thursday closed at yet  
another record high of 11,107.19 points, up 106.82. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro bought 130.33 yen in the late  
afternoon, up from 129.36 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices initially rose moderately on the  
overnight stock gains in New York. But players grew cautious about 
pushing prices higher before a series of closely watched earnings 
reports for the last fiscal year, ending in March, which are 
expected in coming weeks, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Institutional investors start selling each time the Nikkei  
average nears 17,000,'' said Kazunori Jinnai, deputy general 
manager of the equity department at Daiwa Securities SB Capital 
Markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 4.52 points, or 0.33 percent, to 1,347.45. 
The TOPIX fell 9.18 points, or 0.67 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the first section totaled about 727.8 million, up from  
579.4 million Thursday. Retreating issues outnumbered advancers 650 
to 504, while 156 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.240 percent from 1.300 percent late Thursday, 
driving its price up to 102.33 yen from 101.78 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
