<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pollsters Question Internet Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Internet surveys are a great  
way to stir up interest in Web sites, but pollsters want to make a 
clear distinction between those surveys and polls that measure 
public opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	They are considering the possibility of a rating system that  
would require pollsters to inform the public and the media which 
polls are conducted using scientific standards. Pollsters searched 
for a solution to the difficult problem Friday during the annual 
meeting of the American Association for Public Opinion Research. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't overstate the concern that people who practice  
polling have about this,'' said Nancy Belden, a Washington pollster 
who organized the standards discussion. ``It is more urgent because 
of the proliferation of Internet polling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Warren Mitofsky, the veteran New York City pollster who heads  
the group's standards committee, emphasized it's too early to know 
what solution the group will finally pursue. 
</P>
<P>
	But studies of the online surveys have shown their results are  
very different from scientific polls. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pew Research Center ran a comparison of its own probability  
polls and the results of self-selected survey responses to the same 
questions on America Online. More than half in the open online 
survey disapproved of the job President Clinton was doing, while 
two-thirds in the scientific telephone poll approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientific surveys use a technique called random digit dialing,  
in which a computer picks phone numbers at random and the poll 
results are weighted geographically and demographically to 
represent the population as a whole. Most Web polls are 
self-selected, meaning Internet users decide themselves whether to 
respond. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet surveys are increasingly being targeted by interest  
groups that want a new forum to promote their cause. 
</P>
<P>
	``OK Internet Brigade, let's get out there and stand strong for  
Pat!'' was the rallying cry posted recently on Pat Buchanan's 
official web site. The site encourages supporters to ``hit the 
online polls and register your vote for PJB.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aides with several other presidential campaigns, Republican and  
Democratic, said they encourage participation in such polls, but 
have made no organized effort to influence the results. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollsters are trying to cut confusion caused by the Internet  
surveys. 
</P>
<P>
	At CNN, poll director Keating Holland helped convince those who  
run the online surveys to call them ``quick votes'' to make a clear 
distinction that they are not scientific polls. 
</P>
<P>
	The technology of the Internet has simply made more visible a  
problem pollsters have faced for years. Mail-in polls, which have 
been around for years, can cause the same confusion as Internet 
polls, because the poll taker usually has little control over who 
decides to respond. 
</P>
<P>
	One firm has advocated using Internet surveys for election  
polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Leonard Bayer, chief scientist at Harris Black International of  
Rochester, N.Y., says his techniques include finding a large sample 
of willing respondents on the Internet who can be canvassed by 
e-mail. ``Part of the pollsters' art and science is knowing how to 
weight and interpret survey results so that they are projectable to 
the population,'' Bayer said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
