<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Despite Bad Economic News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against other currencies Friday  
after plunging when unexpectedly high consumer price numbers sent 
stocks and bonds tumbling. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's rise against the yen began during Asian trading as  
weak Japanese economic news crippled the yen's fight for stability. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0654 in late trading in New York, down  
from $1.0660 late Thursday. Also, the dollar was quoted at 1.5059 
Swiss francs, up from 1.5027, and 1.4640 Canadian dollars, up from 
1.4583. The British pound fell to $1.6184 from $1.6205. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the dollar rose to 122.73 Japanese yen from 121.85  
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were busy Friday, shoving the dollar first in one  
direction, then another. 
</P>
<P>
	The action during U.S. trading started with the morning release  
of data from the Labor Department, which said consumer prices 
jumped in April an unexpectedly sharp 0.7 percent, the largest 
monthly gain in nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders dumped dollars and bought other currencies as the equity  
and bond markets fell. The 30-year Treasury bond had its largest 
one-day decline since early October as its yield hit highs not seen 
in a year. 
</P>
<P>
	But after a few minutes, bullish sentiment about the U.S.  
economy triggered a round of dollar-buying, pushing the currency 
higher than it was Thursday during late trading. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been everywhere but we finally ended higher,'' said  
Kathy Jones, a currency analyst at Prudential Securities. adding 
that the high yields on the bonds attracted dollar-buyers paying 
attention to the lower yields in other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	In Asian trading, investors moved to the dollar early and  
dropped yen as Japan's Economic Planning Agency's monthly report 
said their economy is stalled in an extremely severe state. 
</P>
<P>
	The report cited the 11th straight month of falling department  
store sales, corporate investment in plant and equipment falling at 
a ``fast pace,'' and record-setting unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's declining domestic demand despite all of the stimulus.  
Eventually, the Bank of Japan will have to do more'' to fight 
Japan's worst recession since World War II, Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the euro countries are no longer traded separately  
and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the euro's exchange rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8359  
German marks, up from 1.8349; 6.1576 French francs, up from 6.1538; 
and 1,818.18 Italian lire, up from 1,814.88. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
