<DOCNO> APW19990514.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 15:51:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wal-Mart Rejects Contraceptive Pill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Wal-Mart, the nation's largest  
retailer, has decided not to sell the morning-after pill at its 
2,400 pharmacy counters. 
</P>
<P>
	WalMart, with a large part of its customer base in conservative,  
small-town America, said Friday that the decision had nothing to do 
with ethical concerns. Instead, it said it concluded that the 
emergency contraceptive might not sell well enough to make it worth 
the effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Family planning advocates criticized the move, saying that some  
women, particularly those in small towns where Wal-Mart has little 
competition, would have greater difficulty finding the drug, 
Preven. 
</P>
<P>
	``They will come to understand that this decision is  
misguided,'' she the president of the Planned Parenthood Federation 
of America, Gloria Feldt. ``Pharmacies have a moral obligation to 
provide health care to women, and frankly, emergency contraception 
prevents unintended pregnancies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said she asked to meet with Wal-Mart executives.  
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, WalMart has banned other products, including  
some kinds of music, handguns and men's magazines, on moral 
grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to carry anything that we feel will offend our  
customers, but that was not the judgment in this case,'' Wal-Mart 
spokesman Jay Allen said from the company's Bentonville 
headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen said Wal-Mart selects products it believes its customers  
will want and decided not to sell the drug when it became available 
in October, in part because of potentially low sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sales wouldn't be the only factor, but it would be one of the  
factors,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He would not say what the other factors were but said Wal-Mart  
is not banning the drug because of the debate over abortion 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not the job of a Wal-Mart store to get involved on  
either side of an issue,'' Allen said. ``It is to serve the 
millions of customers and shareholders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart said it will refer women who want the drug to nearby  
competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Preven is essentially a large dose of regular birth control  
pills. Before Preven was approved, some doctors would tell women to 
take an excess dose of their birth control pills if they had had 
unprotected sex and wanted to prevent pregnancy. Preven is easier 
to use because it comes packaged in a kit that includes simple 
directions and a pregnancy test. 
</P>
<P>
	Preven can be used up to 72 hours after unprotected sex to stop  
a pregnancy. It stops ovulation and prevents fertilized eggs from 
implanting in the uterine wall. The drug is not the same as RU-486, 
which can be used in the first seven weeks of pregnancy to induce 
an abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	Some abortion foes oppose Preve. But because three days is too  
soon to tell if a woman is pregnant, many anti-abortion groups 
haven't taken a stand on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no way to know if fertilization has occurred,'' said  
Rose Mimms, the director of Arkansas Right to Life. ``We have 
enough work to do without taking on something when there's still a 
question of whether there is life there or not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A researcher told the government in 1997 that there was a market  
for Preven to prevent about 2.3 million pregnancies a year. The 
company that makes it, Gynetics Inc. of Somerville, N.J., has sold 
about 80,000 doses since October, according to IMS Health, a market 
data firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Gynetics president Roderick Mackenzie said, ``It can only be  
because they don't think the volume is big enough. I just assume 
it's the money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the Walgreens drug store chain, spokeswoman Yvette Venable  
said of Preven, ``It hasn't been a very strong seller, but we plan 
to continue carrying it.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
