<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ga. Tech's Glover Wants NBA Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Georgia Tech's Dion Glover hasn't played a game  
in almost 14 months. Still, his next game might be in the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	Glover, a 6-foot-5 guard who missed all of last season because  
of a knee injury, declared himself eligible for the NBA draft 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope to explore my options of where I would be drafted,''  
Glover said in a statement released by the school. He said he would 
not sign with an agent, however, so he can keep his college 
eligibility intact if he decides to pull out before the June 30 
draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Glover's decision is somewhat surprising since he hasn't played  
competitively since 1997-98. That season, he was the No. 3 freshman 
scorer in the nation with 18.4 points per game. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first practice as a sophomore, Glover tore the anterior  
cruciate and medial collateral ligaments in his left knee during a 
seemingly harmless one-on-one drill. He spent the rest of the 
season making a full recovery from the injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had talked with Dion about this option when he was first  
injured,'' Tech coach Bobby Cremins said in the statement. ``He has 
taken full advantage of the NBA rules and has promised me that he 
will retain his college eligibility while considering his 
options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glover said he will pay his own way to a tryout camp in Chicago  
and also will work out individually for NBA teams. 
</P>
<P>
	He can withdraw his name 72 hours prior to the 30 draft. Also,  
if he goes through the two-round process without being picked, he 
has 30 days to request that his college eligibility be restored. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to be careful,'' said Tech spokesman Mike Finn.  
</P>
<P>
	He had the third highest-scoring season (608 points) ever  
recorded by a Tech freshman -- behind Kenny Anderson and Stephon 
Marbury -- and tied the freshman school scoring record with a 
33-point effort against Seton Hall in the National Invitation 
Tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	After flirting with the idea of turning pro after his first  
season, Glover decided to return to Tech for at least one more 
year. Now, he may be gone after that lone year on the court. 
</P>
<P>
	Glover is one of 13 players who have declared for the draft. The  
list includes Jumaine Jones of rival Georgia and three stars from 
the ACC -- William Avery and Elton Brand of Duke and Steve Francis 
of Maryland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
