<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pistons Fight Back Against Atlanta  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Facing elimination, the Detroit  
Pistons went back to an old formula. They let their guards take 
over. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Dumars, of course, was part of the 1989-90 championship  
tandem -- sharing the backcourt with Isiah Thomas. Now, Dumars has 
Lindsey Hunter on his wing. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the third game of their first-round series with Atlanta,  
it almost looked like Thomas was back. Hunter was diving for balls, 
breaking up passes and generally playing playoff-style basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, Detroit beat the Hawks 79-63 and lived to play  
again after the lowest-scoring game in NBA playoff history. Atlanta 
still owns a 2-1 edge in the best-of-5 series and can eliminate the 
Pistons tonight at The Palace. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Pistons are vowing to go out with a fight.  
</P>
<P>
	``We can't let up now,'' said Dumars, who will retire at the end  
of this season. ``We're still on the brink of elimination. When 
you're on the brink, you have to play desperate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his hustle, Hunter had 13 points, four assists  
and three steals in Game 3. He also managed to keep Atlanta guard 
Mookie Blaylock in check, holding him to just eight points. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't play the first two games like I did in the regular  
season, but I had to put that behind me,'' Hunter said. ``I love 
the challenge of battling Mookie. He outplayed me two games in a 
row and I was determined not to let it be three.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another key for the Pistons was their ability to contain Dikembe  
Mutombo, the Hawks' 7-foot-2 center. In the first two games, 
Mutombo dominated and Atlanta routed the Pistons, winning each game 
by 20 points. 
</P>
<P>
	But in Game 3, the Pistons never had fewer than two bodies on  
Mutombo. 
</P>
<P>
	They knocked him around a little bit, too. With 6:22 to go in  
the third quarter, Mutombo drove the lane only to be banged to the 
floor by Grant Hill. It was Hill's fourth foul, but the Pistons had 
sent a message: Someone other than Mutombo would have to beat them. 
</P>
<P>
	``It speaks volumes of him and not wanting to give up,'' said  
Dumars, who had 11 points, including 3-of-4 from 3-point range. ``A 
year or two ago, I don't know if he'd take that foul. I think he's 
growing up, and that play kind of displays that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the Hawks were not pleased.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if it was a message foul,'' Hawks coach Lenny  
Wilkens said. ``But if you don't go for the ball, the referee has 
to have the courage to call the flagrant foul. That's not asking 
them to give us something, that's the rule.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 63 points were the fewest ever scored by the Hawks in a  
playoff game and the second-lowest in NBA history, topped only by 
the 54 points by Utah in last year's NBA Finals against the Chicago 
Bulls. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawks' previous low was 71 in 1950 when they were the  
Tri-Cities Black Hawks. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta's 27 points in the first half was the lowest half in  
Hawks' playoff history. The club's previous low-water mark was 28 
in the second half against Chicago on May 10, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will come out next game attacking the basket,'' Mutombo  
said. ``We are going to make adjustments and trap more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the Pistons can force a fifth game, it will be played Sunday  
in Atlanta. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
