<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 14:43:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parties Vie for Kosovo Bill Kudos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A legislative package financing the airstrikes  
on Yugoslavia has Republicans crowing that they are rebuilding a 
hollowed-out military while Democrats can say they outmaneuvered 
the GOP over how federal surpluses should be used. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after House-Senate negotiators struck a compromise on the  
$15 billion spending bill, earlier White House veto threats all but 
vanished. Clinton administration officials claimed victories for 
limiting GOP-sought defense increases and environmental 
restrictions and winning funds for U.S. farmers and victims of 
domestic and overseas natural disasters. 
</P>
<P>
	``This bill is vastly improved upon the legislation and  
expectations we were looking at just one month ago,'' said Linda 
Ricci, spokeswoman for the White House budget office. ``We expect 
the president will be presented with a bill he can sign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans latched onto the bill's defense funds as a triumph  
for their side. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly $12 billion of the measure is for the U.S. role in the  
NATO campaign against Yugoslavia and other Pentagon programs, 
doubling the money President Clinton sought. Republicans who 
control Congress were eager to use that to burnish their 
pro-defense reputation, arguing that the bill is a first step 
toward reinvigorating a military that Clinton has allowed to 
shrivel. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite our differences over the administration's Balkan  
policy, this bill sends a strong message to our troops in the field 
that the Congress supports them,'' said House Appropriations 
Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla., one of the bill's chief 
authors. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans were bragging about language forbidding the federal  
government from grabbing any of the $246 billion tobacco companies 
have agreed to pay states in a legal settlement. Clinton had been 
counting on using billions from that kitty for health and 
anti-smoking programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal conservatives scored two wins, though both were largely  
symbolic. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly $2 billion of the package's cost will be paid for with  
cuts in domestic programs. Clinton didn't want any cuts, preferring 
to use the federal surplus for the entire cost. 
</P>
<P>
	At the insistence of House and Senate GOP leaders, a provision  
offered by Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., was dropped that would have 
provided $140 million to back a $1 billion loan program for 
struggling steel companies. Byrd's prowess for winning home-state 
projects, unparalleled in Congress, has made his proposals an 
enticing target for conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., also benefited when he  
successfully pressured two House GOP negotiators to switch their 
earlier positions and vote to block Byrd's project. After five 
months as speaker in which he has passively let GOP strategy 
evolve, his action was seen by many Republicans as a rare act of 
decisiveness. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House scored some political points on the budget  
surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	With most of the package paid for out of the surplus, which for  
now comes entirely from Social Security, it will be harder for the 
GOP to find money for the tax cuts it wants. It will also be 
tougher for Republicans to claim they are protecting every penny of 
the pension program -- a claim they want to drum into voters' minds 
in time for next year's elections. 
</P>
<P>
	``Republicans adopted the same tax-and-spend policy Democrats  
used for many years,'' said Stanley Collender, a budget analyst for 
Fleishman-Hilliard Inc., the consulting firm. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials boasted that they blocked a loan-guarantee  
program for oil and gas companies, narrowed a bid to let mining 
companies expand toxic dump sites and blocked an effort to lift 
fishing restrictions in Alaska's Glacier Bay National Park. 
</P>
<P>
	But environmental groups complained that too many  
anti-environmental provisions survived. These included items 
offered by Western senators delaying new rules that would force 
mining companies to pay more for cleanups and boosting royalties 
owed by oil companies drilling on public lands. 
</P>
<P>
	``He really should veto this thing,'' said Marty Hayden,  
political director of the Earthjustice Legal Defense Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats may also benefit from something that did not happen.  
</P>
<P>
	Republican bargainers blocked an amendment by Sen. Tom Harkin  
D-Iowa, that would have added $5 billion in emergency farm aid. 
Though they lost the money, Democrats hope they can use the vote as 
an issue in the 2000 congressional races. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
