<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Group Unites Dead Cops' Families </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                       *Assiated Press Writer    	
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The news of a cop fighting for his life drew  
Molly Winters into her past. Another family was about to relive her 
nightmare of eight years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Winters did not know Indiana Conservation Officer Karl Kelley  
when she heard of his drowning accident last April. But she drove 
108 miles from her home in Muncie, Ind., to the Louisville, Ky. 
hospital where he was clinging to life in case his family needed 
any help. 
</P>
<P>
	They did. When Kelley died hours later, Winters was there for  
his wife and kids. Now they are friends, bound by common tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``After something like that happens, you just barely get through  
each day, let alone trying to make any kind of major decisions,'' 
said Laura Kelley Jones, one of Kelley's grown children. 
</P>
<P>
	Winters is a member of Concerns of Police Survivors, or COPS, a  
15-year-old group dedicated to helping spouses, children and 
co-workers of those killed in the line of duty. The survivors offer 
emotional support, run errands, complete paperwork, help organize 
funerals and sometimes become friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Winters and Jones are to be in Washington this weekend at  
National Police Week ceremonies honoring officers killed last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just good to be around a couple thousand other people who  
are going through the same thing, and knowing you're not the only 
one,'' said Jones, who was at a candlelight vigil in Washington on 
Thursday as her father's name was carved into the stone of the 
National Law Enforcement Officers Memorial. 
</P>
<P>
	It was at a similar event 16 years ago that 10 police widows  
came up with the idea for COPS. Fifteen years later, there are 37 
national chapters and about 9,000 families involved. COPS' annual 
seminars have expanded from serving just spouses to include 
officers' co-workers, children and other relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you want to cry, or laugh, or if you feel like screaming or  
whatever, you don't feel uncomfortable,'' said Winters, whose 
husband was shot to death in 1990 while working for the Muncie 
Police Department. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone around you has gone through the same thing. They  
understand if you're laughing and crying about your officer at the 
same time,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Detective Douglas Shugars of the U.S. Capitol Police has  
volunteered his time for nine years during police week at the COPS 
for Kids seminars. But this year he is seeking healing for himself. 
</P>
<P>
	His partner and friend, Detective John Gibson, was shot and  
killed July 24 when a man entered the U.S. Capitol and opened fire 
on staffers and tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right after John was shot, my mind raced with thoughts,''  
Shugars said. ``I knew a little of what I was going to experience 
from working with the kids, but I had no idea the magnitude of the 
emotions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Winters formed the Indiana chapter of COPS in 1998. Like COPS  
volunteers across the country, she responds to hospitals when 
officers are shot or gravely injured. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to give back what I was given,'' Winters explained.  
</P>
<P>
	So does Jones. She said the outpouring of help she received  
after her father's death makes her want to get involved with COPS. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't remember a lot of names and faces in the days  
following the accident,'' Jones said. ``I just remember there were 
people who had been through the same thing who were bending over 
backwards to help.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
