<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 02:51:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor Testifies in Lewis Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Weeks before Reggie Lewis collapsed and died while  
practicing jump shots, his doctor told reporters the Boston Celtics 
star had a minor fainting condition that should not impede his 
basketball career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am optimistic that under medical supervision Mr. Reggie  
Lewis will be able to return to professional basketball without 
limitation,'' Gilbert Mudge said at a May 10, 1993, news conference 
marking Lewis' release from the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	A video of that news conference was played Thursday for jurors  
at Mudge's malpractice trial as Lewis' widow, Donna Harris-Lewis, 
wept. Harris-Lewis is suing the renowned cardiologist, who treated 
the All-Star in the months before he died. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis was 27 when he died of cardiac arrhythmia while practicing  
at Brandeis University 11 weeks after Mudge's news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking publicly for the first time since Lewis died, Mudge on  
Thursday testified his assessment that Lewis had neurocardiogenic 
syncope, a condition that causes fainting spells and is not related 
to the heart, was never a ``definitive diagnosis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge also said there were ``ongoing concerns'' Lewis might have  
a potentially fatal cardiac ailment. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet at the news conference -- and, according to Harris-Lewis, in  
private -- Mudge did not say he was concerned about a heart 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``After extensive testing, evaluation and review of all data, I  
believe that Mr. Lewis has a normal athlete's heart with normal 
functions,'' Mudge said then. ``Our testing showed no evidence of 
cardiomyopathy or abnormal life-threatening arrhythmias.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Harris-Lewis' attorney, Robert Harley, asked Mudge if he  
lied at the news conference, the doctor replied, ``What I did say 
was very limited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harley suggested that Mudge, suddenly in charge of care for  
``the most famous patient in Boston,'' was under pressure to tell 
Lewis, his wife, the Celtics and the public what they wanted to 
hear: that Lewis' condition was not as serious as first believed, 
and that he would play in the National Basketball Association 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	A team of 12 doctors at New England Baptist Hospital initially  
diagnosed Lewis with cardiac arrhythmia after he collapsed during a 
playoff game in April 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lewises turned to Mudge at Brigham and Women's Hospital for  
a second opinion, and he initially agreed. But after further tests, 
Mudge revised the diagnosis and told Lewis he had neurocardiogenic 
syncope. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis sued Mudge and consultants Mark Creager and Peter  
Friedman, claiming they misdiagnosed and mistreated her husband's 
heart condition. A third consultant later settled for an 
undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge was expected to continue testifying today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 09:12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Bond Funds: Handle With Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Spectacularly successful as they have been with  
many other types of investments, mutual funds don't score very high 
in the huge market for U.S. government securities. 
</P>
<P>
	As of the latest tally by Morningstar Inc. in Chicago,  
government-bond mutual funds had assets of about $115 billion -- in 
a market where the amount of securities outstanding runs to several 
trillion dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	General and specialty bond funds, which invest in corporate and  
other types of bonds, are more than three times as big as 
government-bond funds, with combined assets of about $390 billion. 
Municipal bond funds, at a little more than $300 billion in assets, 
also are much larger. 
</P>
<P>
	Funds that invest in long-term government bonds are so few and  
so small they almost qualify as an endangered species, with less 
than $6 billion in their coffers. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not as though they are dealing in something dangerous or  
obscure. Bonds issued by the U.S. Treasury are generally accepted 
as the safest investment you can make, and they are very popular 
with individual investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The story of why government funds aren't any bigger than they  
are sheds some light on the limitations of the fund concept -- how 
it happens that, with all their benefits, funds aren't the answer 
to every investment need in every situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of the things favoring bond funds in general don't carry  
the same weight in the long-term government group,'' observes 
analyst Steve Chung in the Morningstar Mutual Funds research 
service's latest report on the sector. 
</P>
<P>
	``For example, the diversified portfolios of bond funds give  
investors an easy defense against credit risk. But credit risk 
isn't a concern in the realm of U.S. government securities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's assumed that Uncle Sam is the least likely, among all the  
world's issuers of debt, ever to default on a scheduled payment of 
interest or principal. If there ever was a U.S. default, it's also 
assumed that all other debt securities (and stocks too, for that 
matter) would go into the tank as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Want even more assurance? Consider that Uncle Sam, who promises  
to pay off bonds in dollars, has the power to print more dollars in 
case of a shortfall. Such an action might cause severe inflation 
problems, but the contractual promise of the bonds would be 
honored. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung adds, ``Bond funds also give investors access to  
professional money managers who are trained to locate the best 
opportunities in the fixed-income market. However, the 
government-bond market is highly efficient, and few opportunities 
exist for managers to add value.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still another key distinction: Individual investors often find  
it very difficult to buy corporate, municipal or foreign bonds in 
bite-sized amounts at advantageous prices. Commissions and market 
spreads, or the difference between a dealer's buy and sell prices, 
can cost a bundle. 
</P>
<P>
	But Treasury securities can be bought direct from the government  
without commission charges, in denominations as small as $1,000 to 
$10,000. Information on this program is available from any Federal 
Reserve bank or branch. 
</P>
<P>
	And of course, if you invest directly in bonds, you don't have  
to bear the expense of fund management and administrative costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung is quick to add that government-bond funds aren't devoid  
of any attractions. ``The funds in this group do have some clear 
advantages over individual bonds. Portfolio construction and 
rebalancing is easier using funds, for example,'' he notes. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, in a fund portfolio the interest payments tend be spread  
out evenly over time, allowing for that money to be reinvested 
continuously through the ups and downs of the interest rate cycle. 
</P>
<P>
	If all your money is tied up in a single bond, you run the risk  
that its interest-payment or maturity date will come at a time when 
interest rates are low and the options for reinvesting the money 
aren't attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	However -- and this is a big however -- if you want an investment  
that matures at a set time, bonds are likely to fill the bill much 
better than a bond fund, which as a managed portfolio has no set 
maturity date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
