<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rescued Toddler Home From Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MULVANE, Kan. (AP) -- Jessy Kraus gave his mother a smile she'll  
never forget after the little boy was rescued from a well in a 
five-hour ordeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a miracle and it is a blessing,'' said the boy's mother,  
Karen Kraus. 
</P>
<P>
	Jessy, who is 17 months old, was released Friday from HCA Wesley  
Medical Center 12 hours after his nationally televised rescue from 
the well in his back yard in Mulvane, 20 miles south of Wichita. He 
had been trapped 16 feet below ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters had to dig a hole by hand alongside the well to get  
him out because they feared the use of heavy equipment would injure 
him. Rescuers and neighbors cheered when firefighter Tim Deneen 
brought Jessy to the surface. 
</P>
<P>
	``He smiled for me. He knew me. He looked at me. It is a smile I  
won't ever forget,'' Mrs. Kraus said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jessy suffered from exposure and some scrapes, Dr. Curt Pickert  
said at the Wichita hospital. The boy ate a plate of scrambled eggs 
at the hospital, then went home to take a nap. 
</P>
<P>
	``A little boy is going to live and have a normal life thanks to  
them,'' said Annie Schlaegel, the boy's grandmother, of his 
rescuers. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Kraus and her husband, Jerry, who also have an 8-year-old  
son, Cody, were digging the dirt well in a new subdivision. They 
wouldn't say why they needed the well, which is only 8 to 10 inches 
wide and 25 feet deep. 
</P>
<P>
	But authorities said the well was probably being dug to water  
the yard. Private wells are common and not illegal in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	The ordeal was reminiscent of that of a Texas toddler more than  
a decade ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In Midland, Texas, in 1987, the case of 18-month-old Jessica  
McClure created a nationwide sensation after she fell into an 
abandoned well and became trapped 22 feet down in a hole 8 inches 
wide. It took emergency crews 2 1/2 days to reach the little girl. 
</P>
<P>
	Kraus, a truck driver, saw his son fall in but couldn't reach  
him in time, Sedgwick County Fire Marshal Greg Thompson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``All it took was one second,'' Mrs. Kraus said.  
</P>
<P>
	Under flood lights, about 50 emergency workers dug a hole  
alongside the well shaft, seven feet away. The distraught parents 
mostly stayed inside as rescuers worked to reach the boy. 
</P>
<P>
	Oxygen tubes were lowered into the well and warm air was pumped  
in to keep the boy from getting too cold. Lumber was used to shore 
up the well's sides to prevent rocks and dirt from falling on 
Jessy. 
</P>
<P>
	After the shaft was dug, rescuers tunneled over to the well 2  
feet below the boy. As they got closer, they could hear him 
whimpering. 
</P>
<P>
	``My stomach was churning the whole time, knowing what he must  
be going through,'' Deneen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Deneen feverishly clawed through the last few inches of dirt to  
reach Jessy, then caressed the boy's tiny, mud-encrusted feet and 
told him: ``Hang in there, just a few more minutes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, Deneen cleared enough space behind Jessy's head to  
insert a backboard the child could be strapped to. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's my little buddy,'' Deneen told Mrs. Kraus as she rushed  
to see Jessy. ``I know he is your kid, but he is special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A video camera lowered into the well helped rescuers get to the  
boy, who tugged on a rope during the rescue. 
</P>
<P>
	Choking back tears at a news conference, Jerry Kraus said he  
couldn't think of a word big enough to thank everybody. Mrs. Kraus 
found some words of her own. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think you are heroes, and we want to thank God for letting  
us keep Jessy,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 10:32:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Rejects Memphis Police Quotas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Racial quotas used by the Memphis Police  
Department to promote black officers for more than two decades have 
been ruled unconstitutional by a federal judge. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Jerome Turner set a June 30 hearing to  
determine how much money should be awarded to white officers who 
were denied promotions because of the quotas. 
</P>
<P>
	The city began using a quota system in the early 1970s under  
pressure from the U.S. Justice Department to try to remedy past 
discrimination against black officers. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 100 white officers sued in 1989 and 1990 after they  
were passed over for promotion. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, the city created race-neutral tests. The ``validated''  
tests measure job-related abilities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, if the city had developed such a validated test, the  
city would be released from the obligations to use affirmative 
action,'' Turner said in his ruling Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The court finds that the city could have developed a validated  
testing procedure prior to 1988, and that its attempts to do so 
were meager.'' 
</P>
<P>
	City attorney Louis Britt had no comment on whether the city  
will appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 22:21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Threats Force Class To End Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALLEN, Texas (AP) -- The school board in this Dallas suburb has  
canceled the remaining two weeks of class for all 9,800 students 
because of repeated bomb threats following the Colorado school 
massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	Parents were angry and students puzzled when they found the  
schools closed on Friday morning. The board's decision was reached 
only hours earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not sure we can guarantee the safety of every student.  
We had to err on the side of caution,'' said district spokesman Tim 
Carroll. ``We have to assume every threat is real even if deep down 
a lot of us think these are kids, these are threats, these are just 
jokes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Allen schools received 11 bomb threats this week, but no bombs  
were found. A 15-year-old middle school student was charged with 
calling in a threat from his school cafeteria. 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll said the threats were taken more seriously because of  
the assault that left 15 people dead at Columbine High School in 
Littleton, Colo., last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just think it's ridiculous,'' parent Kurt Dowd said of the  
cancellation. ``I think they're playing right into the hands of 
these people that are perpetrating this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Allen High School, students were allowed inside Friday -- but  
only after passing newly installed metal detectors -- to gather 
backpacks and other belongings. Few took the threats seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kids trying to test the system,'' Vinh Nguyen said. ``I  
don't think they mean to hurt anybody, they just want to get out of 
school. I'm pretty ticked off. They got what they wanted.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
