<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Auburn Star Signs With Agent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOBILE, Ala. (AP) -- Former Auburn receiver Robert Baker, paroled  
in March after serving 10 months of a 15-year sentence for drug 
trafficking, will take his chances with the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the question is whether any NFL team will take a chance on  
him. 
</P>
<P>
	``For our football team, we wouldn't mess with him,'' said Bruce  
Lemmerman, director of college scouting for the New Orleans Saints. 
``Does he get an opportunity? It will be hard. How do you sell it 
to your fans? They're going to look at this guy's past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baker, who had one year of college eligibility left, has signed  
with an agent and will enter the NFL's supplemental draft. His 
agent, Rick Davis of West Palm Beach, Fla., was skeptical at first. 
But Davis is also the lawyer for former Auburn coach Terry Bowden, 
who recommended he speak to Baker. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm real impressed after talking with him,'' Davis told the  
Mobile Register. ``He's sorry for what he did and he knows he made 
a mistake. Some people will never let him forget it. But he has an 
opportunity to influence people in a positive way now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis did not return calls from The Associated Press seeking  
comment Friday. NFL spokesman Greg Aiello was out of the office and 
unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker, 23 of Gainesville, Fla., met with new coach Tommy  
Tuberville shortly after his release about possibly returning this 
fall as a fifth-year senior. But he dropped out of school this week 
and will enter the draft in either June or July. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him he would enhance his position in the draft if he  
went back to school,'' Davis said. ``We didn't recruit him. This 
was his decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baker hasn't played football in three years. He led Auburn with  
1,174 all-purpose yards in 1996, including 526 yards receiving. He 
was academically ineligible for the 1997 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker was sentenced in May 1998 after pleading guilty to  
trafficking cocaine. The mandatory three-year sentence for 
trafficking was waived. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
