<HEADLINE> Pipe Bombs Found on Ind. Van </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRAZIL, Ind. (AP) -- A 13-year-old boy with a grudge against a  
girl at school was arrested Friday on suspicion of planting at 
least seven pipe bombs -- one of which exploded -- on two vehicles 
belonging to her parents. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy was taken out of his middle school by police and is  
scheduled to appear in juvenile court next week. 
</P>
<P>
	A pipe bomb attached to Tonya M. Corn's van and exploded Friday  
as she was driving, but she was not hurt. Police later found two 
unexploded bombs that fell off her van and four more pipe bombs 
attached to her husband's vehicle at the couple's home. 
</P>
<P>
	``It all happened today, and we ain't in the mood to discuss  
nothing,'' Mike Corn said. ``We've told our story to the police 30 
or 40 times today already.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The boy's name was not released.  
</P>
<P>
	State Trooper David Kuhn said the couple told police several  
weeks ago that the boy was stalking the family. The stalking began 
after the couple's daughter told school officials the boy had 
brought a gun to school, Kuhn said. 
</P>
<P>
	School Superintendent Thomas Rohr said rumors that the boy had  
brought a gun to school were never confirmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
