<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 13:11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Forecaster Lacks Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT COLLINS, Colo. (AP) -- William Gray, a scientist who has  
been issuing a closely read hurricane forecast every year for more 
than a decade, may be forced out of the prediction business for 
lack of funding. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't get money,'' said Gray, a professor at Colorado State  
University. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray, 69, used to get funding from the National Oceanic and  
Atmospheric Administration, the National Science Foundation and the 
insurance industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The insurance industry stopped paying when his federally funded  
research became available for free on the Internet. NOAA has 
rejected his requests for funding for the past six years. The 
Federal Emergency Management Agency also rejected funding. 
</P>
<P>
	His only support now comes from the NSF, $145,000, which after  
overhead and other research, amounts to about $50,000, he said. He 
said he needs $400,000 a year to keep his forecasts coming. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray said he believes his research has been rejected because he  
has publicly questioned the validity of sophisticated computer 
programs -- called numeric models -- that are becoming the dominant 
method of forecasting. The programs use mathematical formulas to 
forecast the weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray uses computer programs but primarily bases his predictions  
on what he calls the cultural method, or study of the past. 
</P>
<P>
	A March 30 rejection letter from NOAA said Gray's grant proposal  
``lacks sufficient discussion of methodology to permit an effective 
evaluation of the approach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Tomastik of NOAA said the decisions to reject Gray's  
proposals were made by a peer review committee of fellow 
scientists, not the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray's forecasts are read closely along the Atlantic and Gulf  
coasts. 
</P>
<P>
	His forecasts have been close to the mark during the 16 years he  
made predictions, with 1997 the major exception. He predicted seven 
hurricanes with three of them major; only three occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	``More times than not he is on the right side of climatology,''  
said Max Mayfield, deputy director of the National Hurricane Center 
in Coral Gables, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	For the 1999 season, Gray has predicted 14 named storms and nine  
hurricanes, four of them major. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 21:11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S., China Work To Resolve Dispute  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United States and China tried Friday  
to narrow their differences over NATO's attack on Beijing's embassy 
in Belgrade, one of several conflicts related to Yugoslavia that 
have deadlocked much of the Security Council's work. The two 
countries were working on a council reaction to the embassy attack 
and a humanitarian resolution on Kosovo that has become so highly 
politicized that China and Russia announced that it would abstain 
from the vote. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Reports Heaviest Bombing Yet  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO is reporting its heaviest  
bombing of the seven-week air campaign against Yugoslavia. The 
alliance says it concentrated attacks against the 40,000 Serb 
troops and special police in Kosovo, hitting heavy armor and arms 
supplies hidden in tunnels. On Friday, NATO bombs hit a convoy of 
ethnic Albanian refugees and killed dozens, Yugoslavia claimed. 
Serb media was reporting 79 bodies had been found. NATO says it's 
investigating the incident. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Seeks Campaign Money  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- On a $3 million fund-raising tour of the West  
Coast, President Clinton told Democrats Friday that his 6 1/2 years in 
the White House have been ``a labor of love.'' Party patrons were 
paying as much as $25,000 for a weekend meal with Clinton. He spoke 
at a $200,000 Seattle luncheon before heading to a $500,000 dinner 
in the San Francisco Bay area. The president's four-day take for 
Democrats -- with events also in Beverly Hills, San Diego and Las 
Vegas -- was expected to top $3 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Rejects Air Pollution Rules  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal appeals court Friday blocked the  
Environmental Protection Agency from imposing tougher air quality 
requirements the agency says are needed to protect people with 
respiratory problems and children. A three-judge panel acted on a 
lawsuit by a number of industry groups. The EPA said it will seek 
to appeal the ruling. 

</P>
<P>
	Minorities Lag in Health Care  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Minorities lag behind whites in the United  
States on nearly every health measure, according to a report 
documenting the widespread disparities. The inequalities are 
well-known among health professionals, who point to economics, 
health systems, racism and culture in trying to explain them. ``No 
simple solutions would eliminate these disparities,'' concludes the 
report, released Friday by the Commonwealth Fund, a New York-based 
research group. 

</P>
<P>
	Internet Poll Validity Questioned  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Pollsters gathering Friday  
said scientific polls could be drowned out by the proliferation of 
Internet surveys that they say don't accurately measure public 
opinion. Now pollsters are considering the possibility of a poll 
rating system that would require pollsters to inform the public and 
the media which polls are conducted with scientific standards. 
Pollsters struggled with the difficult problem during the annual 
meeting of the American Association for Public Opinion Research. 

</P>
<P>
	Congress Drops Gondola Compensation  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress has decided not to provide $40  
million in compensation for last year's accident in which a U.S. 
Marine jet killed 20 skiers in an Italian cable car. Italian 
officials called the move ``another insupportable slight.'' Senate 
and House negotiators dropped the provision this week from a 
package financing the air campaign against Yugoslavia and other 
items. It had been approved in March by the Senate, but ran into 
opposition in the House and from the Defense Department. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Plunges 193.87 Points  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average fell 193.87  
points to 10,913.32 Friday after a steep rise in consumer prices 
set off renewed worries about inflation. The Nasdaq fell 54.13 to 
2,527.87. The 0.7 percent rise in the consumer price index for 
April was the largest monthly gain in nearly nine years. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat Beat Knicks, Stay Alive  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With Tim Hardaway finding his scoring touch,  
Alonzo Mourning shutting down Patrick Ewing and Miami's bench 
giving it a sorely needed boost, the Heat staved off elimination 
Friday night by defeating New York 87-72. Hardaway had his highest 
scoring game of the series with 14 points, including a 3-pointer 
that put Miami ahead for good with 7:54 left. Mourning had 16 
points and 13 rebounds and held Ewing to three points and one 
rebound in the second half. 

</P>
<P>
	Sabres Slam Bruins 3-0  
</P>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Dominik Hasek made 24 saves as the Buffalo  
Sabres beat the Boston Bruins 3-0 on Friday night and moved within 
one victory of clinching their second-round series. Alexei Zhitnik, 
Vaclav Varada and Michael Peca scored as the Sabres took a 3-1 lead 
in the Eastern Conference series and improved their record to a 
playoff-best 7-1. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
