<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 17:21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jazz or Kings, Blazers Don't Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The question was inevitable, and the  
Portland Trail Blazers handled it like skilled politicians. 
</P>
<P>
	Which team would they rather play in the second round of the  
playoffs, the Utah Jazz or the Sacramento Kings? 
</P>
<P>
	``Careful who you wish for -- you may get 'em,'' Blazers coach  
Mike Dunleavy said. ``Whoever it is, it is. And we'll take care of 
business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It would seem obvious who the Blazers would rather have win the  
surprisingly competitive best-of-5 series. Portland swept all four 
games against Sacramento during the regular season, while the 
Blazers lost two of three to Utah, the two-time defending Western 
Conference champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Blazers point guard Damon Stoudamire was so certain the Jazz  
would win Game 4 against the Kings on Friday night and even the 
series 2-2 that he didn't even plan to watch it on TV. ``I'm going 
out,'' he said, adding that he'd monitor updates from a bar 
downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	``The series isn't over by any means,'' Stoudamire said after  
Friday's 2 1/2-hour practice. ``We need to have a mindset to play 
Utah, and Sacramento would be a bonus. Everybody in here feels 
pretty confident against Sacramento. But against Utah, we'd have to 
take it up to a whole other level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other Blazers were more leery of the Kings, the only team to  
average more than 100 points a game in the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to wipe that slate clean,'' guard Jim Jackson said.  
He recalled a similar situation when he played for Ohio State in 
1992. The Buckeyes had beaten Michigan's Fab Five twice during the 
regular season, then lost to the Wolverines in the NCAA 
tournament's round of eight. 
</P>
<P>
	``In that game, in that situation, they were the better team on  
that night,'' Jackson said. ``So in this series, you see that 
Sacramento is playing a lot better than Utah, even though Utah beat 
them three times during the regular season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arvydas Sabonis, Portland's stoic Lithuanian center, summed up  
the Blazers' confidence when a reporter asked if he was preparing 
differently for the Jazz or the Kings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Same,'' he said simply.  
</P>
<P>
	Blazers guard Isaiah Rider didn't practice Friday because of a  
sprained right knee suffered in Wednesday's series-clinching 
victory over Phoenix. Rider was going for a loose ball when the 
Suns' Tom Gugliotta fell backward into Rider's knee. Dunleavy said 
Rider's condition has improved, and he should be ready when the 
second round begins. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's feeling better,'' Dunleavy said.  
</P>
<P>
	All of the Blazers are feeling fine, having advanced to the  
second round for the first time in seven years. Now they're 
thinking bigger, while holding out hope of regaining homecourt 
advantage for the second round should Sacramento win. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expected to get past the first round,'' Jackson said.  
``It's a good position to be in. It gives you a sense that we've 
already made it to the next level. Now everybody else has to come 
to that next level with us.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 06:13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls Paper To Back Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hearing that The New York Times was about to  
publish a story on the state of Vice President Al Gore's 
presidential campaign, President Clinton picked up a phone and put 
in his two cents' worth. 
</P>
<P>
	The president's take: The campaign, which many pundits say is  
off to a bumpy start, ``is in a lot better shape now than it was 
eight weeks ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Times said Clinton called Thursday night to volunteer his  
impressions. The president said he was not alarmed by the state of 
the campaign and still expects Gore to win the Democratic 
nomination next year. He also acknowledged advising Gore to loosen 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is true that I have urged him to go out there and enjoy  
this,'' Clinton said. ``I have told him to go out and have a good 
time. I want people to know him the way I know him. I want people 
to see him the way I see him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton specifically praised Gore's decision to name former Rep.  
Tony Coelho, D-Calif., as his campaign manager: ``He's a strong man 
and an experienced person and he'll really take a lot of the 
burdens off the vice president.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
