<DOCNO> APW19990514.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 01:31:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Face Elimination Tonight  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It's time to find out if Pat Riley has another  
bit of motivational magic up his sleeve. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley's Miami Heat are on the brink of elimination tonight in  
Game 4 of their first-round series against the New York Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything we've worked for, everything we've talked about is  
on the brink. We've got to bring it all and play well,'' Riley said 
Thursday. ``It can't just be a maniacal effort, it's got to be a 
maniacal effort with effective offense and defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A big part of that equation will be Tim Hardaway, whose play has  
been unproductive throughout the series with the exception of his 
11 assists in Game 2. Hardaway still wasn't talking Thursday, so 
his numbers were left to speak for themselves: 6-for-32 from the 
field, 1-for-14 from 3-point range, 22 total points and one 
ejection. 
</P>
<P>
	``Evidently, things haven't been going his way thus far,''  
teammate Alonzo Mourning said, ``but I know he can turn things 
around. I've seen him turn things around, and this series is far 
from being over with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway had a miserable night in Game 3 as the Heat lost by 24  
-- their second blowout defeat in the series. He shot just 1-for-8, 
including 0-for-5 on 3-pointers, and lost his composure by getting 
ejected early in the fourth quarter when he realized the game was a 
lost cause. 
</P>
<P>
	At practice Thursday, Hardaway refused to speak to the media and  
stood on the court shooting while his teammates tried to come up 
with explanations for his slump. 
</P>
<P>
	``Y'all keep talking about Timmy, Timmy, and Timmy's our point  
guard,'' Mourning said. ``But listen to me, we've got a lot of 
confidence in him. He knows what he has to do to get us going, and 
he's capable of doing that. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tim's a competitor and a clutch player all his career, and if  
anybody can come back, he can,'' Dan Majerle said. ``Tim's our 
leader obviously, but if Tim's not doing it someone else has to do 
it. Look at everybody's numbers, except Zo's, and they're down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the Heat's second-leading scorer in this series is  
Voshon Lenard, who has been limited to 23 minutes of garbage time 
in Game 1 and Game 3, but has 24 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Take away Lenard's 6-for-8 shooting from 3-point range, and the  
rest of the Heat are a shocking 8-for-49. At one point in Game 3, 
they were 0-for-17 from behind the arc. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley seemed to hint that Lenard might get a little more playing  
time tonight. Majerle has been taking up most of the minutes at 
shooting guard, but has been hampered by two bone spurs in his 
collarbone -- both of which are fractured. 
</P>
<P>
	Majerle has shot just 2-for-13 in the series, Keith Askins  
hasn't scored a single point, Jamal Mashburn has gone to the 
free-throw line only three times and P.J. Brown' scoring and 
rebounding numbers have dipped. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks have tried to contain Hardaway by picking him up  
defensively well above the 3-point line and by having their big men 
sprint back on defense to establish position in case Hardaway 
drives past his man in transition. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway's best effort of the series came in Game 2, when he had  
11 assists, but shot 1-for-5 from the field. In Game 1, he shot 
4-for-19. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Game 2, I don't think we were successful against him at  
all,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``He dominated the game 
without shooting, and I think that's what great players do. As far 
as the other games, everybody goes through tough stretches, and 
he's just gone through a tough stretch. But we never have, and 
never will, underestimate him. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks are trying to become just the second eighth-seeded  
playoff team in NBA history to knock off a No. 1 seed. Denver did 
it to Seattle in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
