<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish Twins Impress NHL Scouts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LILLEHAMMER, Norway (AP) -- A couple of shy Swedish twins who  
would prefer to continue playing together are getting plenty of 
attention from NHL scouts at the World Hockey Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	While Daniel and Henrik Sedin haven't stood out on a team loaded  
with NHL talent, the 18-year-olds are expected to hold center stage 
at June's NHL entry draft . Many expect them to among the first 
five players chosen. 
</P>
<P>
	Having played on the same team all their hockey lives, and on  
the same line for the past six years, Henrik and Daniel are not 
anxious to be split up. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the twins were toying with the idea that Daniel, the  
higher-rated and younger by six minutes, might go into this year's 
draft, while Henrik would wait until 2000, increasing the odds of 
both ending up in the same city. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently, however, both seem to be leaning toward joining the  
draft this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, I'd prefer to play with my brother, it would be  
fun,'' Daniel said. ``It's easy to play with Henrik, so it would 
help. But it's not all-important. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we go on different teams that's just part of the business.  
We can be away from each other, that's not a problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ordinarily, players must make their decision by May 1, but the  
twins received an extension until 10 days after the world 
championships. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sedins will get one last chance to impress the scouts when  
Sweden plays Canada on Saturday for third place in the tournament. 
The Czech Republic also Finland in the first of two games for the 
title. 
</P>
<P>
	If they split, a shootout will decide the championship after  
Game 2 on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The twins are just the latest talent to come out of  
Ornskoldsvik, a little hockey factory about 400 miles north of 
Stockholm that has produced NHL stars Peter Forsberg, Niklas 
Sundstrom and Markus Naslund. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel and Henrik had a strong regular season, and an  
even-better Swedish Hockey League championship series for MoDo. For 
that, they were rewarded with an invitation to the national team's 
training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever they decide, the pair said they would play at least  
another year in Sweden before heading for North America. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to get stronger and better at everything,'' Henrik  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	So identical are the twins, only their uniform numbers and they  
way the hold their sticks give them separate identities in the 
minds of many. Henrik is right-handed shot and Daniel shoots from 
the left side. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are so similar, and it's obvious they have the same train  
of thought,'' said former NHL player Rich Sutter, twin brother to 
the San Jose Sharks' Ron Sutter. ``Just watching them you can tell 
there is something else there, something undefinable. 
</P>
<P>
	``They remind me of Ron and myself, the same patterns are there.  
``It's hard to put into words, but I guess there's a bit of magic 
there. I can see it in those kids.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the twins admit there is a special bond which probably  
goes beyond simple time, they downplay the magic between them. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not telepathy or anything. If he's hurt I don't think I  
feel anything,'' Daniel said.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But we think very much alike and we are very close,'' Henrik  
said. ``We do think the same way, we finish each others' sentences, 
we answer questions the same way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That proved to be true when they were separately asked if there  
was a leader between them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm the boss. I'm older,'' was Henrik's answer.  
</P>
<P>
	``Me, I'm the boss,'' Daniel said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
