<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Lift Limits on Duke Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- Federal regulators who slapped restrictions  
on medical researchers at Duke University Medical Center amid 
concerns about safety have lifted their limits on human 
experiments. 
</P>
<P>
	The Office for Protection from Research Risks, a division of the  
National Institutes of Health, on Monday ordered Duke to stop 
enrolling new patients in federally funded medical experiments. 
</P>
<P>
	The regulators said administrators at one of the country's  
leading clinical research centers had been too slow improving 
oversight of experiments. 
</P>
<P>
	The OPRR on Friday released researchers from the freeze. A day  
earlier, Duke administrators submitted a plan for ensuring the 
hospital's Institutional Review Board could keep up with 2,000 
experiments involving thousands of human subjects. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said it was satisfied with the plan.  
</P>
<P>
	``They presented to us adequate plans to correct the problems we  
had identified,'' said Dr. Michael Carome, the OPRR's top 
compliance officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``But there is still work to be done. We view this as a new  
beginning for them and expect significant improvements in their 
program to protect human subjects.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agency found that members of the board -- which gives  
approval for tests and monitors patients in those studies -- had 
voted on projects in ways that created potential conflicts of 
interest and did not review research to assure patient safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke officials said that problems cited were mostly due to poor  
record keeping and that no patients were endangered. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke has about 2,000 research projects under way involving  
thousands of patients. Duke received $228 million in 1998 for 
federal and non-governmental research, with tens of millions for 
human clinical trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Carome said that 250 to 300 government-funded projects remain  
under suspension until Duke shows the projects have been 
appropriately reviewed by a review board. 
</P>
<P>
	Recruitment of subjects and other actions in those projects  
cannot proceed until the new review is completed. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Duke had been banned from recruiting new patients to  
federally funded programs, research was allowed to continue on 
those already enrolled in such experiments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 20:51:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sanders Returns To Cincinnati </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Reggie Sanders had a tender hamstring when he  
returned to Cincinnati on Friday, and he knew how that would play. 
</P>
<P>
	The fans would say: Reggie's hurt? So what else is new?  
</P>
<P>
	It didn't bother him. Sanders has started his baseball career  
over in San Diego, where he says the fans haven't made such an 
issue out of his frequent injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``When my hamstring was hurting and when my back started hurting  
a little bit, it's like the media and the fans (in San Diego) were 
saying, `He plays so hard, I see exactly why he gets hurt,''' 
Sanders said. ``But if it was the media here, it's something 
totally different. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything's good. I've moved on.''  
</P>
<P>
	After seven seasons in Cincinnati, the Reds grew weary of his  
undependability and traded him to San Diego on Feb. 2 as part of 
the Greg Vaughn deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, 31, had missed half of the 1996 and 1997 seasons  
because of myriad injuries. Fans grew frustrated and teammates made 
jokes about his brittleness behind his back. 
</P>
<P>
	The outfielder developed a live-and-let-live attitude in his  
final seasons with the Reds: If the fans wanted to question his 
toughness, let 'em. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's one thing I had to learn. That's one thing that made me  
the player I am today,'' Sanders said. ``You can't worry about what 
the critics say. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm the only one who knows what's going on with my body. There  
was one point when I was a younger player that it used to bother 
me. Now it's not an issue anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders has been bothered by a sore back, wrist and hamstring  
this season, but played in 28 of the Padres' 34 games. He left a 
game after the fifth inning Wednesday because of a sore hamstring, 
but was in the lineup Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	There were a few boos but not much of a reaction overall when he  
came to the plate in the first inning and flew out. He ended up 
going 1-for-4 with a walk in a 7-3 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Before arriving in Cincinnati, he said he was determined to play  
in the city where he felt maligned. He was more diplomatic about 
his feelings Friday, but he was in the lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he wanted to show Cincinnatians something, he said,  
``No, I have nothing to prove. This is not a proving session for me 
-- coming here to try to get 15 home runs or this and that. It's not 
about that. It's just about us trying to come in here and win a 
series and go back home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, neither team has gotten the advantage in the trade.  
Sanders is batting .295 with seven homers, 12 RBIs and eight 
steals. Vaughn is hitting .209 with eight homers, 20 RBIs and four 
steals. Both teams were in last place in their divisions before the 
game began. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders said he hasn't followed the Reds since he was traded,  
except to glance in the newspapers occasionally. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm one of those people that when I move, I move,'' he said.  
``I've always been that way. It's nothing personal. That's just the 
way I am.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
