<DOCNO> APW19990514.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 15:31:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Passes Gun Background Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Republicans forced passage of new  
restrictions on gun show sales Friday, overriding solid Democratic 
opposition and a complaint by President Clinton that the provision 
was ``riddled with high-caliber loopholes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vote, 48-47, marked a retreat on the part of the GOP and  
came in an atmosphere of intense political jockeying over gun 
control spurred by last month's shooting rampage at a Colorado high 
school. 
</P>
<P>
	``They know the public wants gun control, but they're afraid to  
offend the National Rifle Association,'' Sen. Charles Schumer, 
D-N.Y., said of the Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Countered Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, ``The National Rifle  
Association hasn't had a thing to do with it. I don't care whether 
they accept it or not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said their proposal would require background checks  
for anyone who buys a weapon at a gun show. The GOP had refused 
earlier in the week to accept such a plan, and Hatch and others 
said they might be open to further concessions on other gun control 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, it was not clear whether the bill would ever  
come to a final vote. Lawmakers of the two parties accused each 
other of laboring to make sure it died. 
</P>
<P>
	Senatorial tempers flared during the day, as Hatch and Schumer  
clashed on the floor and the Utah Republican later challenged 
Clinton heatedly. ``The president doesn't know what he's talking 
about,'' Hatch said. ``He hasn't told the truth on this from word 
one, and we all know it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, led by Hatch and Sen. Larry Craig of Idaho, said  
their intention was to require a background check on anyone seeking 
to make a purchase at a gun show. On Wednesday, Republicans muscled 
through passage of a plan requiring only voluntary checks in some 
cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said even the revised measure was loophole-filled.  
Sensing the political upper hand, they refused to allow Republicans 
to clarify their proposal further, forcing GOP senators to cast 
votes on a measure that Clinton attacked vigorously earlier in the 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new Senate Republican bill is still riddled with  
high-caliber loopholes,'' the president said at the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``It won't stop criminals from buying guns at gun shows. At the  
same time, it will open up a new pawnshop loophole that lets 
convicted felons get guns at a local pawnshop. That's actually 
worse than current law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The maneuvering came on legislation to increase prosecution of  
juvenile offenders. Majority Leader Trent Lott brought the measure 
to the floor this week expressly to allow the political parties to 
respond to the shootings in the Columbine High School in which two 
student gunmen killed 12 fellow students and a teacher before 
killing themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats responded with a raft of gun control proposals, while  
Republicans generally sought to turn the debate toward violence 
present in modern-day television programming, movies, video games 
and the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	To underscore that, Lott issued a statement critical of  
Clinton's weekend fundraising trip to the West Coast. ``What's the 
message to our children? Democrats care about your safety, unless 
it's inconvenient to their partners in Hollywood,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate GOP aides conceded their party was outmaneuvered on the  
issue, and other officials said recent private polling indicated 
strong support for gun-control measures even among GOP voters who 
have opposed it in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Democrats have seized on a political issue, and I  
understand that and regret that,'' said Sen. John McCain of 
Arizona, a contender for the GOP presidential nomination and one of 
a group of senators who forced Craig and Hatch to reverse course. 
</P>
<P>
	On other issues, the Senate rejected a proposal by Schumer to  
require Internet Web sites to obtain federal licenses if they sell 
firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	And Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., announced that he and Hatch had  
agreed to a bipartisan proposal requiring sale of safety locks with 
guns. His office said the measure had the support of the Senate's 
gun-control advocates. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP amendment on gun shows was agreed to in an unusual  
atmosphere in which Hatch and members of the GOP leadership openly 
lobbied reluctant Republicans to save the provision from rejection. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, 47 Republicans and Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.,  
supported the proposal, while 40 Democrats and seven Republicans 
opposed it. The political crosscurrents were evidence in the roster 
of Republicans who voted against the proposal. They ranged from 
gun-control advocates such as John Chafee of Rhode Island to 
gun-control foes such as Sens. Bob Smith of New Hampshire and Craig 
Thomas of Wyoming. 
</P>
<P>
	Idaho's Craig said the intent of the GOP was clear: ``An  
individual who wants to obtain a gun at any gun show must submit to 
a background check.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats insisted the legislation was drafted to exempt some  
purchasers and raised several other objections. 
</P>
<P>
	They charged it would open up a new loophole by allowing anyone  
who pawned a gun to retrieve it without undergoing a background 
check. Democrats said that would allow criminals to obtain guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch and McCain both told reporters they were open to possible  
changes to address that issue. 
</P>
<P>
	But Craig balked at that and also objected to Democratic demands  
for new record-keeping requirements on the gun-sale instant checks. 
``I'm not going to let hysteria in this country let law-abiding 
citizens be dropped into a web,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
