<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 00:12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baffert's Lone Filly in Preakness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Trainer Bob Baffert's once-powerful brigade of  
classic horses has dwindled to one tough filly -- Excellent Meeting 
-- for Saturday's Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	After his other star filly, Silverbulletday, drew an unfavorable  
No. 14 post position, Baffert and owner Mike Pegram took her out of 
the Preakness on Thursday and put her in today's Black-Eyed Susan 
Stakes at Pimlico. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Bob will be well represented in the Derby with  
Excellent Meeting,'' Pegram said of the John Mabee-owned filly who 
finished fifth in the Kentucky Derby. ``We're disappointed because 
we came here to run in the Preakness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, Baffert confirmed that Prime Timber, fourth  
in the Derby, was out of the Preakness. A few days later, he said 
Prime Timber was also out of the Sir Barton Stakes on the 
undercard. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert's other Derby runner, General Challenge, was declared  
out of the Preakness the day after enduring a rough trip in the 
Derby and finishing 11th. 
</P>
<P>
	And by the time the Belmont Stakes rolls around on June 5,  
Baffert might not even saddle a horse in the race that brought him 
to the brink of winning Triple Crowns with Silver Charm in 1997 and 
Real Quiet in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``This could our last stop,'' Baffert said.  
</P>
<P>
	But that doesn't mean Excellent Meeting won't give Baffert a  
chance for his third straight Preakness win. 
</P>
<P>
	``It takes an exceptional filly to run with these colts, and  
Excellent Meeting showed it in the Derby with the trip that she 
had,'' Baffert said, pointing out she was only 2 1/4 lengths behind 
the winner, Charismatic, after a bumpy start. ``She easily could 
have won the race. She came out of it great. I wasn't pointing her 
to this race. I just let her tell me how she came out of the Derby, 
and I told Mr. Mabee she came out of it unbelievable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vicar, a disappointing 18th in the Derby after leaving from the  
No. 17 post, also was expected to be withdrawn from Preakness by 
trainer Carl Nafzger. Vicar, winner of the Fountain of Youth and 
Florida Derby, drew the No. 13 post in Wednesday night's draw. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not wishing anybody any bad luck,'' Nafzger said, ``but we  
just will not run from No. 13. If we scratch, it won't be until 
Saturday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Silverbulletday out, jockey Gary Stevens became available,  
and trainer Nick Zito signed him up to ride Stephen Got Even in the 
Preakness. Stevens replaces Chris McCarron, who sustained a 
hairline fracture near the left heel when he was unseated while 
working a horse Monday at Hollywood Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had luck with Gary in the past,'' Zito said. ``He rode  
Halory Hunter for us to win the Blue Grass last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Thursday's announced defections, a field of 12 3-year-olds  
is expected to go to the post in the 124th Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	Excellent Meeting, with Kent Desormeaux aboard, will attempt to  
become the fifth filly to win the Preakness -- the first since 
Nellie Morse in 1924. Winning Colors was the last filly to run in 
the Preakness, finishing third for trainer D. Wayne Lukas in 1988. 
She'll also be just the third filly to run in the second leg of the 
Triple Crown since 1939. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the Derby, Excellent Meeting won seven of 11 starts  
against her own sex, including handing Silverbulletday her only 
loss last August. 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee, runner-up to Derby winner Charismatic, was the 5-2  
favorite, with Excellent Meeting the second choice at 5-1. 
Charismatic, with Chris Antley aboard, was 6-1, with Cat Thief, 
Lukas' other Preakness colt, at 8-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Dubai-based Worldly Manner, who finished seventh in the Derby  
after staying in contention entering the stretch, might be another 
horse to watch. 
</P>
<P>
	``He came out of the Derby in great shape, and we're pretty  
confident,'' assistant trainer Tom Albertrani said. ``The Derby 
tuned him up a little.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Worldly Manner, with Jerry Bailey in the irons, was a 12-1  
choice. The colt is owned by Godolphin Racing, Inc., the Dubai arm 
of Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum and Sheikh Maktoum al Maktoum's 
racing empire. 
</P>
<P>
	Albertrani said Sheikh Mohammed will attend the Preakness.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
