<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No. 1 Ranking In Sight for Rafter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Patrick Rafter, covered with red dirt and slugging  
it out from the baseline, is moving closer to the No. 1 ranking. 
</P>
<P>
	He advanced to the semifinals of the Italian Open, grinding out  
a 4-6, 7-5, 6-1 victory Friday over Nicolas Lapentti of Ecuador. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a big surprise for me,'' Rafter said. ``You have all the  
top guys here, and I came in with very little form. I don't know 
why it's happening this week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rafter lost two consecutive opening-round matches before Rome.  
The serve-and-volleyer reached his first semifinal since September, 
when he won a second straight U.S. Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, if he keeps going and captures this tuneup for the French  
Open, he can vault from a No. 4 ranking to the top. 
</P>
<P>
	The three players ahead of him -- No. 1 Yevgeny Kafelnikov, No. 2  
Pete Sampras and No. 3 Carlos Moya -- have all lost already in Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm getting closer,'' Rafter said. ``But it's not necessarily  
driving me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On a day when his serve was average, Rafter had to rally after  
being down a set and 2-0 in the second to a player ranked No. 32 in 
the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures topped 80 degrees and occasional gusts kicked red  
dust into the players' eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	Rafter next faces No. 15 seed Felix Mantilla. The Spaniard  
advanced Friday with a 6-2, 6-4 victory over German qualifier David 
Prinosil. Mantilla's eight career titles all have come on clay. 
</P>
<P>
	In the other half of the draw, No. 3 seed Alex Corretja of Spain  
beat unseeded Argentine Franco Squillari 5-7, 7-6 (7-4), 7-5. 
Squillari squandered a match point when serving at 5-4 in the 
second set, clubbing a forehand into the net to end a 33-stroke 
rally. 
</P>
<P>
	No. 16 seed Gustavo Kuerten, the 1997 French Open champion,  
defeated No. 10 Karol Kucera 3-6, 6-4, 7-5 for the last semifinal 
berth. 
</P>
<P>
	Rafter was a surprise semifinalist at the French Open two years  
ago but has won no clay titles. He showed great patience against 
Lapentti. 
</P>
<P>
	``So far, the clay has been good for me,'' Rafter said. ``Many  
years in the past it hasn't been. I'm just enjoying every match 
because you never know how long it's going to last.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't look as if Friday's encounter would last long.  
Lapentti got to everything, put service returns at Rafter's ankles 
and rifled passing shots. 
</P>
<P>
	But the match shifted when Lapentti had three break points to go  
up 3-0 in the second set. Rafter used an ace and two service 
winners to stay alive. 
</P>
<P>
	``That would have been another kick in the head. That was one  
point that made the difference,'' Rafter said. ``It could have 
easily been 6-4, 6-1, and the crowd would have booed me off the 
court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he broke at love in the fourth game to make it 2-2, and  
broke again in the last game of the second set when Lapentti missed 
four backhands on extended rallies. 
</P>
<P>
	``You play well, your confidence grows,'' said Lapentti, an  
Australian Open semifinalist in January. ``You start to miss and it 
keeps getting worse.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 14:33:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stocks Plunge; Dow Ends Down 193.87  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks plunged today, with the Dow Jones  
industrial average tumbling more than 193 points, after the 
government's report of a steep rise in consumer prices renewed 
inflation worries and sent bond prices sharply lower. Analysts said 
the 0.7 percent rise in the consumer price index caught the market 
by surprise. The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 193.87 at 
10,913.32, more than wiping out a 106.82-point gain yesterday that 
gave the Dow a new closing high of 11,107.19. Broader stock 
indicators were sharply lower as well. The Nasdaq composite index 
fell 54.13 to 2,527.87. The inflation report led to a drop of more 
than two points in the price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury 
bond, pushing yields to 5.92 percent, the highest level in nearly a 
year. The bond yield stood at 5.89 percent late in the session. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,913.32 - 193.87
NYSE Issues:         Advances  670  Declines 2409  Unchgd  463
