</P>
<P>
	Consumer Prices Jump in April  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer prices took the biggest leap in nine  
years last month as Americans faced a record spike in gasoline 
prices and costs jumped for many other goods and services -- from 
food and clothing to doctor's office visits and airline tickets. 
April's 0.7 percent rise in the Consumer Price Index, reported by 
the Labor Department today, was the largest since October 1990 and 
pushed the rate of inflation so far this year to 3.3 percent on an 
annual basis. That compares with a 1.6 percent rise for all of 
1998, a year in which consumers benefited from falling energy 
prices. ``The best news on inflation is probably behind us,'' said 
Sung Won Sohn, an economist with Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. in Minneapolis. 
``Even though one month does not make a trend ..., I think we are 
beginning to see pent-up price pressure show up.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Court Voids EPA Air-Pollution Rules  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal appeals court today set aside new  
air quality standards issued by the Environmental Protection Agency 
in 1997, handing the Clinton administration a major environmental 
defeat. The three-judge panel, acting on a lawsuit by a number of 
industry groups, said the EPA in setting the new standards put in 
place a section of the 1990 Clean Air Act ``so loosely as to render 
them unconstitutional delegations of legislative power.'' The EPA 
issued a statement saying it will ask the Justice Department to 
appeal the decision, probably first to the full circuit, and if 
necessary to the U.S. Supreme Court. 

</P>
<P>
	Industrial Production Rises  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Production at the nation's factories, mines  
and utilities rose 0.6 percent in April, the Federal Reserve said, 
the most since August 1998. That followed a 0.5 percent March 
increase, revised to reflect much stronger industrial activity than 
previously reported. Output of consumer products rose 0.6 percent 
in April. Production of durable goods, including cars, furniture 
and home electronics jumped 2.1 percent in April. Production of 
nondurables, such as food and fuel, increased 0.2 percent with 
increases for chemicals and clothing offsetting disruptions at 
refineries. 

</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing May Buy U S West  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Baby Bell phone company U S West Inc. is in  
talks to be acquired by Global Crossing Ltd., a telecommunications 
upstart run by a former AT&AMP;T executive, a person familiar with the 
situation said today. U S West declined comment. Based in Denver, 
it provides phone service in 14 Western and midwestern states. 
Global Crossing, which is building a worldwide fiber optic network 
and recently agreed to buy a phone company named Frontier Corp., 
did not return calls seeking comment. Earlier this year, the 
Bermuda-based company lured Robert Annunziata away from AT&AMP;T to be 
its chief executive. U S West shares were at 62 1/2, up 2 1/4. Global 
Crossing shares were at 61 3/8, up 1 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Survey: Black Women Invest Less  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Black women want to invest in stocks, but  
they've been stymied by family demands such as caring for children 
and financially supporting others, according to a study released 
today about the investment attitudes of blacks and whites. Overall, 
blacks are underinvested because of ``formidable cultural and 
demographic factors,'' even as the bull market still roars on Wall 
Street, according to the second annual survey sponsored by Ariel 
Mutual Funds and Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. ``After working so hard to 
join the middle class, many blacks are still missing out on the 
greatest wealth-building opportunity in American history,'' said 
John Rogers, president of Ariel Mutual Funds, a black-owned 
investment firm. 

</P>
<P>
	Chase Manhattan Exec Eyed for Fed  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House is getting closer to choosing  
a banker active in lending to disadvantaged people and businesses 
as a new governor of the Federal Reserve Board. The Clinton 
administration is currently tangling with Senate Banking Committee 
head Phil Gramm, R-Texas, over federal requirements for banks to do 
that kind of lending. Any White House nominee for the post would 
have to be approved by the banking panel before being confirmed by 
the full Senate. Carol J. Parry is an executive vice president of 
Chase Manhattan Bank, the nation's third-largest. She is in charge 
of community development lending programs, making her responsible 
for loans for low- and moderate-income housing, commercial 
revitalization projects and businesses owned by women and 
minorities. 

</P>
