<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Triple Transplant Performed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A Michigan businessman was adjusting to a new  
heart, liver and kidney following an extremely rare 
triple-transplant operation performed last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent Slater, 64, of Rockford, Mich., became only the second  
person to undergo such surgery in the United States, according to 
the Virginia-based United Network of Organ Sharing, which tracks 
all U.S. organ transplants. 
</P>
<P>
	Slater needed the May 7 operation, which took 14 hours, because  
of the combined effects of rheumatic fever and a hepatitis C 
infection. He also suffered from progressive heart failure, which 
prevented vital organs from getting enough oxygen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel pretty good, considering,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	University of Chicago Hospitals spokesman John Easton said  
Slater remained in serious condition early today. Doctors 
considered it too early to say whether his body would reject the 
new organs, Easton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors said that Slater's heart was transplanted first,  
followed by the liver -- the riskiest part of the operation since 
the solution used to preserve the liver prior to transplant can be 
deadly to a heart if not flushed out properly. The kidney was 
transplanted last. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Michael Millis oversaw Slater's liver and kidney transplants  
and Dr. Valluvan Jeevanandam transplanted his heart. All the organs 
came from the same donor. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Thomas Starzl, who in 1989 performed the only other U.S.  
heart-liver-kidney transplant, lauded the Chicago doctors' 
accomplishment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a big deal,'' said Starzl, a retired surgeon at the  
University of Pittsburgh Medical Center. ``Every stage of the 
enterprise is more complex than in a normal transplant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Starzl's triple-transplant patient -- 26-year-old Lisa Martin --  
died of kidney disease four months after her operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Such radical surgeries have raised ethical questions about  
giving multiple organs to one person instead of trying to save more 
patients. There are 66,000 Americans awaiting major organ 
transplants. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors said in Slater's case, the organs probably would have  
gone unused because the donor also had been infected with hepatitis 
C. That excluded those organs from use in uninfected patients. 
Also, Slater and the donor both shared type AB blood, the rarest 
type. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
