<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Portland Weather Challenge to Runner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Sprinter Ato Boldon wasn't planning to  
take a shot at a world record this weekend. It's a good thing, 
because rain and chilly temperatures are expected to slow down 
everyone's times at Saturday's Adidas Oregon Track Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon, one of the world's fastest men in both the 100 and 200,  
will instead use the meet to refine his ``drive phase'' -- a 
carefully honed technique used to go from the starting blocks to 
top speed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like a choreographed dance, and I need to make sure I hit  
all the steps,'' Boldon said Friday, resting beneath covers in his 
hotel room, the heat cranked up. ``I don't want a close race, 
especially in this weather. You don't want to have to press. You 
want to put everybody away early.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon is the headliner at the meet, to be held at Lewis &AMP; Clark  
College. It's the first of five outdoor events in the inaugural 
Golden Spike Tour. The series ends with the USA Championships in 
Eugene. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if Boldon has a bad race or holds up considerably, he  
probably will break the meet 100 record of 10.15, held by Terry 
Bowen. Boldon's closest competition likely will come from Brian 
Lewis, whose personal-best is 10.0. 
</P>
<P>
	Other notable entries at the Classic include hurdler Allen  
Johnson, pole vaulter Jeff Hartwig and distance runner Regina 
Jacobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon had a sore right hamstring that forced him to slow up in  
the second half of last week's 100 at the Modesto Relays, which he 
won with a wind-aided time of 9.89. But he said the leg has 
completely healed. 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon's friend and HSI teammate, Maurice Greene, competed at  
Modesto in different heats. Greene, ranked No. 1 in the 100 last 
year, isn't entered in the Oregon Classic, but arrived Friday to 
support Boldon. 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon and Greene, who each have run a 9.86, are again expected  
to challenge the world 100 record of 9.84 set by Donovan Bailey at 
the 1996 Atlanta Olympics. But the friends haven't placed much 
importance on reaching the mark. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maurice and I decided this year that we were not going to talk  
world record,'' Boldon said. ``People immediately thought, `Yeah, 
that's because they said it last year and it didn't happen.' No, 
not at all. We feel that changes our focus, when we go out there 
and try to run to make the clock stop at a world record, as opposed 
to run the race and let the clock worry about itself. I think you 
have to go for the best race, and that becomes the world record 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	``My singular focus this year is the world championships, as  
opposed to any record.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon, who has his own web site (www.atoboldon.com), monitors  
weather sites and answers e-mail with a laptop he takes with him on 
the road, said he received a dispatch from a European fan who 
listed all the sub-9.90 100s since 1997. They all belong to either 
Greene or Boldon. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was totally amazing to me,'' Boldon said. ``It really  
makes me see that Maurice and I have been literally doing things 
that have not been done before. So I think because of that we see 
it as kind of us against them. It's like Maurice and I are back to 
back, with our fists up.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
