<HEADLINE> Texas Prep Breaks Pole Vault Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Orangefield senior Eric Eshbach set a  
scholastic pole vault record of 18 feet, 2 1/4 inches at the Texas 
state high school meet today, shattering the previous mark of 17-9 1/2 
by Joe Dial of Marlow, Okla., in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	Dial's mark was set at a meet sanctioned by the National  
Federation of State High School Athletic Associations. 
</P>
<P>
	Eshbach's vault also surpassed the best American schoolboy mark  
ever recorded. Brandon Richards vaulted 18-2 at Eugene, Ore. in 
1985 but his mark was set the summer before he entered college and 
was not considered for the record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew I had it in me,'' Eshbach said. ``I just didn't know  
when it would come. I knew the day I jumped 18 I'd go higher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eshbach cleared 17-6, 17-10 and 18-0 on his first tries. He then  
missed his first two attempts at 18-2 1/4, before clearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Eshbach pushed the bar to 18-6, but after two misses and citing  
a sore back, he had enough. 
</P>
</TEXT>
