<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Spending Bill Headed for Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional leaders plan to push legislation  
through the House and Senate next week that would double the funds 
President Clinton requested for the battle over Kosovo, assistance 
to U.S. farmers and aid for Central American hurricane victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Capping three days of bargaining, House-Senate negotiators shook  
hands Thursday evening on a package that ultimately swelled to 
nearly $15 billion. Clinton had sought $6 billion for the air 
campaign against Yugoslavia, and just over $1 billion for Central 
America, farmers and assorted other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The final hurdle was overcome after House bargainers, pressed by  
House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., reversed themselves and 
rejected a guaranteed loan program for some steel companies 
proposed by Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va. The steel assistance and a 
similar program for ailing oil and gas companies sponsored by Sen. 
Pete Domenici, R-N.M., will be considered later in a separate 
package, which unlike the Kosovo measure will have no guarantee of 
reaching the president's desk. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been going to conferences with senators for years,'' said  
29-year House veteran Rep. Bill Young, R-Fla., chairman of the 
House Appropriations Committee. ``We always hit one or two 
obstacles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans won a defense increase in the package, which would  
provide $11.8 billion for the air attacks on Yugoslavia, a general 
military buildup and Balkan refugees. That doubling of Clinton's 
request helped the GOP polish its pro-Pentagon credentials and will 
help them live within next year's budget limits. 
</P>
<P>
	They also got language proposed by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison,  
R-Texas, blocking Clinton from grabbing any of the $246 billion 
states have won from a legal settlement with the tobacco industry. 
Clinton wanted to use a portion of those funds for anti-tobacco and 
other health programs. The president argues that some of the money 
belongs to the federal government under the Medicaid 
health-insurance program. 
</P>
<P>
	But three months after Clinton requested the aid for Honduras  
and other Central American countries battered by the deadly 
Hurricane Mitch, he finally got it -- along with four times the 
amount he sought for U.S. farmers hurt by low commodities prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Several GOP provisions the administration opposed as  
anti-environmental were either rejected or watered down. These 
included an effort by Alaska's senators to protect commercial 
fishing in Glacier Bay National Park and a drive by Domenici to 
prevent the silvery minnow from being protected in the Rio Grande 
River. 
</P>
<P>
	All but $1.6 billion of the bill's cost will be paid out of this  
year's projected $111 billion federal surplus. The rest will come 
from cuts in domestic programs, mostly food stamp funds some 
lawmakers said would be unused. The administration defeated earlier 
GOP plans to cut money used to back loans by international banks 
and to purchase nuclear materials from Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd's steel provision was removed from the bill after two House  
Republicans reversed themselves Thursday and House negotiators 
voted 12-11 to reject the program. The two were Reps. Ralph Regula, 
R-Ohio, and Joe Skeen, R-N.M. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had some discussions,'' Regula said of his meeting with  
Hastert. ``That's his role as leader, which is perfectly 
appropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The provision, approved last month by the Senate, would have  
provided $140 million to back $1 billion in loan guarantees for 
moderate-sized steel companies hurt by imports. Among them would be 
the Weirton Steel Corp. of Weirton, W.Va. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I see here is a steamroller,'' Byrd said of the vote that  
knocked the steel provision out of the spending bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Remaining in the bill was a Senate-approved provision providing  
up to $4.3 million to pay reparations for Japanese people interned 
during World War II, including some from Latin America who were 
placed in U.S. detention camps. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders decided against reducing the $900 million in added  
funding the compromise would provide to the Federal Emergency 
Management Agency following the tornadoes that hit Oklahoma and 
other states. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 07:32:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Maker Fights To Extend Patents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It is only a single drug, but a legislative  
battle over whether to extend Claritin's patent involves some of 
Capitol Hill's top lobbyists. At stake is $1.9 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough Corp. has brought in some big names to push  
legislation that could extend the patent on its popular 
anti-allergy drug by three years. The patent is set to expire in 
2002. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side, generic drug makers are waging a lobbying  
battle of their own, eager to break into new, lucrative markets. 
When Schering-Plough's patent expires, generic drug makers will be 
able to sell their own versions of Claritin. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a 1984 law, Claritin and six other lesser-known drugs that  
were being reviewed by the Food and Drug Administration received 
only two-year patent extensions rather than the five years given 
other pharmaceuticals. 
</P>
<P>
	The current legislation in Congress, sponsored by Reps. Ed  
Bryant, R-Tenn., and Jim McDermott, D-Wash., would allow the 
companies that make these seven drugs to ask the U.S. Patent and 
Trademark Office for another three years of patent protection. 
</P>
<P>
	``These medicines were kept off the market and away from the  
American public, in many cases for 10 years or more, because of 
administrative delays that had nothing to do with their safety to 
consumers,'' McDermott said. 
</P>
<P>
	Helping to make the case for the bill is an all-star lineup of  
lobbyists, including former Federal Aviation Deputy Administrator 
Linda Daschle, wife of the Senate's top Democrat, Tom Daschle of 
South Dakota; former Democratic Sen. Dennis DeConcini; former 
Republican Rep. Vin Weber; former White House Chief of Staff Howard 
Baker; and former Watergate prosecutor Richard Ben-Veniste. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they're doing is adding a tax onto people who need the  
drugs to more than pay for the expenses of the lobbyists,'' said an 
opponent of the legislation, Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough also has gotten some unsolicited help from  
former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop, who wrote a letter to the 
lawmakers leading the charge for the bill. An aide to Koop said he 
acted on his own and is not being paid by the drug company. 
</P>
<P>
	``America's pharmaceutical research engine drives major advances  
in the treatment and cure of disease,'' Koop wrote. ``Patent 
protection is a major factor stimulating this research and drug 
development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough spokesman William O'Donnell said the bill would  
not guarantee a patent extension, only an independent examination 
of whether the company should get another three years of 
protection. 
</P>
<P>
	``We support a fair and equitable process,'' O'Donnell said.  
``We are trying to get support for that general principle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough has made similar attempts in the past to pass  
the legislation. Last October, lawmakers tried unsuccessfully to 
attach the provision to the giant session-ending spending bill. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Schering-Plough already had big-name lobbyists  
working for it like DeConcini and Peter Knight, who was campaign 
manager for President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	But as the expiration date nears, Schering-Plough has beefed up  
its lobbying team. Two of its newer members, Daschle and 
Ben-Veniste, recently lobbied Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., who said 
he still was undecided. 
</P>
<P>
	The generic drug makers are running ads directed at lawmakers  
and their staffs. They emphasize consumers would be the big winners 
if they could buy lower-cost generic versions sooner rather than 
later, never mentioning their own financial interest in the 
outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	Buddy Menn, vice president for government affairs at the Generic  
Pharmaceutical Industry Association, delivered that message in a 
large first-floor Capitol meeting room to House Democrats, and over 
the telephone to officials at AARP and Consumers Union. 
</P>
<P>
	``The message is the one solution to the rising costs of  
prescription drugs is good old-fashioned competition,'' Menn said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
