<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duke Research Ban Lifted by NIH </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- The government lifted most restrictions  
Friday on federally funded medical research on humans at Duke 
University, three days after the experiments were suspended because 
of lax safety oversight. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said it was satisfied with the university's plan  
to correct the problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``They presented to us adequate plans to correct the problems we  
had identified,'' said Dr. Michael A. Carome, chief compliance 
officer for Office for Protection From Research Risks, a part of 
the National Institutes of Health. 
</P>
<P>
	``But there is still work to be done. We view this as a new  
beginning for them and expect significant improvements in their 
program to protect human subjects.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the agency had ordered Duke not to enroll new  
subjects in federally funded experiments. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency found that members of the medical center's  
Institutional Review Board -- which gives approval for tests and 
monitors patients in those studies -- had voted on projects in ways 
that created potential conflicts of interest and did not review 
research to assure patient safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke officials said that problems cited were mostly due to poor  
record keeping and that no patients were endangered. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke has about 2,000 research projects under way involving  
thousands of patients. Duke received $228 million in 1998 for 
federal and non-governmental research, with tens of millions for 
human clinical trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Michael A. Carome, chief compliance officer for OPRR, said  
that 250 to 300 government-funded projects remain under suspension 
until Duke shows the projects have been appropriately reviewed by a 
review board. 
</P>
<P>
	Recruitment of subjects and other actions in those projects  
cannot proceed until the new review is completed. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Duke had been banned from recruiting new patients to  
federally funded programs, research was allowed to continue on 
those already enrolled in such experiments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
