<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Senate Backs Gun Show Limits  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The GOP-led Senate today voted 48-47 for new  
restrictions on gun show sales, despite President Clinton's warning 
that the provision was ``riddled with high-caliber loopholes.'' The 
political maneuvering involved legislation to increase prosecution 
of juvenile offenders following the Columbine High School massacre 
near Denver. The Senate turned down a proposal to require Internet 
Web sites to obtain federal licenses if they sell firearms. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Dive: Dow Off 193.87  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average fell 193.87  
points to 10,913.32 today after a steep rise in consumer prices set 
off renewed worries about inflation. It wiped out yesterday's 
106.82-point gain that set a new closing high of 11,107.19. Broader 
stock indicators and bond prices were also loser. On the NYSE, 
losers led gainers 2,411-676. The Nasdaq fell 54.13 to 2,527.87. 
The 0.7 percent rise in the consumer price index for April was the 
largest monthly gain in nearly nine years. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Blocks Air Pollution Rules  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal appeals court today blocked the  
Environmental Protection Agency from imposing tougher air quality 
requirements the agency says are needed to protect people with 
respiratory problems and children. A three-judge panel acted on a 
lawsuit by a number of industry groups. Although the EPA said it 
will ask the Justice Department to appeal, the ruling halted any 
further enforcement of rules imposed in July 1997 that require 
states to dramatically reduce the amount of ozone, or smog, and 
microscopic soot they may allow in the air. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Hit Refugees, Serbs Claim  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO bombs hit a convoy of ethnic  
Albanian refugees and killed dozens early Friday, Yugoslav 
authorities claimed. Reporters were shown a devastated scene of 
charred bodies, wrecked tractors and terrified survivors. The 
state-run Tanjug news agency reported ``ceaseless'' NATO air 
activity over Kosovo Friday night with attacks near several major 
cities. NATO said it was investigating the claim, while the State 
Department said Serb reports of the attack should be viewed with 
skepticism. The Serb-run Media Center in Kosovo reported 79 were 
killed and 61 were injured. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Voices Regret to Jiang  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, whose calls to Chinese  
President Jiang Zemin had been refused since the U.S. bombing of 
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade last week, spoke by telephone to 
the Chinese leader today. Clinton expressed hope that the two 
countries could repair the damage to their relations. On the 52nd 
day of NATO's air campaign, Defense Secretary William Cohen said 
U.S. troop morale remains high. 

</P>
<P>
	Israel Election Remains Uncertain  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and  
opposition leader Ehud Barak waited today as two minor contenders 
dropped hints but did not make a firm pledge to pull out before 
Monday's election. New polls indicate that Barak has widened his 
lead over Netanyahu. 

</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart Won't Sell Next-Day Pill  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Wal-Mart, the nation's largest  
retailer, has decided not to sell the morning-after pill at its 
2,400 pharmacy counters. WalMart, with a large presence in 
small-town America, said it concluded the emergency contraceptive 
might not sell well enough to make it worth the effort. Family 
planning advocates were critical, saying that some women, 
particularly those in small towns where Wal-Mart has little 
competition, would have greater difficulty finding the drug, 
Preven. 

</P>
<P>
	Sears To Pay Child Labor Fine  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. has agreed to pay a $325,000  
penalty to settle allegations it violated child labor laws by 
letting teen-agers operate heavy machinery or work too many hours. 
The U.S. Labor Department said its investigation found 227 children 
were working at Sears in violation of child labor law. 

</P>
<P>
	Cubs Blank Braves  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sammy Sosa homered and Jon Lieber (4-1) gave up  
seven hits on his way to his first shutout as the Chicago Cubs beat 
the Atlanta Braves 9-0 today. Sosa's two-run homer in the third 
inning off Tom Glavine (2-4) was his ninth of the year and gave the 
Cubs a 4-0 lead. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  

</P>
