<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Wins Trial in Missouri </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Cigarette makers have defeated a Missouri  
lawsuit seeking millions of dollars and had the largest judgment 
ever entered in a tobacco trial cut by more than half in Oregon. 
</P>
<P>
	An Oregon judge on Thursday slashed a $79.5 million punitive  
damages verdict against Philip Morris to $32 million, which still 
remains the largest award ever against a tobacco company. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury had awarded the family of Jesse Williams the punitive  
damages plus $821,485 in compensatory damages for medical costs and 
pain and suffering. Williams was a former school janitor who died 
of lung cancer in 1997 at age 67 after smoking Marlboro cigarettes 
for 42 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge did not cut the compensatory amount.  
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. Supreme Court said there are limits,'' Multnomah  
County Circuit Judge Anna Brown said. ``By no means is my personal 
point of view substituted for that of the jury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors said they were infuriated by documents showing that  
Philip Morris executives had lied for decades about the link 
between smoking and cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	William Gaylord, who represented the Williams family, said  
during the hearing over damages that any reduction would be a 
public relations coup for the company. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. juries have awarded damages in smoking liability cases only  
five times -- twice in Florida and once in New Jersey, Oregon and 
California. The Florida and New Jersey verdicts were overturned on 
appeal, while the $51.5 million award in California was halved by a 
judge. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kansas City, Mo., on Thursday, a federal jury handed Brown &AMP;  
Williamson Tobacco Corp. its second victory in four days, deciding 
the company was not at fault in the case of a smoker who died of 
lung cancer in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Steele's family had sued for $26 million, claiming the  
company sold him an unreasonably dangerous product. 
</P>
<P>
	But jury foreman Gary White said Steele ``was quite aware of the  
dangers, but the pleasures outweighed the dangers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, a jury in Memphis, Tenn., cleared B&AMP;W and two other  
tobacco companies of liability in the deaths of three smokers. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analyst Gary Black of Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co. said  
the recent trial victories showed investors the industry can manage 
legal challenges. 
</P>
<P>
	``The industry needed to win this case and the case in Memphis  
to show plaintiffs' attorneys that these cases are not easy to 
win,'' Black said. ``They needed to show they were in control.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 06:13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Revision of Hate Crime Law Stalls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Efforts to strengthen Texas' hate crimes  
law failed again in the state Senate -- a failure the bill's sponsor 
attributed to presidential politics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since our governor is a leading presidential hopeful, the eyes  
of the world are on Texas,'' said state Sen. Rodney Ellis, a 
Houston Democrat. ``Everything we do now takes on national 
implications.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. George W. Bush, repeating the same comment he's given for  
several weeks, said again Thursday that he ``will look at the bill 
when it makes it to my desk, if it makes it to my desk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal to include gays in the legislation has been a major  
hurdle. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed legislation has received the backing of President  
Clinton and Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley. A 
broadening of hate crimes laws also is being considered on the 
federal level. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of the state legislation -- named after James Byrd  
Jr., the black man dragged to his death in East Texas last summer -- 
said they have yet to give up, but they deemed the bills ``on life 
support.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After trying for days to reach a compromise with Republicans on  
the bill to strengthen the state hate crimes law, Democrats tried 
an unusual parliamentary tactic to send it from the Criminal 
Justice Committee to the full Senate for debate. 
</P>
<P>
	That move failed Thursday, and the bill was left pending.  
</P>
<P>
	West tried next to pass a different hate crimes bill out of the  
State Affairs Committee. But the Republican chairwoman, state Sen. 
Florence Shapiro, never called for a vote on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had an agreement that I would hear it if he had the  
votes,'' she said. ``And he did not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Republican-dominated committees meet again today and the  
bills could be considered. Midnight is the deadline for Senate 
committees to consider legislation, and the Legislative session as 
a whole ends May 31. 
</P>
<P>
	The state's current hate crimes law -- which punishes crimes  
committed with bias or prejudice as a motive -- has been criticized 
by bill supporters as too vague to enforce. 
</P>
<P>
	As passed by the House last month, a hate crime would be defined  
as one motivated by the victim's race, ethnicity, gender, 
disability, religion or sexual preference. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellis said that the major ``sticking point'' to the hate crimes  
bill was the categories of protected groups -- in particular the 
measure that would cover homosexuals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
