<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Aims To Punish EU in Beef Spat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States said Friday it will ask for  
stiff tariffs on $202 million worth of European products in 
retaliation for the European Union's decision to ignore a deadline 
on opening its markets to hormone-treated American beef. 
</P>
<P>
	The request to the World Trade Organization to impose 100  
percent tariffs on the products came one day after the European 
Union missed a WTO deadline to end its 10-year ban on U.S. beef. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU said it would not comply with the deadline because  
preliminary results from at least one new study suggested some of 
the meat could cause cancer, although the bulk of its research will 
not be completed until next year. The United States rejects this 
contention. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, the EU's unwillingness to meet its  
international obligations leaves the U.S. with no choice,'' 
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We take this course as a last resort,'' added U.S. Trade  
Representative Charlene Barshefsky. ``The EU should meet its WTO 
obligations. ... To do anything less is to jeopardize the 
credibility and integrity of the WTO.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $202 million is the estimated amount of beef that would be  
exported annually without the ban, officials said. More than 90 
percent of American cattle producers feed hormones approved by the 
Food and Drug Administration to make cattle grow faster and bigger. 
</P>
<P>
	Hugo Paemen, the EU's chief envoy to the U.S., said the EU's  
decision was based solely on scientific study. ``This does not mean 
that there is unwillingness on the part of the European Union to 
comply with its obligations in relation to the World Trade 
Organization,'' Paemen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU would be willing to strike a compensation deal with the  
United States, which would, for instance, lower tariffs on other 
American goods coming into Europe, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe the compensation package is far preferable to  
retaliation which is trade restrictive and hurts U.S. importers and 
EU companies that have nothing to do with the beef sector,'' Paemen 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States and the 15-nation European Union are already  
embroiled in a dispute over trade barriers imposed on bananas 
produced by American companies. U.S. officials have targeted $191.4 
million in European products for 100-percent tariffs in that 
dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Glickman and Barshefsky said the U.S. would be willing to  
discuss compensation in the beef dispute as an interim step. 
</P>
<P>
	But, ``compensation is only acceptable if the EU agrees to lift  
the ban,'' Barshefsky said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under WTO settlement procedures, the U.S. request for tariffs  
must be granted by June 12 unless the EU claims the amount exceeds 
the harm caused to U.S. exports. If the EU makes that claim, the 
matter will go to arbitration. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, if the U.S. request is approved, the products will be  
chosen from a preliminary list of $900 million worth of European 
products. The United States did not release the final list of $202 
million in products on Friday, leaving scores of American importers 
wondering what will be affected. 
</P>
<P>
	The preliminary list, while covering predominantly agriculture  
products, contains a limited number of manufactured goods, 
including Italian moped motorcycles and hair clippers. The 
agriculture goods included canned hams from Denmark and other types 
of pork, beef and poultry, a variety of tomato products, Roquefort 
cheese, truffles, onions, chestnuts, paprika, goose liver, chewing 
gum, chocolate and mineral water. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of importers of European delicacies, such as foie gras  
and truffles, argued at a hearing last month that they were being 
caught unfairly in a trade war between the world's two largest 
trading partners. They urged U.S. officials to exempt the products 
they care about. 
</P>
<P>
	The higher tariffs would effectively double the prices and are  
designed to eliminate the goods from the U.S. market in 
retaliation. 
</P>
<P>
	``While retaliation is a necessary step to force EU compliance,  
the only real solution to this issue is access to the EU market for 
U.S. cattle producers,'' said George Swan, president of the 
National Cattlemen's Beef Association. ``Access is all that is 
required.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
