<HEADLINE> Wheat Pulls Corn, Soybeans Down / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures fell sharply Friday on the Chicago  
Board of Trade, dragging corn and soybeans lower as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat erased initial gains amid renewed pessimism about whether  
world demand will be strong enough to cut into ample supplies. Good 
weather in winter wheat regions this weekend may prove beneficial 
to the crop, boosting yields. Rains also were expected over the 
weekend in Chinese growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures this week found a measure of support from  
government projections that the crop will be far smaller than last 
year's. But prices also were pressured Friday by talk the active 
July contract could fall to $2.10 a bushel before it expires. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn fell in sympathy with wheat despite a lower acreage  
projection from influential forecasting firm Sparks Co. of Memphis, 
Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans were slightly lower amid fears acreage will continue to  
grow, boosting what is already expected to be a bumper crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 10 cents to $2.60 1/2 a bushel; July  
corn fell 2 1/4 cents to $2.21 3/4 a bushel; July oats fell 4 1/4 cents to 
$1.21 a bushel; July soybeans fell 1/2 cent to $4.69 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures rose sharply on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange  
amid continued optimism that the Memorial Day start of the summer 
grilling season will boost demand sharply. Pork futures moved 
sharply lower on profit-taking from recent highs this week. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .50 cent to 61.90 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .92 cent to 73.67 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell 1.18 cents to 58.87 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell 2.82 
cents to 56.20 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
