<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gettysburg Museum Change Advised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GETTYSBURG, Pa. (AP) -- An advisory panel recommended Friday that  
the National Park Service proceed with plans to tear down the 
Cyclorama building at Gettysburg National Military Park as part of 
a proposal to build a new visitor center and museum. 
</P>
<P>
	The 37-year-old building, which houses a circular painting of  
the Civil War battle, was determined last year to be eligible for 
listing on the National Register of Historic Places. The move 
caused a potential conflict with plans for the new center and 
museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the Gettysburg park, led by Superintendent John A.  
Latschar, have said their primary goal was to protect the site of 
the 1863 battle, on which the building was constructed. Removing 
the building would help restore the conditions of a significant 
part of the battlefield, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Latschar said Friday that the recommendation by the Advisory  
Council on Historic Preservation resolves the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is, basically, the advisory council's concurrence in our  
proposal to remove the building and rehabilitate the historic 
landscape,'' Latschar said. ``The advisory council is our supreme 
court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Architects who wanted the Cyclorama included on the National  
Register weren't happy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I find it very hard to understand that you would selectively  
take one piece of this whole tapestry and remove it and say that 
would make sense in preserving the landscape,'' said architect Dion 
Neutra, who worked on the building. ``It doesn't wash.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
