<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Owner of Sunken Tour Boat Testifies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- The owner of a tour boat that sank in  
Lake Hamilton, killing 13 people, testified today he was assured by 
a mechanic that the craft was sound hours before it took to the 
water. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Bridges, owner of Land and Lake Tours Inc., testified he was  
called at home the morning of May 1 by Bill Woodall, a company 
mechanic who had worked on the Miss Majestic. Its operator, 
Elizabeth Helmbrecht, had brought the boat in for repairs on April 
29. 
</P>
<P>
	Woodall ``called me Saturday morning, and said he turned it over  
to the driver,'' Bridges told the Coast Guard Marine Safety Board 
of Investigation. ``I said, `Did you get everything fixed?' and he 
said `Yes.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Bridges testified today that mechanics at the family-owned  
company often don't explain to him the nature of repairs. 
</P>
<P>
	``They just call and say this boat is ready to go,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The boat was pulled from the water Sunday. Investigators found a  
rip in an accordian-like seal at one end of the drive shaft cover. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Oliver, another company mechanic, testified on Thursday  
that he safely tightened a drive shaft seal he replaced on the Miss 
Majestic less than two hours before the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I wouldn't have driven it myself, I wouldn't have put  
anyone else on it,'' Oliver said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under questioning, Oliver said that while the seal was tight, it  
might have been misaligned. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's possible it was not square,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Helmbrecht gave the vessel a visual inspection before  
selecting the Miss Majestic to take 20 tourists on a $9 tour of Hot 
Springs and Lake Hamilton, Oliver said. Ms. Helmbrecht was among 
eight people who survived. 
</P>
<P>
	In testimony Thursday, Coast Guard Chief Warrant Officer Robert  
Thompson said he found several problems with the boat's pumps. 
</P>
<P>
	In testing after the Miss Majestic was pulled from the lake  
Sunday, one shut off after 22 seconds, one pumped two gallons a 
minute when it should have pumped 12.5 and another pumped at 12 
gallons a minute when it should have worked at 18.3 gallons a 
minute, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The low rate of pumping power could have contributed to the  
sinking, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
