<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mark Martin Wins Hardee's 250 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Mark Martin outran Roush Racing teammate  
Jeff Burton over the last fifth of the rain-delayed Hardee's 250 
Busch Grand National race Friday night and Matt Kenseth took over 
the series points lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin took the lead from Burton on the 197th lap at Richmond  
International Raceway and pulled away from the defending champion 
to post his track-high fifth Busch victory on the 
three-quarter-mile oval. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin, who also won Busch races at Las Vegas and Texas this  
season, gained his series-record 37th career victory and third in 
this race. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenseth, who started the race 19 points behind leader Dale  
Earnhardt Jr. in the driver standings and 10 ahead of No. 3 Elton 
Sawyer, took advantage of a wreck that put both drivers off the 
track by finishing third. The solid effort moved him into the 
points lead by 84 over Earnhardt, who wound up 32nd, and by 119 
over Sawyer, who limped home in 34th place. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great to race against Mark and Jeff Burton,'' Kenseth  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Todd Bodine finished fourth and Jeff Green was fifth.  
</P>
<P>
	The race, delayed 2 hours, 43 minutes at the start by rain, was  
sloppy throughout. The first caution came on the second lap when 
Lyndon Amick spun out exiting the second turn, and there were two 
yellow flags in the first 10 laps and three cars behind the wall 
after the first 32 laps. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time it was over, there had been 11 caution flags that  
slowed the race for 58 laps, and nine cars had called it a long 
night early. 
</P>
<P>
	But the last 79 laps were all run under green, and that helped  
Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't beat those guys on new tires,'' Martin said. ``I  
just thought if we could ever get into green flag racing we'd be 
all right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike many of the less-experienced competitors, Martin and  
Burton seemed to have no trouble with the damp conditions, and the 
Winston Cup stars rewarded fans who waited as many as 12 hours with 
their late-race battle. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got beat by the best tonight,'' Burton said.  
</P>
<P>
	Martin, though, was clearly stronger under green, and he wound  
up winning by 1.111 seconds despite battling lapped traffic at the 
end. His average speed was 90.072 mph in a race that took 2 hours, 
4 minutes, 54 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Harry Gant had shared the track lead with four career Busch  
victories. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Grissom, who collected Earnhardt Jr. and Elliott Sadler  
when he crashed into the turn 3 wall, was transported to Memorial 
General Medical Center. There was no immediate word on his 
condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
