<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Forecaster Out of Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT COLLINS, Colo. (AP) -- William Gray, the researcher whose  
hurricane forecasts are relied on from the Caribbean to the Gulf 
Coast, may be out of the prediction business. 
</P>
<P>
	``My project is nearly broke. I'm having to terminate staff or  
find other funding for their salaries,'' Gray said Friday. ``I 
don't have my salary for this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Wagner, emergency manager for the Florida Keys, said  
Gray's departure ``would be a great loss. He's the only one giving 
us guidance on what the activity is going to be in the Atlantic 
Basin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gray, 69, used to get funding from the National Oceanic and  
Atmospheric Administration, the National Science Foundation and the 
insurance industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Insurers stopped paying when his federally funded research  
became available for free on the Internet. NOAA has rejected his 
requests for funding for the past six years. The Federal Emergency 
Management Agency also rejected funding. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he is paid to teach by Colorado State University, the  
only support for his hurricane research now comes from the NSF, 
$145,000. He said that amounts to about $50,000 after expenses and 
other research. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he needs about $400,000 a year to keep his forecasts  
coming. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray said he believes his research has been rejected because he  
has publicly questioned the validity of sophisticated computer 
programs -- called numeric models -- that are becoming the dominant 
method of forecasting. The programs use mathematical formulas to 
forecast the weather, based on existing conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray uses computer programs, too. One wall in his office is  
awash with calculations that would make a calculus teacher drool. 
He calls it ``our hurricane pool.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His calculations include a study of past events, but also  
conditions elsewhere, including West Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Tomastik of NOAA said the decision to reject Gray's  
proposals were made by a peer review committee of fellow 
scientists, not the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray's forecasts have been close to the mark during the 16 years  
he made predictions, with 1997 the major exception. He predicted 
seven hurricanes with three of them major; only three occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	For the 1999 season, Gray has predicted 14 named storms and nine  
hurricanes, four of them major. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 19:21:14 </DATE_TIME>
