<DOCNO> APW19990514.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 14:23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spurs' Robinson Vows Playoff Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- David Robinson says the Minnesota  
Timberwolves' season should be over Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They could come out and make it really tough. They could make  
shots, they could do a lot of things,'' the San Antonio Spurs' 
center said Friday. ``But if we play the way we're capable of 
playing, we should be able to finish the job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Especially if Avery Johnson lights up the Wolves again.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson is averaging 20.3 points in the playoff series, more  
than double his regular-season production. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs, behind Johnson's 24 points on 12-of-15 shooting, took  
a 2-1 lead in the best-of-5 series with an 85-71 thumping of the 
tired Timberwolves at the Target Center on Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson bounced back from a lackadaisical first two games with  
17 points, 18 rebounds and seven assists as the top seed in the 
Western Conference regained the homecourt advantage after a Game 2 
letdown at the Alamodome. 
</P>
<P>
	But Johnson said Robinson better not count his blessings just  
yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still need more,'' Johnson said. ``I don't want you talking  
to David because he got 18 rebounds and 17 points like he played a 
great game. There's still opportunity for him to do more, and 
that's what we're going to talk about in this film session. He has 
not arrived yet in this series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What more could Robinson possibly do?  
</P>
<P>
	``He can be even more aggressive. We've got to help him get in  
position where he can be aggressive,'' Johnson said. ``If we 
continue to make shots from the perimeter, then hopefully he'll get 
more 1-on-1 coverages inside and he can do more damage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's not going to happen, said Wolves coach Flip Saunders,  
who's going to continue double-teaming Robinson and Tim Duncan in 
the low post and daring Johnson to win it with jump shots. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the same strategy Saunders has employed the entire  
series, only on Thursday night, the Wolves were so slow to rotate 
``it was like our feet were in mud.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Contrary to what you might think, there's no time that I walk  
in that locker room and say, `OK guys, we're going to give Avery 
Johnson open 15-foot shots,' '' Saunders said. ``I got a son that's 
in seventh grade and I know that if I give him open 15-foot shots, 
he's going to go out and make seven out of 10.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The problem, Saunders said, was that the Wolves were slow to  
rotate Thursday night, leaving Johnson with what amounted to free 
throws worth two points apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our idea was to get the ball out of Timmy's and David's hands.  
When Avery gets it, get there and contest his shots,'' Saunders 
said. ``We're not going to change what we're doing. What we're 
hoping to do is change our effectiveness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wolves forward Sam Mitchell said Johnson was so wide open,  
``that was like playing H-O-R-S-E. He won't get those looks 
tomorrow, I'll tell you that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Garnett said the Wolves are going to have to deny Johnson  
just as hard as they do Duncan and Robinson. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to readjust, control him, but at the same time do what  
we've been doing,'' Garnett said. ``You can't let one man beat you 
like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garnett said the Wolves, who made just 28 of 80 shots Thursday  
night, have what it takes to force a Game 5 by beating the Spurs 
for a third time this year at the Target Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, we do because we're one of the teams that just don't  
stop,'' he said. ``When you think we're out of it, boom, we're 
right back there, right in your face. We don't give up. We don't 
know what it is to give up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I definitely know one thing, we're a team that's going to  
fight and we're going to fight you to the end, whether that's 
biting, scratching, poke in the eyes,'' Garnett said. ``We're going 
to do what we have to do to win.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
