<HEADLINE> AP Corrects Doctors' Income Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- In a May 13 story on doctors' incomes, The  
Associated Press erroneously reported that an American Medical 
Association study said managed care contributed to a decline in 
doctors' incomes in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The AMA study said the decline was due to changes in the  
economics of health care, but did not cite managed care. Outside 
experts interviewed by the AP said managed care was a factor. 
</P>
<P>
	The story also erroneously quoted the study as saying doctors  
worked an average of 48 hours a week in 1998. The correct figure is 
55 hours a week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
