<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Titans, Matthews in Four-Year Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Veteran offensive guard Bruce Matthews  
is convinced the Tennessee Titans are close to greatness and he 
wants to be around when they achieve it. 
</P>
<P>
	The 37-year-old Matthews agreed to a four-year contract, the  
Titans announced Thursday. Terms were not disclosed by the team, 
but The Tennessean reported it includes a $4 million signing bonus 
with base salaries of $500,000 this year, $2 million next year and 
$4.075 million in 2001 and 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The salaries for this year and next year are guaranteed,  
according to the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews, an 11-time Pro Bowl selection, has spent his entire  
16-season career with the franchise, playing in a club-record 248 
games and never missing a game due to injury. He became an 
unrestricted free agent at the end of last season but indicated a 
desire to stay with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite three straight 8-8 seasons, Matthews thinks the Titans  
are championship caliber. At a news conference Thursday, he noted 
Atlanta went to the Super Bowl last year, one season after his 
brother Clay retired. 
</P>
<P>
	He doesn't want that to happen to him.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm gonna hang around long enough that this thing will have to  
go to the Super Bowl,'' Matthews said. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews, who doesn't have an agent, negotiated directly with  
the Titans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bruce has been in the league long enough to understand what  
the numbers are, and where he fits,'' said Floyd Reese, general 
manager of the Titans. 
</P>
<P>
	Reese said management ``badly'' wanted Matthews to finish his  
career a Titan. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this world of unrestricted free agency, it may never happen  
again,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews' 248 games ranks him 11th on the NFL's career games  
list. He can pass Jackie Slater this season for the most games 
played by an offensive lineman (259). He has started 244 games 
playing all five offensive line positions. 
</P>
<P>
	Durability is in the Matthews family genes. Clay played 19  
seasons and 278 games with the Cleveland Browns and Atlanta. His 
father, Clay Sr., played four seasons with the San Francisco 49ers 
in the 1950s. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-5, 305-pound Matthews played left guard last season  
but will move to center because of the loss of Mark Stepnoski, who 
signed with Dallas in the off-season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really excited about it,'' Matthews said. ``You eliminate  
a lot of the collisions 'cause you're not pulling and doing some of 
the things you have to do at guard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews said despite all the years and games he hasn't lost his  
youthful enthusiasm for the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that's changed is just sometimes getting up the next  
morning is a lot slower,'' he said. ``And my kids are almost as big 
as me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
