<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Air Faces Antitrust Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Last year the airline industry chided the  
government for complaining about anti-competitive behavior but 
never taking its case to court. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the Justice Department sued American Airlines for  
allegedly trying to quash competition at its Dallas-Forth Worth 
hub, the first predatory pricing case since the government 
deregulated the industry in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	That left a question: Was it a one-shot deal or a sign of things  
to come? 
</P>
<P>
	The department's antitrust chief, Assistant Attorney General  
Joel I. Klein, said at a news conference that his staff is 
investigating other airlines, but a high-level Transportation 
Department source said the most developed case was against 
American. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see any other complaint imminent,'' said the source,  
speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside analysts were uncertain.  
</P>
<P>
	``I would assume there will be a lot of shoes dropping,'' said  
Darryl Jenkins, director of the aviation institute at George 
Washington University. 
</P>
<P>
	A private antitrust lawyer, Marc Schecter, noted the  
government's lawsuit emphasized that American dominates the 
Dallas-Fort Worth hub, with a 70 percent share of passenger 
traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	Schecter predicted that Justice Department attorneys would be  
looking at hubs where one airline is overwhelmingly dominant to see 
how such airlines responded to any competition. 
</P>
<P>
	In a lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court in Wichita, Kan., the  
department charged that American repeatedly tried to drive small, 
start-up airlines out of the DFW airport by saturating their routes 
with additional flights and cutting fares. After the competitors 
withdrew or drastically reduced their service, American 
re-established high fares and reduced its service, the government 
alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno said American increased its prices  
between Dallas-Fort Worth and Wichita by 50 percent after it forced 
Vanguard Airlines, a lower-cost competitor, out of that route. 
American was accused of using similar tactics with Sun Jet on 
flights to Long Beach, Calif., and with Western Pacific on flights 
to Colorado Springs, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	``American adopted a predatory responsive policy. ... American  
knew this strategy would be costly and pursued it only in order to 
drive out the new carriers, so it could return to its monopoly 
pricing,'' Klein said. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline responded with a statement saying the allegations  
were unwarranted. 
</P>
<P>
	It added: ``American Airlines will resolutely challenge the  
government's case. The company is confident that the court will see 
the government's action as an ill-considered attempt to fashion new 
law -- to pick winners and losers in the marketplace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Deregulation advocates say it has brought lower fares and more  
service to airline passengers. The chief criticism comes from 
smaller communities that are served by only one major carrier and 
are forced to pay the going rate in and out of its hub. 
</P>
<P>
	In April 1998, the Transportation Department said it planned to  
crack down on airlines that engage in practices aimed solely at 
driving start-up carriers out of business. The guidelines included 
three triggers: when a major carrier added more flights, sold more 
seats or offered discount fares to more customers than a start-up 
carrier could possibly serve. 
</P>
<P>
	The airlines, through their trade group, the Air Transport  
Association, complained that the proposed rules were vague. They 
also said the Justice Department had existing authority to punish 
airlines for anti-competitive practices, but had not done so even 
once since deregulation. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenkins, of George Washington University, complained that ``the  
government's trying to have a class of protected businesses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``If the Justice Department prevails on this, it will  
have the most chilling and devastating effect on American business, 
because you will no longer be able to match a competitor's price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Terry Trippler, an airfare analyst, said consumers are partly to  
blame, because they often clamor for a discount carrier but then 
patronize a major airline when it offers matching service in 
response to a start-up. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know why the consumers don't support the start-up for  
long?'' Trippler asked. ``They want their frequent flier miles. So, 
can we really blame all of this on American? I don't think so.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
