<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornado Leaves Okla. Town in Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STROUD, Okla. (AP) -- Turnpike billboards promise shopping just  
ahead. But when cars cruise within sight of the Tanger Factory 
Outlet Center, roadside signs flash a warning: Keep moving. 
</P>
<P>
	No shoppers can stop at this mall. No clerk can work in its  
tangled mess of metal. No cash registers ring to ease the debts 
looming over City Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	Tornadoes spared lives here May 3 but left this isolated city of  
about 3,000 ``in a world of hurt'' when it wiped out all 53 mall 
stores and 18 other businesses, City Manager Earl Burson said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're going to be affected by is in the long term, not  
the short term,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The warning signs urge any gawkers who might slow down on the  
lonely stretch of Interstate 44, halfway between Tulsa and Oklahoma 
City, to move on rather than stare at the mall. The storm tore off 
the mall's signature red roof and stripped walls to their studs. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for Greensboro, N.C.-based Tanger Factory Outlet  
Centers said the company intends to rebuild the shopping center but 
is still assessing the situation. ``I'm not really sure if we can 
say anything more from that,'' spokeswoman Carrie Warren said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Burson said the city also has no guarantee that another major  
employer, SYGMA Network, will rebuild its damaged food-distribution 
truck terminal. 
</P>
<P>
	SYGMA has shifted most of its 165 workers to locations in other  
states, Burson said. Many of the mall's 325 employees are searching 
for jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our concern is if these people find jobs in Tulsa, can we keep  
them in Stroud?'' Burson said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the city 65 miles northeast of Oklahoma City also has  
immediate worries. The mall supplied two-thirds of Stroud's income, 
bringing in about $150,000 a month in sales taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Stroud has taken on loans to start an industrial park and build  
a new water treatment plant. With other debts, its monthly loan 
payments are more than $70,000, Burson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're turning to our state. We're turning to the federal  
government,'' he said. ``We've asked, `Please help.' But we don't 
know what they're going to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Chris Hodge's office supply store, the pinch is already  
evident from the loss of SYGMA and other business customers. 
</P>
<P>
	She sees ripple effects. Her daughter, a mall employee, can't  
afford to pay her babysitter without work. 
</P>
<P>
	``The babysitter can't come into the store,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The storm also closed Stroud's hospital, destroyed houses and  
wiped away mobile homes. Ms. Hodge said she is fortunate, 
especially considering the massive and deadly destruction from 
tornadoes in and near Oklahoma City. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the economic uncertainty unnerves her.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's really scary right now,'' she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 01:31:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jazz Backcourt Not the Same  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Utah Jazz coach Jerry Sloan says the  
flagrant foul that knocked down John Stockton in the opening 
seconds of Game 2 of their playoff series against Sacramento still 
is affecting the veteran point guard. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after Stockton went 1-for-9 from the field and scored just  
five points in Utah's 84-81 overtime loss to Sacramento in Game 3, 
Sloan said Stockton has not fully recovered from the foul. 
</P>
<P>
	Stockton said Thursday he's feeling fine and has no lingering  
effects from the foul by Chris Webber, who lowered his shoulder and 
dropped Stockton to the court. But Sloan has his doubts. 
</P>
<P>
	``John Stockton's not the same person after he got hit.  
Physically,'' the coach said Thursday as the Jazz began practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah's venerable backcourt of Stockton and Jeff Hornacek, which  
has led the Jazz to two straight NBA Finals, is looking just plain 
old against Sacramento's young tandem of Jason Williams and Tariq 
Abdul-Wahad. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams and Abdul-Wahad, appearing in their first playoff  
series, outplayed and outscored their counterparts as the Kings 
defeated the Jazz on Wednesday night to take a 2-1 lead in the 
best-of-5 series. 
</P>
<P>
	``They did a great job defensively on our backcourt,'' Sloan  
said. ``They are bigger, stronger and, obviously, younger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings, who won a home playoff game for the first time since  
moving to Sacramento in 1985, can wrap up the first-round series 
with a victory at home tonight. After losing by 30 points in Game 
1, the Kings have won two straight. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams had 12 points, six assists and matched his career high  
with eight rebounds Wednesday night, while Abdul-Wahad had six 
points and helped hold Hornacek to four points on 1-of-6 shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``At some point, when we started losing games, we knew it (age)  
was going to become an issue,'' Hornacek said. ``Right now, they're 
freewheeling it. We had the opportunity in Game 2 to knock their 
confidence down, and we didn't do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stockton has 2,082 points in 150 playoff games and Hornacek has  
1,871 points in 122. Williams and Abdul-Wahad each has played in 
three playoff games. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't deny facts. We are older than them,'' Stockton said.  
``But is it a factor in the game? I don't think so. I certainly 
don't feel that. I think we just couldn't get a shot to fall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings, not surprisingly, tried to avoid playing the age card  
Thursday and instead focused on the ability of veterans such as 
Stockton, Hornacek and Karl Malone to find ways to rebound from 
playoff deficits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would never count out Stockton, Malone and Hornacek. They  
scare me to death,'' Sacramento coach Rick Adelman said, adding he 
doesn't believe Stockton has been affected by Webber's flagrant 
foul. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't believe it bothered him. He's too tough,'' the Kings  
coach said. ``Whenever he gets knocked down, he gets up. I think 
he's going to get up (Friday) night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams also sees no sign of Webber's hit changing Stockton.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's still the same Stockton to me, he's still a great  
player,'' the Kings' rookie point guard said. ``Maybe he's 
different toward Web, but he's the same toward me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
