<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine Student To Leave Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- A student who suffered a massive shotgun wound to  
his jaw in the Columbine High School shootings said Friday that he 
was headed outside to smoke a cigarette with friends when the two 
gunmen opened fire. 
</P>
<P>
	At first, Lance Kirklin thought it was a senior prank.  
</P>
<P>
	He said he saw two ``shadows'' firing before he slipped out of  
consciousness. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was right outside in the commons area. I think that we were  
the first ones shot,'' Kirklin said. ``The two kids who were the 
shooters, I didn't know them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kirklin, 16, who almost died in the attack, met reporters at  
Denver Health Medical Center for the first time since the April 20 
shootings, which left 15 dead and 23 wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirklin doesn't remember details of the shootings.  
</P>
<P>
	He suffered multiple injuries: A pointblank gunshot blast  
shattered his jaw. A bullet severed an artery in his leg. He also 
was hit by three other bullets. 
</P>
<P>
	He has had several operations, including a skin and bone graft  
from his leg to temporarily fill the hole in his jaw. Dozens of 
doctors and physical therapists have worked on him. His hospital 
bill is already close to $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors said Kirklin likely will be released from the hospital  
``within the week,'' but his recovery is not over. 
</P>
<P>
	Throat doctor Stephen Batuello said Kirklin probably will need  
at least six more operations on his face to help permanently close 
the ``crater'' left by the shotgun blast. 
</P>
<P>
	Batuello said Kirklin suffered extensive damage in his jaw and a  
tiny hole left by the tissue replacement has not yet sealed. 
Consequently, Kirklin has to be fed by a tube. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirklin said he can't wait for the hole to close because he  
wants to drink apple juice. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a hole in my face so it just drips out,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Kirklin was with friends Daniel Rohrbough and Sean Graves when  
the shooting began. Rohrbough, 15, was killed. Graves, also 15, was 
shot in the back and has been undergoing physical therapy for a 
spinal cord injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirklin said he wants to let the Columbine community know that  
he feels good. 
</P>
<P>
	He had a special message for his Graves: ``I know it's hard, but  
you just got to push yourself and work hard to get back to 
normal.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
