<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DNA To Verify Fate of Extinct Fish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Advances in genetic technology will allow  
scientists to determine whether a fish already declared extinct is 
still alive after all, a government scientist said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue pike, once Lake Erie's most popular catch, was declared  
extinct in 1983, having been virtually wiped out by the late 1950s 
because of over-fishing. But a close relative, the walleye, is 
still around. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently, a blue-colored fish closely resembling the blue pike  
started appearing in smaller lakes in Canada. The U.S. government 
will use genetic testing to determine whether those specimens are 
truly the blue pike, or whether they are a grayish form of the 
walleye, or perhaps a hybrid. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an intriguing question,'' said Mary Burnham-Curtis, a  
fishery biologist at the U.S. Geological Survey's Great Lakes 
Science Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists have long suspected a link between the blue pike and  
the walleye and in fact generally classify the two as subsets of 
the same species. The main difference appears to be in color, which 
could result either from genetics or environmental factors. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Burnham-Curtis said genetic techniques developed within the  
past decade would help determine the cause and extent of the 
differences and help scientists identify the newly collected 
specimens. 
</P>
<P>
	Preliminary DNA tests will be completed within four months, with  
additional analysis conducted for at least eight months more, Ms. 
Burnham-Curtis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Genetic samples from blue pike museum samples will be compared  
with current and museum samples from the new fish, the walleye and 
a third relative, the sauger. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue pike test results will go to the U.S. Fish and Wildlife  
Service, which would have to determine whether to reverse its 
extinction declaration, something that has never been done. If that 
happens, wildlife officials would have to decide whether to 
reintroduce the species to the original Great Lakes habitats. 
</P>
<P>
	A reintroduction of the species could be worth hundreds of  
millions of dollars a year for the sport-fishing industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
