<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Names Two to New Positions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mike Silverman, deputy managing editor of The  
Associated Press, and Thomas Kent, international editor, have been 
appointed to new senior newsroom positions for the news 
cooperative. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverman will head AP's national news group as deputy managing  
editor for national news. He will direct coverage of U.S. news for 
all AP domestic and world wires. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent, international editor since 1990 and a former bureau chief  
in Moscow, becomes deputy managing editor for projects and 
administration. In the new position, Kent will coordinate coverage 
among AP's many news groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointments were announced Thursday by AP Executive Editor  
William Ahearn, to take effect June 1. Silverman and Kent will 
report to AP Managing Editor Jonathan Wolman. 
</P>
<P>
	Alice Klement was named national enterprise editor, reporting to  
Silverman and directing a group of feature writers, beat reporters 
and investigative reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverman, 55, was named deputy managing editor in 1992. He  
joined the AP in San Francisco in 1971 and moved to the national 
editing desk in New York in 1976. He was a national editor and then 
senior national editor before becoming assistant managing editor 
for national news in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	He is a native of Chicago and holds degrees from the University  
of Chicago and Stanford University. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to his appointment as international editor, Kent was news  
editor of AP's World Service Division in New York; Moscow bureau 
chief; NATO and European Community correspondent in Brussels, 
Belgium; and head of AP operations in Iran during the Iranian 
revolution. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent, 48, is from Cleveland. He graduated from Yale University  
and started with the AP in Hartford, Conn., in 1972. He is a former 
Pulitzer Prize juror and board member of the Overseas Press Club. 
</P>
<P>
	Klement, 48, joined the AP two years ago as assistant enterprise  
editor. Before coming to the AP, Klement served as a Fulbright 
Senior Scholar in Indonesia and the McMahon Centennial Professor at 
the University of Oklahoma School of Journalism and Mass 
Communication and worked as a writing and editing coach in more 
than two dozen newsrooms. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Chicago, she graduated from Northwestern  
University's Medill School of Journalism and the DePaul University 
College of Law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
