<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 00:41:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N. Korea Returning GIs' Remains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- North Korea says it will return remains  
thought to be those of six American soldiers killed nearly 50 years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The remains were to be carried across the demilitarized zone  
between North Korea and South Korea today. 
</P>
<P>
	They were discovered within the last month by a joint U.S.-North  
Korean team searching along the Chong Chon River, 100 miles north 
of Pyongyang, a Pentagon statement said. The area was the site of 
battles in November 1950 between the U.S. Eighth Army and Chinese 
communist forces. 
</P>
<P>
	The recovery was the first joint search effort this year and the  
10th since such collaborations began in 1996. In all, the joint 
searches have yielded 35 sets of remains believed to be U.S. 
soldiers. Three have been identified. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 8,200 Americans are missing in action from the Korean  
War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
