<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Maker Wants Lawsuits Dropped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A generic drug maker accused of conspiring to  
raise prices for two popular tranquilizers believes the government 
overstepped its authority in bringing the case to court. 
</P>
<P>
	Mylan Laboratories Inc. asked a federal judge Thursday to  
dismiss the federal antitrust lawsuits filed by the Federal Trade 
Commission, 31 states and the District of Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Mylan argued that the remedies sought exceeded those  
permitted by law and that the commission's authority to bring 
antitrust matters to court is limited. 
</P>
<P>
	Mylan and other defendants said monetary awards must come  
through criminal cases brought by the Justice Department, not civil 
cases filed by the FTC. 
</P>
<P>
	``Make no mistake about it, the commission's case is  
unprecedented and threatens to rewrite how the commission does its 
business,'' said Mylan attorney John K. Carroll. ``The commission's 
role is fundamentally a forward-looking role and not one to punish 
and fashion liability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Thomas F. Hogan said he would rule later. A  
trial, if any, is not expected until at least mid-2000 and may be 
consolidated with some of the roughly two dozen lawsuits filed by 
hospitals, insurers and other private parties. 
</P>
<P>
	Mylan is accused of cutting off competition through an exclusive  
deal with a key supplier. The government says prices of lorazepam 
and clorazepate rose by more than 25 times, almost single-handedly 
distorting a government measurement of wholesale inflation in May 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pittsburgh-based drug company has denied all charges. Also  
named as defendants are the supplier and its U.S. distributor. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC normally uses the courts for consumer fraud cases and  
handles antitrust matters internally using administrative judges. 
Officials have said the $120 million sought makes the lawsuit the 
largest antitrust case brought by the commission. 
</P>
<P>
	But commission attorney Melvin H. Orlans said no law prevents  
the commission from bringing a case as long as it is not a 
technical one that would require the expertise of administrative 
judges. The Mylan case does not fall under that exemption, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mylan reached a deal in late 1997 to be the exclusive buyer of  
active ingredients made by Profarmaco S.R.L. of Milan, Italy. Other 
makers of those ingredients cannot supply adequate quantities to 
Mylan's competitors, essentially shutting them out, the government 
argues. 
</P>
<P>
	Mylan has said the exclusive deal was designed to guarantee an  
uninterrupted source of ingredients and the generic drugs still 
cost much less than brand-name versions. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission seeks at least $120 million for refunds to  
consumers. The states' lawsuit does not specify a price tag but 
seeks refunds for their agencies' purchases and other direct and 
indirect damages, as well as a deterrent against future deals. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors each year issue more than 18 million prescriptions for  
lorazepam, a generic version of Ativan, for treating anxiety, 
tension, agitation and insomnia. More than 3 million prescriptions 
for clorazepate are issued a year. Clorazepate, the generic version 
of Tranxene, is used to treat anxiety and hypertension. 
</P>
<P>
	The states that filed the complaint are Alaska, Arkansas,  
California, Colorado, Connecticut, Florida, Idaho, Illinois, Iowa, 
Kentucky, Louisiana, Maine, Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri, New 
Mexico, New York, North Carolina, Ohio, Oklahoma, Oregon, 
Pennsylvania, South Carolina, South Dakota, Texas, Tennessee, Utah, 
Vermont, Washington, West Virginia and Wisconsin. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
