<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Committee To Receive Timber Papers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Resources Committee, after issuing a  
subpoena, will receive hundreds of additional government documents 
regarding a 1994 timber contract cancellation in Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department agreed to hand over the documents  
following a meeting Thursday between Attorney General Janet Reno 
and Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, the committee chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Committee officials agreed to keep the documents confidential  
and to consult with the Justice Department should the committee 
later wish to make them public. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a good sign that future negotiations with the  
Department of Justice will proceed more cooperatively,'' Young said 
in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Young has been sharply critical of the contract cancellation in  
the Tongass National Forest, which idled 1,000 timber and mill 
workers. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he wants to find out why the Agriculture Department took  
the action, whether it was legal, and if it was politically 
motivated. 
</P>
<P>
	Alaska Pulp Corp.'s 50-year contract, issued in 1957, was  
terminated after the Japanese-owned company closed its old pulp 
plant in Sitka, Alaska. The contract required that such a plant be 
in continuous operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Alaska Pulp sued the government for $1.6 billion in 1995,  
asserting that the contract cancellation amounted to a breach of 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Committee has already received tens of thousands of  
documents for an investigation it began more than a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	But Justice officials worried that disclosing another 67 paper  
documents and hundreds of computer files Young wanted -- some 
containing legal advice -- would hurt their defense against a 
lawsuit pending in the U.S. Court of Claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Young contended that the Clinton administration's concerns were  
just an excuse ``to hide embarrassing documents about bad decisions 
or possible violations of federal law.'' The committee voted April 
28 to order Justice officials to turn over the documents. 
</P>
<P>
	The subpoena drew protest from Democrats, who contended Young  
was misusing Congress' investigative powers to give Alaska Pulp an 
advantage in the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	But Young made it clear to Reno that he is interested in  
decisions about the contract cancellation, not the lawsuit, said 
Duane Gibson, a committee lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department spokeswoman Chris Watney said the agreement  
protects government legal interests and respects the committee's 
oversight role. ``We are pleased,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
