<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> For Charities, Use Heart Plus Head / On the Money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Americans are opening their hearts, and their  
wallets, to help victims of the fighting in Kosovo, the recent U.S. 
tornadoes, and the Colorado school shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	While consumer groups applaud such generosity, noting that  
solicitations have been increasing lately, they caution donors to 
be careful with their contributions and wary of scam artists who 
may try to profit from the suffering of others. 
</P>
<P>
	No major cases of fraud have been reported recently, according  
to several groups contacted, but some watchdog organizations are 
issuing precautionary notices warning of some of the tactics that 
may be used. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're never going to hear of them until the sheriff drags  
them out of town,'' said Daniel Langan, a spokesman for National 
Charities Information Bureau, based in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	When responding to an appeal, individuals should ask for as much  
detail as possible about what services a charity intends to 
provide, long-term or immediate, and how it intends to reach its 
goals. 
</P>
<P>
	Donors will also want to know how much of their contributions  
actually go to charitable purposes, vs. administrative costs. Most 
consumer groups recommend at least 60 cents out of each dollar 
spent be used for specific programs. 
</P>
<P>
	They suggest asking for a copy of a group's annual report and  
any other pertinent financial information. Even newly established 
organizations should have written material available describing 
their programs, anticipated expenditures, and how they will carry 
out activities. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internal Revenue Service and many states require most  
charities to file financial documents to maintain their tax-exempt 
status. 
</P>
<P>
	``When in doubt, check it out,'' said Bennett Weiner, vice  
president of the Council of Better Business Bureau's Philanthropic 
Advisory Service. He suggests individuals check with their local 
BBB or with their state attorney general. 
</P>
<P>
	The vast majority of charities are reputable. But occasionally  
individuals will come across a group that isn't. 
</P>
<P>
	Scams come in many forms. There are the bogus phone  
solicitations with the sole intent of gaining illegal access to an 
individual's credit card number, the offers to send a someone to a 
home to pick up a donation for a made-up charity, or the bogus 
door-to-door appeals looking for small change and bills. Often 
times, the culprits will use a name similar to that of an 
established charity. 
</P>
<P>
	``Subsequent to any disaster you will see rather questionable  
appeals emerge,'' said Weiner. ``One of the common ones is the use 
of excessive pressure and the need for immediate assistance over 
the telephone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ann Kaplan, editor of Giving U.S.A., a publication of the  
American Association of Fund-Raising Counsel, recommends 
individuals stick with well-known charities for now as they support 
the latest relief efforts in the Balkans and in areas hard hit by 
the recent tornadoes. 
</P>
<P>
	There are lists of charities in newspapers, she noted, and  
finding one to support is really a matter of personal preference. 
Individuals will want to align themselves with groups involved in 
causes or with philosophical beliefs with which they feel 
comfortable, Kaplan added. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCIB is one of several groups that evaluates charities which  
solicit from the general public, and it has comprised a list on its 
Web site (www.give.org/refugeerelief.cfm) of 13 charities actively 
involved in relief efforts in the Balkans that meet all its 
criteria for effective operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the others: The American Institute of Philanthropy in  
Bethesda, Md., (www.charitywatch.org) lists 15 Kosovo relief 
charities that received top ratings for assisting Kosovo refugees. 
The Council of Better Business Bureaus in Arlington, Va., 
(www.bbb.org) has reports on several charities reviewed by its 
Philanthropic Advisory Service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 15:41:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Probe Explores School Reading Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Maryland and Kentucky, which posted big gains in  
fourth-grade reading scores, would have shown no improvement if 
they had not excluded more special-education students from the 
national test, federal education researchers said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Three other states with the biggest improvements -- Connecticut,  
Louisiana and South Carolina -- would have shown more modest gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 reading scores of fourth-grade students -- the only  
grade level available for state-by-state comparison -- increased 
from 1994 scores in several states, including those that suffered 
political fallout over previous poor showings. 
</P>
<P>
	The report Friday, presented to the board that conducts the  
voluntary national tests, theoretically puts some states close to 
where they started. The states with the largest score gains -- 
Connecticut, Louisiana and South Carolina -- all would have had 
lower average scores had special-education students been included. 
Kentucky and Maryland's scores would have remained steady. 
Minnesota's scores improved under the model because it excluded 
fewer special-ed students. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 18 of the 36 participating states left out more special  
education students from the 1998 testing sample than from the 1994 
group. Of those states, 15 posted gains in the average score. But 
just five states showed changes significant enough to concern 
reviewers. 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky pulled out 10 percent of students selected for its 1998  
sample, compared with 4 percent in 1994. It improved its average 
reading scores by 6 points, on a 500-point scale. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland pulled 9 percent of students in 1998 compared with 7  
percent of sample students in 1994. Its average score improved by 5 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	And Connecticut, the nation's highest-scoring state, removed 10  
percent of the students selected to participate, compared with 6 
percent in 1994. Its average score improved by 10 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Louisiana pulled 13 percent in 1998, up from 6 percent in 1994.  
Its average improved by 7 points. 
</P>
<P>
	South Carolina in 1998 excluded 12 percent of its sample and 7  
percent in 1994. The state reported a 7 point rise in its average 
score. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials cautioned that the report was based on a model  
analysis of how excluded students would have performed. Changes are 
stated in terms of less or more ``statistical significance,'' 
rather than specific percentage points, and therefore can't be used 
to adjust state scores or rankings. 
</P>
<P>
	``The results are what they are,'' said Pascal D. Forgione Jr.,  
chief of the Education Department's statistical branch, told the 
board, which met at the Loews Hotel here to examine the tests it 
gives. ``We need to do more analysis before any conclusions can be 
drawn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the model used the most conservative estimate of how  
special-needs kids would have done, ``short of giving them all 
zeros.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Wilmer Cody, chief of Kentucky's Education Department and  
test board member, challenged the report, saying many special-needs 
children are in mainstream classrooms and might not necessarily do 
much worse on the tests. 
</P>
<P>
	``Trying to analyze this by generalizing is going to leave us  
without understanding what is taking place,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Because many states used the gains to tout success of their  
reforms, the validity and integrity of the national voluntary test 
has been scrutinized more closely. 
</P>
<P>
	The board said it would seek specific data on the excluded  
students, but did not say how it would factor that information into 
the current test score averages. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will be working ... to ensure that we don't have an  
exclusion rate that would cloud results in the future,'' Louisiana 
schools chief Cecil Picard said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Until 1998, many special-needs students took the national test.  
Then federal law required that special-needs students get special 
help on any test comparing their results with others. The testing 
board responded by having states exclude those students from the 
national sample. 
</P>
<P>
	The test, called the National Assessment of Educational  
Progress, and its board were established by Congress. The test is 
given roughly every two years to a nationwide sample of children in 
three grade levels in core subjects like math and reading. The 
voluntary test is generally the only way to compare student 
progress nationwide, because states' tests vary. 
</P>
<P>
	A congressional hearing on the tests is scheduled for May 27.  
</P>
</TEXT>
