<DOCNO> APW19990514.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 01:22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Skins' Westbrook Talking to Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- Michael Westbrook is talking to reporters  
again. That doesn't mean he likes what they do. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't trust the media,'' the Washington Redskins receiver  
said Thursday. ``A group of people making their living off the 
unhappiness of other people. It just saddens me that a lot of you 
all live like that. It makes you happy to get a good article on 
making somebody else sad. I just don't find that humane.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Westbrook was giving his first full news conference since his  
bloody attack on teammate Stephen Davis 19 months ago. As he has 
been throughout his whole career, Westbrook was full of 
contradictions that made him as difficult to read as ever. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke of being more mature, then called a local writer a  
``nerd'' for writing negative columns. He compared his attack on 
Davis to a ``hockey fight'' and said he didn't need counseling for 
it, but wouldn't explain how it happened. 
</P>
<P>
	He also blamed injuries, the quarterbacks, the offensive line --  
everything except his only ability -- for his disappointing four 
seasons in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anybody can check me. Can I get open? What kind  
of question is that?'' he said. ``The offensive line hasn't been 
healthy. I haven't been healthy. The quarterbacks didn't know if 
they wanted to play quarterback or not. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that I've done the best that I can do on the field  
when the opportunity has presented itself. ... If I can just play 
16 games. Judge me on 16 games, 16 healthy games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since he was selected No. 4 overall in the 1995 draft, Westbrook  
has been suspended twice, fined twice and benched three times for 
various infractions on and off the field. He has missed 16 games 
due to injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The most infamous moment came when he started punching Davis on  
the sideline during a practice on Aug. 19, 1997. The Redskins fined 
Westbrook $50,000, suspended him for one exhibition game, told him 
to apologize and ordered him to undergo counseling. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hockey players have fights every day, all day,'' Westbrook  
said. ``What did I need counseling for? Because I had a fight? 
</P>
<P>
	``It was more so to please the public. I don't think anything  
was mentally wrong with me, and I'm the still the great friend to 
my friends and great family member to my family members and a 
respectable human being to people that just walk past me every 
day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Westbrook said he stopped talking to reporters because he felt  
the matter was blown out of proportion. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fight itself shouldn't have happened,'' he said. ``After  
it happened, I don't think the media should have ran with it the 
way it did. It sold papers, but it made my fans and family 
miserable, and I thought that was a bigger price to pay than the 
$50,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Westbrook would not say what provoked him to hit Davis, who  
threw no punches but took several and was left face down with a 
bloody nose. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's strictly between me and Stephen,'' Westbrook said. ``We  
had a fight, and it was for a reason. I apologized to him. We sat 
down and talked since, and we're really good friends now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Westbrook was enjoying his best season -- 44 catches,  
736 yards -- before suffering a neck injury Dec. 6 against San 
Diego. He had surgery in January and is expected to recover fully. 
</P>
<P>
	The 26-year-old receiver said he decided to open up partly  
because he's now the senior member of the receiving corps and wants 
to set an example for the younger players. Other than an appearance 
on teammate Brian Mitchell's talk show on WTEM-AM last season and 
an interview on WJLA-TV earlier this week, he had stayed virtually 
silent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just tired of playing the little childish games that you  
all have been playing with me and I've been playing with you,'' 
Westbrook said. ``It's time for all of us to grow up. It's time to 
be more mature.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
