<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crashes Or No, Tour Buses Still Hot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRANSON, Mo. (AP) -- When Bill Rodgers heard the awful news, that  
22 people had died in a tour-bus crash in New Orleans, he said a 
``little prayer for God's guidance,'' then climbed back on his bus 
to Branson. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't help but give it some consideration because we come  
to Branson twice a year on the bus,'' the 87-year-old retired 
policeman from Fort Smith, Ark., said Thursday as he waited for his 
wife to pick up a few munchies at the Mountain Man Nut and Fruit 
Company for the ride back home. 
</P>
<P>
	He and 41 other riders, mostly old friends and acquaintances,  
had been on the road when they learned of the Mother's Day crash in 
New Orleans. Most of them had been so busy shopping and taking in 
as many as three shows a day that they hadn't heard there had been 
another crash on Wednesday, this one injuring 15 people near 
California's Yosemite National Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I don't think it's something that will keep us from  
coming,'' Rodgers said of the two accidents. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something that's certainly regrettable,'' he continued,  
``And we all realize it's something that could happen every trip.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But then he smiled and added: ``We just say a little prayer for  
God's guidance and get on the bus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While people's fear of flying inevitably rises after a plane  
crash, bus crashes don't appear to have the same effect. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think just in terms of people's imagery about the situation,  
it is much more terrifying to think about falling out of the sky,'' 
said Linda Welsh, a psychologist and director of the Agoraphobia 
and Anxiety Treatment Center in Bala Cynwyd, Pa., near 
Philadelphia. ``With a plane crash, they imagine a total loss of 
life ... where with a bus accident there's a sense that people do 
survive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bus accidents were terrible tragedies, riders said this  
week. And, yes, tragedy could strike anyone any time; even on a 
beautiful, sun-splashed day in Branson. But, they added, if you 
stayed home every time a bus veered off a highway, a plane crashed 
or a train jumped the tracks, you'd never go anywhere. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of us are widows, and for us it's the only way to go. Or  
else we just don't go,'' said Juanita Puckett as she waited for her 
bus by Branson's Star Walk of Fame, where hand prints of local 
entertainers like Jim Stafford, Tony Orlando and Barbara Fairchild 
are encased in cement. 
</P>
<P>
	And it wasn't just Midwesterners who seemed fearless. Anecdotal  
reports from the Gulf Coast and Atlantic City, N.J., indicated that 
there was no drop in bus ridership at other resorts cities. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, a spokeswoman for Houston-based Coach USA, which  
provides motorcoach charter, tour and sightseeing services, said 
she hadn't heard of any cancellations this week because of the 
crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Margie Garner admitted she couldn't help but think about  
the New Orleans disaster this week when the accelerator on her bus 
gave out and it rolled to a stop near a steep ravine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did think about it when I looked down into that ravine and  
realized how high up we were and thought what it would be like if 
our bus went off the road,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But,'' she quickly added, ``it's safer than driving our car.''  
</P>
<P>
	Federal statistics would seem to back her up. They show that an  
average of six people die in motorcoach crashes in a given year, 
while 22,000 died in car crashes in 1997. That same year, 49 people 
died in accidents involving U.S. commercial airlines. In addition, 
there were 40 air taxi fatalities, and 646 died in private planes. 
</P>
<P>
	Welsh said buses are less scary to anxious passengers because  
one can always get off, while there is no exit from a plane once 
the door is closed. ``It comes down to a control issue,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	And taking the bus is more than just a way to get there for Mrs.  
Garner, 67, and her 70-year-old husband, James. 
</P>
<P>
	Like many of the 6.7 million tourists who came to Branson last  
year, the Garners are retired, and traveling to places in big, 
comfortable, high-rise buses staffed with social directors is a way 
of life for them and their friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 10,000 buses dropped tourists off here last year, said  
Branson spokesman Jerry Adams, helping give this mountaintop city 
famous for its dozens of music theaters the ranking as one of 
America's top motorcoach destinations, according to the National 
Tour Association. 
</P>
<P>
	And this week in Branson was no different from any other in  
mid-May, according to Ed Michel, president of Ozark Mountain 
Sightseeing, one of the area's largest operators. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point we've had no statements from anybody, no  
comments, no calls, nobody even getting on the bus talking about 
it,'' he said of the crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	With the beginning of Branson's peak season still two weeks  
away, he estimated there were 60 tour buses arriving in town on 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, they appeared to be everywhere. Five were parked behind  
Yakov Smirnoff's theater for an afternoon show. Three more were up 
the street at Mickey Gilley's, with two more parked across the 
street in front of the Osmond Family Theatre. All the while, a 
constant parade of them moved up and down the street. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990514.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 15:48:08 </DATE_TIME>
