<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Global Crossing May Buy U S West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Baby Bell phone company U S West Inc. is  
close to an agreement to merge with Global Crossing Ltd., a 
telecommunications upstart that's on an acquisition streak, 
according to people familiar with the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, being structured as a stock swap, would create a  
company with $17 billion in annual sales and a stock market value 
of $65 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West, based in Denver, brings to the table local phone  
customers in 14 western and midwestern states, a wireless phone 
service, and a high-speed Internet access business. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing, headquartered in Bermuda, brings a local and  
long-distance phone business and a vast undersea fiber optic cable 
network. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's some real value to both sides,'' said Rex Mitchell, an  
industry analyst for NationsBanc Montgomery Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger, which could be announced as soon as Monday, would be  
set up as union of equals, with each company owning a 50 percent 
interest, according to a person familiar with the details. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company, which would keep the Global Crossing name,  
would have two separate stocks: one to track the performance of the 
high-growth Internet and data assets, the other stock for the 
traditional telephone assets. Investors will be able to choose 
which stock they want to hold. 
</P>
<P>
	This would be Global Crossing's third deal in as many months. In  
April, it agreed to pay $885 million for the undersea cable 
operations of the British telecommunications company Cable &AMP; 
Wireless. In March, Global Crossing signed an contract to acquire 
Frontier Corp., a phone company based in Rochester, N.Y., for about 
$11 billion in stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing was started two years ago by Gary Winnick, a Los  
Angeles financier who once worked with junk bond purveyor Michael 
Milken and now serves as co-chairman. Global Crossing, which went 
public last August, has seen its stock price increase five-fold to 
over $60 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The man behind the buying spree is Robert Annuziata, Global  
Crossing's chief executive officer, who is trying to build a 
communications empire to rival the one he left: AT&AMP;T Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Annuziata, however, would share the power and the top title of  
the new company with Solomon Trujillo, chief executive of U S West, 
a source said. 
</P>
<P>
	Their merger plans still face several challenges.  
</P>
<P>
	U S West, a product of the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T, is prohibited  
from offering long-distance service in its local phone territory 
until it gives up its monopoly in that area. 
</P>
<P>
	Any deal also may require the support of Frontier shareholders,  
who could pose obstacles. Global Crossing is issuing new shares of 
stock to buy Frontier. If it issues still more shares to merge with 
U S West, the value the shares being given to Frontier investors 
will be diluted. 
</P>
<P>
	However, as a long distance provider, Frontier also stands to  
gain from a link-up with U S West because the combination should 
ultimately be able to offer customers local, long-distance and 
wireless phone services. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the challenges, Annuziata is expected to push hard to  
get U S West. The company is the nation's largest provider of 
high-speed Internet access over digital subscriber lines, known as 
DSL, a fledgling service that works over regular telephone wires. 
There were about 50,000 DSL subscribers in the country last year, 
and about 60 percent of those were U S West customers. 
</P>
<P>
	DSL is considered the most worthy rival to the cable television  
wires that AT&AMP;T is using to build a multimedia network for TV, 
phone and Internet service. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, AT&AMP;T agreed to pay $58 billion to acquire MediaOne  
Group, the nation's fourth largest cable company and formerly a 
sister company of U S West. That deal included an alliance with 
Comcast, the No. 3 cable company. Along with AT&AMP;T's pending 
alliance with Time Warner and its recent purchase of 
Tele-Communications Inc., AT&AMP;T will have access to the four largest 
cable systems in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see a polarization in the industry,'' said Christine  
Heckart, vice president at TeleChoice Inc., a consulting company. 
``At one end will be the global super-carriers. ... At the other 
end will be a highly fragmented community of niche players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U S West declined to comment. Calls to Global Crossing were not  
returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors, responded quickly to the news, bidding up the price  
of U S West shares by $2.25 to $62.25 amid a broad selloff on the 
New York Stock Exchange. Global Crossing's Nasdaq-listed stock was 
off 62 1/2 cents at $59.37 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *AP Business Writer Bruce Meyerson contributed to this report.    	

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
