<DOCNO> APW19990514.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-14 16:23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Issue Tricky for GOP Candidates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The abrupt shift on gun control by  
congressional Republicans underscores the difficulty facing GOP 
presidential candidates tackling the tricky issue in the wake of 
the Colorado school shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Rifle Association, an old GOP ally, appeared to win  
a major victory Wednesday when the Senate rejected a Democratic 
measure requiring background checks of firearms sales at gun shows. 
The Senate passed a measure by Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, to make 
the checks voluntary. 
</P>
<P>
	Party leaders retreated under pressure Thursday from  
rank-and-file Republicans, including presidential candidate John 
McCain of Arizona. He and several other senators said they were 
unhappy with Wednesday's vote, even though they had voted in favor 
of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a realization that there was a loophole that had to  
be closed,'' McCain said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate voted 48-47 Friday to approve a measure establishing  
a system of background checks for all buyers of firearms at gun 
shows, overriding criticism from Democrats and the White House that 
new loopholes will give criminals access to firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not an overly burdensome requirement in the face of  
the tragic shootings at Columbine,'' McCain said after the vote 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The congressional change-of-course reflects a growing sentiment  
in Washington that voters want new limits on guns. Several party 
officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said private polling 
conducted after last month's shooting at Columbine High School in 
Colorado reveals strong support for gun control, even among 
Republican primary voters. 
</P>
<P>
	That is a marked shift from the past.  
</P>
<P>
	Some of that polling has been conducted for Elizabeth Dole, the  
former American Red Cross leader who ranks second in most GOP 
presidential polls. In a series of high-profile announcements, Mrs. 
Dole opposed concealed-weapons laws and supported bans on assault 
weapons and armor-piercing bullets. 
</P>
<P>
	Her advisers are betting that the issue will help her build a  
base of female voters and pull moderate Democrats into GOP 
primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	An added bonus: The against-the-grain stances drew attention to  
her candidacy just as her campaign appeared stalled, aides say 
</P>
<P>
	``The time has come for Democrats and Republicans to put  
consensus before confrontation so we can get tough on crime,'' Mrs. 
Dole said Friday during a campaign swing through Iowa. That means 
``instant background checks should be required wherever guns are 
commercially sold,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to help the police fight crime,'' she said. ``I do not  
see a reason for a family to have an assault weapon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The early GOP favorite, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, is harder to  
pin down. 
</P>
<P>
	He expressed support for background checks in Texas, but did so  
only after a bill to that effect died in the state legislature. The 
governor later explained that he never endorsed the bill, which he 
said had many flaws, and urged Congress to address the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman said Thursday that Bush would not have supported the  
Democratic gun show measure defeated in the Senate. Bush believes 
the bill would have imposed too many regulations and given too much 
power to the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, spokesman 
David Beckwith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush favored the Craig proposal, though he would prefer the  
checks be mandatory, Beckwith said. Hours later, the GOP-led Senate 
reversed course and seemed to adopt Bush's position. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it should be required that any vendor ... should have  
access to (the federal database) and required to use it,'' Beckwith 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamar Alexander, competing with Bush and Dole for moderate GOP  
voters, said shortly after the Colorado shooting that future 
massacres ``will not be stopped by more laws coming out of 
Washington.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a subtle shift, the former Tennessee governor took no  
position on the bill Thursday but spokesman Steve Schmidt said, 
``Federal gun control legislation is something that Gov. Alexander 
is not opposed to, to keep guns out of the hands of people who 
shouldn't have them: Criminals, the insane and children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conservative businessman Steve Forbes said he would have  
supported Craig's measure, but called it a ``quick fix'' and said 
the solution to mounting violence is ``reshaping our culture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the rest of the GOP candidates oppose any new  
restrictions on guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Vice President Dan Quayle and conservative activist Gary  
Bauer said they support voluntary, not mandatory, background checks 
at gun shows. Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire opposed even the 
Craig measure, and was among a small group of Republican senators 
who voted against an attempt to stiffen it on the floor on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
