<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Party Must Choose Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- For 70 years, Mexico's ruling party had  
little difficulty in choosing a presidential candidate. The 
president picked someone, the party rubber-stamped the choice and 
the nominee always won, usually by a landslide. 
</P>
<P>
	But electoral victories are no longer guaranteed, and President  
Ernesto Zedillo has repeatedly said he won't designate a candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the leadership of the Institutional Revolutionary  
Party will announce how the party, known as the PRI, will choose 
its nominee for the July 2000 elections. That could be a pivotal 
moment in determining the party's candidate -- and maybe the next 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rules of the game are going to clearly indicate who has  
the advantage in the game,'' said independent Sen. Adolfo Aguilar 
Zinser. 
</P>
<P>
	Party president Jose Antonio Gonzalez Fernandez has said the PRI  
is committed to a democratic, grassroots selection process. 
</P>
<P>
	But some believe the rules -- including who can vote and how  
campaigns can be conducted -- could be rigged to benefit Zedillo's 
favorites and prevent old-style populist politicians, such as 
Tabasco Gov. Roberto Madrazo, from getting the nomination. Madrazo 
has been aggressively campaigning and doing well in opinion polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Zedillo, who is prohibited by law from running for re-election,  
is seen as favoring a candidate likely to continue his fiscally 
conservative economic policies -- most likely Interior Secretary 
Francisco Labastida. 
</P>
<P>
	If the rules are seen as biased toward Zedillo's candidate, that  
could worsen divisions within the party, undermining its chances of 
beating back what could be its strongest opposition challenge ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The potential candidate who may be the best hope for unifying  
the party is Veracruz Gov. Miguel Aleman, the son of a former 
president. Aleman has said he wants to see what the party announces 
Monday before deciding whether to run. 
</P>
<P>
	Few expect Zedillo to stay out of the selection process  
entirely. He was seen as pulling strings to assure the selection of 
Gonzalez Fernandez, his former labor secretary, as head of the 
party, a position that will have great influence in the selection 
of the PRI candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	He has also said that not naming the candidate doesn't mean  
staying out of the process. 
</P>
<P>
	At a ceremony in March, he said, ``I have the full right and all  
the moral and political authority to give my opinion about the 
characteristics of the process in which our party will select our 
candidate.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
