<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Promises To Protect Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MACAU (AP) -- China is committed to curbing deflation, but that  
will not come at the expense of a stable currency, China's central 
bank chief said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have solid ground to safeguard the stability'' of the  
Chinese yuan, Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of 
China, told a banking conference in Macau. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that China had $146.7 billion in foreign exchange  
reserves and has only a small amount of short-term foreign debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The yuan, fixed at 8.28 to the dollar, has been stable for two  
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail prices in China are falling fast as the economy slows  
down from the double-digit growth of a few years ago. The retail 
price index -- China's benchmark for inflation -- was down 3.5 
percent in April compared with the same month a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank tried to pump more money into the economy by  
cutting interest rates three times in 1998. It also cut the reserve 
ratio -- the percentage of deposits banks are required to hold in 
cash -- to 8 percent from 13 percent, Dai noted. 
</P>
<P>
	Dai gave no indication when or if the central bank would ease  
rates this year. 
</P>
<P>
	He indicated that China continued to seek to open its economy,  
saying: ``We will continue our opening up policy and won't change 
our basic policy to open to the outside world.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
