<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blazers Await Jazz or Kings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Portland Trail Blazers have a few days  
to rest -- and to keep tabs on the Sacramento-Utah series. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been a remarkable week for the Blazers, who went from  
underachievers to undefeated in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last Friday, the Blazers were in a sour mood after losing  
four of their last five regular-season games, including a 
momentum-crushing 28-point blowout against the Los Angeles Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days later, on the eve of Game 1 of their first-round series  
against Phoenix, the Blazers impatiently answered questions about 
whether they could regain their stride against the surging Suns. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers emphatically erased those doubts with a 3-0 sweep,  
completed with Wednesday night's 103-93 comeback victory in 
Phoenix. Portland ended a six-year string of first-round exits. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a really good feeling,'' said forward Brian Grant, who  
like other Blazers played in his first winning playoff series. 
``Walt Williams and I may have been jumping around extra hard on 
the sidelines because we were in Sacramento together. We've both 
been down some rough roads. Now, to make it to the second round -- 
we're not saying it's like a championship or anything, but it's 
just a big relief to make it to the second round.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grant recovered from a painful bone bruise in his left knee to  
have a terrific series: He averaged 19.3 points and 9.3 rebounds 
and made 71.9 percent of his shots. 
</P>
<P>
	After a physical, emotionally draining Game 3, the Blazers  
arrived back in Portland on Thursday and took the rest of the day 
off. They were scheduled to practice today, but a hot topic surely 
will be the stunning collapse of the Utah Jazz. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah's improbable 84-81 overtime loss in Sacramento on Wednesday  
night gave the Blazers hope for opening the second round at the 
Rose Garden. Should the Jazz lose the series, Portland would have 
homecourt advantage against the Kings, who were 0-4 against the 
Blazers this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Portland's Isaiah Rider was listed as day to day on Thursday  
after spraining his right knee in the third quarter Wednesday. 
Rider was said to be walking fine, however, and indicated he would 
be ready for the next round. 
</P>
<P>
	Rider was hurt when he dove for a loose ball and the Suns' Tom  
Gugliotta fell into his right knee. Rider came back and, although 
he contributed little on the court, urged his teammates on loudly 
and waved a towel from the sideline. After the game, he even 
compared himself to Willis Reed and his famed hobbling entrance for 
the New York Knicks in the 1970 finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers came very close to losing their cool several times  
during the game. 
</P>
<P>
	When Rider was fouled hard by Danny Manning late in the second  
quarter, he briefly confronted Manning, but then walked away. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, however, left the bench area to defend Rider, an act  
that usually carries an automatic one-game suspension. Williams was 
not suspended Thursday, and a league official said the incident was 
still being looked at. 
</P>
<P>
	Portland has gotten into trouble all season for outbursts and  
tantrums directed at officials, and Wednesday night was no 
different. Rasheed Wallace, whose protests have been characterized 
by wide-eyed, open-jawed looks and flailing arms, was particularly 
animated after one call. There also was a brief altercation behind 
the Blazers bench involving seldom-used and injured rookie guard 
Bonzi Wells and a Phoenix security guard. 
</P>
<P>
	``Guys have to understand that you can't react to everything  
that happens,'' point guard Damon Stoudamire told The Oregonian. 
``It just magnifies everything. It just makes it worse. Wherever we 
play in the second round, it's going to be the same thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, Portland's emotion and energy carried it through  
with a 24-10 run to end the game and the series. And that kind of 
intensity -- in measured doses -- will be needed if the Blazers are 
to advance to the Western Conference finals and beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't come here to get into the second round. I came here  
because I felt this team had the best opportunity to win a world 
championship,'' said Greg Anthony, who signed as a free agent 
following the lockout. ``So far, I feel real happy about my 
decision.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
